{"title_page": "Samuel Sinyangwe", "text_new": "{{short description|Data scientist and activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals       = \n| name               =  <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| post-nominals      = \n| image              =  SamuelSinyangwe.jpg\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = Sinyangwe stands in front of a painted wall\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  c. 1990\n| birth_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation         = Policy analyst, activist\n| years_active       = \n| era                = 21st century\n| employer           = \n| organization       = [[Campaign Zero]]\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      =  <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\"; or by |label_name=, which produces label \"Label(s)\" -->\n| style              = \n| home_town          = [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| title              =  <!-- Formal/awarded/job title. The parameter |office= may be used as an alternative when the label is better rendered as \"Office\" (e.g. public office or appointments) -->\n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| boards             =  \n| spouse             =  <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = \n| website            =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Sinyangwe''' (born c. 1990) is an American [[Policy analysis|policy analyst]] and [[Racial equality|racial justice]] [[Activism|activist]]. Sinyangwe is a member of the [[Movement for Black Lives]] and a co-founder of We the Protestors, a group of digital tools that include Mapping Police Violence, a database of police killings in the [[United States]], and [[Campaign Zero]], a policy platform to end police violence. Sinyangwe is a co-host the ''[[Pod Save the People]]'' podcast, where he discusses the week's news with a panel of other activists.\n\n== Early life ==\nSinyangwe was born circa 1990 to a Tanzanian father and a Jewish mother who met while studying at [[Cornell University]].<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/samswey/status/874390139883204608></ref><ref name=\":4\" /> He grew up in [[College Park (Orlando)|College Park]] neighborhood of [[Orlando, Florida]] and attended [[Winter Park High School]] in the [[International Baccalaureate]] program.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|last1=Cordeiro|first1=Monivette|title=How an Orlando data scientist is helping #BlackLivesMatter make the case against police violence|url=http://www.orlandoweekly.com/orlando/how-an-orlando-data-scientist-is-helping-the-blacklivesmatter-movement-make-the-case-against-police-violence/Content?oid=2478826|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=Orlando Weekly|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref> He has discussed the influence of his upbringing in Florida, where he was a black child often surrounded by white peers, on his eventual career trajectory; he was shaken and moved to action after the 2013 [[Trial of George Zimmerman|acquittal of George Zimmerman]] in the shooting death of [[Shooting of Trayvon Martin|Trayvon Martin]] in [[Sanford, Florida]], where Sinyangwe had regularly attended soccer practice: \"I was that kid. I could have been Trayvon. That\u2019s why it hit me so personally and that\u2019s why I realized that needed to be something that took the priority in terms of my focus.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nSinyangwe graduated from [[Stanford University]], where he studied how race intersects with American politics, economics, and class.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Marusic|first1=Kristina|title=This Map Of Police Violence Aims To Create A Path To Justice|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2133351/map-police-violence/|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=MTV News|date=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSinyangwe started his career at PolicyLink with the Promise Neighborhoods Institute.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dHxqDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT476&ots=ftZuIq_nxZ&dq=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22&lr&pg=PT486#v=onepage&q=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22&f=false|title=The Routledge Handbook of Developments in Digital Journalism Studies|last=Richardson|first=Allissa V.|date=2018-09-05|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781351982085|editor-last=Eldrige II|editor-first=Scott|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=28. The Movement and its Mobile Journalism: A phenomenology of Black Lives Matter journalist-activists|editor-last2=Franklin|editor-first2=Bob}}</ref> As protests emerged in the wake of the 2014 [[shooting of Michael Brown]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri]], he connected with Ferguson activists online, ultimately taking a leave of absence from his job to join them in Missouri.<ref name=\":5\" /> With [[DeRay Mckesson]] and [[Johnetta Elzie]], he began working to develop policy solutions to address police violence in America.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sinyangwe particularly noticed the absence of official government statistics on police violence and began compiling them from other sources like Fatal Encounters and KilledbythePolice.net, in order to challenge claims about police shootings being rare events or only resulting from resisting arrest.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWith other activists, Sinyangwe founded We the Protestors, an organization aimed at developing a set of digital tools to support [[Black Lives Matter]] activism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3064214/meet-the-startup-building-the-digital-civil-rights-movement|title=Meet The Startup Building The Digital Civil Rights Movement|last=Peters|first=Adele|date=2016-10-03|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> We the Protestors projects include a database of police killings, Mapping Police Violence,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hellman|first1=Jaime|title=No clear picture on how many people are killed by police|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/watch/shows/Ali-Velshi-On-Target/articles/2015/5/28/No-data-on-how-many-killed-by-police-in-America.html|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=Al Jazeera America|date=May 28, 2015}}</ref> and a platform of policy solutions to end police violence called [[Campaign Zero]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://splinternews.com/the-latest-numbers-on-police-killings-show-the-problem-1793853657|title=The latest numbers on police killings show the problem may be worse than we thought|last=Meyerson|first=Collier|work=Splinter|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/05/20/activist-samuel-sinyangwe-louisiana-mass-incarceration|title=Activist Samuel Sinyangwe Sheds Light On Louisiana\u2019s Horrible Mass Incarceration Problem|last=Lawler|first=Opheli Garcia|date=May 20, 2017|work=The Fader|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref> Sinyangwe also serves as a data scientist for OurStates.org, a project focused on state legislatures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/981351/black-lives-matter-activists-turn-attention-to-statehouses.html|title=Black Lives Matter activists turn attention to statehouses|last=Whack|first=Errin Haines|date=April 3, 2017|website=Albuquerque Journal|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> and with Mckesson and [[Brittany Packnett|Brittney Packnett]] founded the [[Resistance Manual]], an open-source project aimed at connecting anti-racist activists with activists focused on intersecting issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/deray-launches-resistance-manual-an-open-source-site-designed-to-take-on-trump/|title=DeRay and Stay Woke Activists Launch Resistance Manual, an Open-Source Site Designed To Take on Trump|last=Ellefson|first=Lindsey|date=January 17, 2017|website=Mediaite|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 U.S. Presidential campaign]], Sinyangwe and colleagues met with Democratic candidates [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liebelson|first1=Dana|last2=Reilly|first2=Ryan J.|title=Black Lives Matter Activists Meet With Bernie Sanders To Make Sure He's On Board|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-black-lives-matter_us_55f9ca9ce4b00310edf57b02|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=The Huffington Post|date=16 September 2015}}</ref> and [[Hillary Clinton]] on these policy issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liebelson|first1=Dana|last2=Reilly|first2=Ryan J.|title=Inside Hillary Clinton's Meeting With Black Lives Matter|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-lives-matter-hillary-clinton_us_56180c44e4b0e66ad4c7d9fa|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=The Huffington Post|date=9 October 2015}}</ref> He has been a vocal critic of the \"[[Ferguson effect|Ferguson Effect]]\", using data to refute the theory that policing had diminished and crime increased in face of activist scrutiny of police use of force.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5nxqDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA121&ots=9KiW8OUcM_&dq=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22%20%22ferguson%20effect%22&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22%20%22ferguson%20effect%22&f=false|title=Black Lives Matter: From a Moment to a Movement|last=Hillstrom|first=Laurie Collier|date=2018-09-07|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=|isbn=9781440865718|location=|pages=120\u2013121|language=en}}</ref> [[Melissa Harris-Perry]] has compared Sinyangwe to journalist and anti-[[Lynching in the United States|lynching]] activist [[Ida B. Wells]], noting that Wells began her work by \"compil[ing] the data, the social science and research about how, when and where lynchings were happening to begin to make it stop.\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nSinyangwe is a co-host of Mckesson's podcast ''[[Pod Save the People]]'', which discusses the week's news with a panel of other activists including Mckesson, Packnett and [[Clint Smith (writer)|Clint Smith]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/careers/getting-started/2018/09/11/activist-deray-mckesson-offers-insight-protests-civil-rights-blacks/1258521002/|title=How I became a civil rights activist: DeRay McKesson talks protesting, pursuing justice|last=Hutcheson|first=Susannah|date=September 11, 2018|work=USA Today|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref> The podcast particularly focuses on race, grassroots activism, discrimination and other forms of inequality;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2018/07/26/5-political-podcasts-help-cope-worlds-current-chaos/|title=5 political podcasts to help you cope with the world's current chaos|last=Fadrilan|first=Katrina|date=2018-07-26|work=The Daily Californian|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en-US}}</ref> recommending ''Pod Save The People'' in ''[[GQ]]'', June Diane Raphael of ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]'' wrote, \"The stories they uplift and think critically about are the ones I'm now wondering why I've never been exposed to/exposed myself to.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/best-podcasts-recommendations|title=21 Fresh Podcast Recommendations from All Your Favorite Podcasters|last=Peele|first=Anna|date=2018-07-31|work=GQ|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref> Sinyangwe has also been featured on [[CNN]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/tv/2015/04/15/ctn-sam-singyangwe-police-violence-reports.cnn|title=Researcher: 'Police shootings are on the rise'|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2015|website=|publisher=CNN|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> [[MSNBC]],<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/57833246/ns/msnbc/|title='The Melissa Harris-Perry Show' for Sunday, September 6th, 2015|last=|first=|date=September 6, 2015|website=The Melissa Harris-Perry Show|publisher=MSNBC|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> [[BBC News]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-32740523|title=Why do US police keep killing unarmed black men?|last=|first=|date=May 26, 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> [[FiveThirtyEight]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/blacks-are-killed-at-a-higher-rate-in-south-carolina-and-the-u-s/|title=Blacks Are Killed By Police At A Higher Rate In South Carolina And The U.S.|last=Fischer-Baum|first=Reuben|date=2015-04-08|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Los Angeles Times|''The Los Angeles Times'']],<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-police-campaign-zero-20150821-story.html|title=Activists come up with a plan to end police killings. Here it is.|last1=Pearce|first1=Matt|date=August 21, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> and other publications. He has written for the [[The Huffington Post|''Huffington Post'']] and ''The Guardian''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/13/ferguson-effect-james-comey-fbi-policing|title=Giving the 'Ferguson effect' a new name won't make it truer|last=Sinyangwe|first=Samuel|date=May 13, 2016|website=The Guardian|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and fellowships==\nIn 2017, Sinyangwe was named to the [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]] list for law and policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2017/law-policy/#1148b8761f69|title=30 Under 30 2017: Law & Policy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> He was also a 2017 [[Echoing Green]] Black Male Achievement Fellow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/samuel-sinyangwe|title=Samuel Sinyangwe|last=|first=|date=|website=www.echoinggreen.org|publisher=Echoing Green|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSinyangwe lives in New York City.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbcblk28-2017/nbcblk28-samuel-sinyangwe-number-cruncher-fight-against-systemic-racism-n714771|title=#NBCBLK28: Samuel Sinyangwe: Number cruncher in the fight against systemic racism|last=Simon|first=Mashaun D.|date=February 8, 2017|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected writings==\n\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/samuel-sinyangwe/stop-pretending-the-ferguson-effect-is-real_b_8403786.html|title=Stop Pretending the 'Ferguson Effect' is Real|date=May 13, 2016|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2 December 2016}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/13/ferguson-effect-james-comey-fbi-policing|work=The Guardian|title=Giving the 'Ferguson effect' a new name won't make it truer|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=2 December 2016}}\n*[http://useofforceproject.org/s/Use-of-Force-Study.pdf \"Examining the Role of Use of Force Policies in Ending Police Violence\"], Police Use of Force Project, September 20, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinyangwe, Samuel}}\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Data scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:1990s births]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:African-American activists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Tanzanian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Data scientist and activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals       = \n| name               =  <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| post-nominals      = \n| image              =  SamuelSinyangwe.jpg\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = Sinyangwe stands in front of a painted wall\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  c. 1990\n| birth_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation         = Policy analyst, activist\n| years_active       = \n| era                = 21st century\n| employer           = \n| organization       = [[Campaign Zero]]\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      =  <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\"; or by |label_name=, which produces label \"Label(s)\" -->\n| style              = \n| home_town          = [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| title              =  <!-- Formal/awarded/job title. The parameter |office= may be used as an alternative when the label is better rendered as \"Office\" (e.g. public office or appointments) -->\n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| boards             =  \n| spouse             =  <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = \n| website            =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Sinyangwe''' (born c. 1990) is an American [[Policy analysis|policy analyst]] and [[Racial equality|racial justice]] [[Activism|activist]]. Sinyangwe is a member of the [[Movement for Black Lives]] and a co-founder of We the Protestors, a group of digital tools that include Mapping Police Violence, a database of police killings in the [[United States]], and [[Campaign Zero]], a policy platform to end police violence. Sinyangwe is a co-host the ''[[Pod Save the People]]'' podcast, where he discusses the week's news with a panel of other activists.\n\n== Early life ==\nSinyangwe was born circa 1990 to a Tanzanian father and a Jewish mother who met while studying at [[Cornell University]].<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/samswey/status/874390139883204608></ref><ref name=\":4\" /> He grew up in [[College Park (Orlando)|College Park]] neighborhood of [[Orlando, Florida]] and attended [[Winter Park High School]] in the [[International Baccalaureate]] program.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|last1=Cordeiro|first1=Monivette|title=How an Orlando data scientist is helping #BlackLivesMatter make the case against police violence|url=http://www.orlandoweekly.com/orlando/how-an-orlando-data-scientist-is-helping-the-blacklivesmatter-movement-make-the-case-against-police-violence/Content?oid=2478826|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=Orlando Weekly|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref> He has discussed the influence of his upbringing in Florida, where he was a black child often surrounded by white peers, on his eventual career trajectory; he was shaken and moved to action after the 2013 [[Trial of George Zimmerman|acquittal of George Zimmerman]] in the shooting death of [[Shooting of Trayvon Martin|Trayvon Martin]] in [[Sanford, Florida]], where Sinyangwe had regularly attended soccer practice: \"I was that kid. I could have been Trayvon. That\u2019s why it hit me so personally and that\u2019s why I realized that needed to be something that took the priority in terms of my focus.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nSinyangwe graduated from [[Stanford University]], where he studied how race intersects with American politics, economics, and class.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Marusic|first1=Kristina|title=This Map Of Police Violence Aims To Create A Path To Justice|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2133351/map-police-violence/|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=MTV News|date=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSinyangwe started his career at PolicyLink with the Promise Neighborhoods Institute.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dHxqDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT476&ots=ftZuIq_nxZ&dq=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22&lr&pg=PT486#v=onepage&q=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22&f=false|title=The Routledge Handbook of Developments in Digital Journalism Studies|last=Richardson|first=Allissa V.|date=2018-09-05|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781351982085|editor-last=Eldrige II|editor-first=Scott|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=28. The Movement and its Mobile Journalism: A phenomenology of Black Lives Matter journalist-activists|editor-last2=Franklin|editor-first2=Bob}}</ref> As protests emerged in the wake of the 2014 [[shooting of Michael Brown]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri]], he connected with Ferguson activists online, ultimately taking a leave of absence from his job to join them in Missouri.<ref name=\":5\" /> With [[DeRay Mckesson]] and [[Johnetta Elzie]], he began working to develop policy solutions to address police violence in America.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sinyangwe particularly noticed the absence of official government statistics on police violence and began compiling them from other sources like Fatal Encounters and KilledbythePolice.net, in order to challenge claims about police shootings being rare events or only resulting from resisting arrest.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWith other activists, Sinyangwe founded We the Protestors, an organization aimed at developing a set of digital tools to support [[Black Lives Matter]] activism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3064214/meet-the-startup-building-the-digital-civil-rights-movement|title=Meet The Startup Building The Digital Civil Rights Movement|last=Peters|first=Adele|date=2016-10-03|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> We the Protestors projects include a database of police killings, Mapping Police Violence,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hellman|first1=Jaime|title=No clear picture on how many people are killed by police|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/watch/shows/Ali-Velshi-On-Target/articles/2015/5/28/No-data-on-how-many-killed-by-police-in-America.html|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=Al Jazeera America|date=May 28, 2015}}</ref> and a platform of policy solutions to end police violence called [[Campaign Zero]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://splinternews.com/the-latest-numbers-on-police-killings-show-the-problem-1793853657|title=The latest numbers on police killings show the problem may be worse than we thought|last=Meyerson|first=Collier|work=Splinter|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/05/20/activist-samuel-sinyangwe-louisiana-mass-incarceration|title=Activist Samuel Sinyangwe Sheds Light On Louisiana\u2019s Horrible Mass Incarceration Problem|last=Lawler|first=Opheli Garcia|date=May 20, 2017|work=The Fader|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref> Sinyangwe also serves as a data scientist for OurStates.org, a project focused on state legislatures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/981351/black-lives-matter-activists-turn-attention-to-statehouses.html|title=Black Lives Matter activists turn attention to statehouses|last=Whack|first=Errin Haines|date=April 3, 2017|website=Albuquerque Journal|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> and with Mckesson and [[Brittany Packnett|Brittney Packnett]] founded the [[Resistance Manual]], an open-source project aimed at connecting anti-racist activists with activists focused on intersecting issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/deray-launches-resistance-manual-an-open-source-site-designed-to-take-on-trump/|title=DeRay and Stay Woke Activists Launch Resistance Manual, an Open-Source Site Designed To Take on Trump|last=Ellefson|first=Lindsey|date=January 17, 2017|website=Mediaite|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 U.S. Presidential campaign]], Sinyangwe and colleagues met with Democratic candidates [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liebelson|first1=Dana|last2=Reilly|first2=Ryan J.|title=Black Lives Matter Activists Meet With Bernie Sanders To Make Sure He's On Board|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-black-lives-matter_us_55f9ca9ce4b00310edf57b02|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=The Huffington Post|date=16 September 2015}}</ref> and [[Hillary Clinton]] on these policy issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liebelson|first1=Dana|last2=Reilly|first2=Ryan J.|title=Inside Hillary Clinton's Meeting With Black Lives Matter|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-lives-matter-hillary-clinton_us_56180c44e4b0e66ad4c7d9fa|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=The Huffington Post|date=9 October 2015}}</ref> He has been a vocal critic of the \"[[Ferguson effect|Ferguson Effect]]\", using data to refute the theory that policing had diminished and crime increased in face of activist scrutiny of police use of force.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5nxqDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA121&ots=9KiW8OUcM_&dq=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22%20%22ferguson%20effect%22&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q=%22Samuel%20Sinyangwe%22%20%22ferguson%20effect%22&f=false|title=Black Lives Matter: From a Moment to a Movement|last=Hillstrom|first=Laurie Collier|date=2018-09-07|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=|isbn=9781440865718|location=|pages=120\u2013121|language=en}}</ref> [[Melissa Harris-Perry]] has compared Sinyangwe to journalist and anti-[[Lynching in the United States|lynching]] activist [[Ida B. Wells]], noting that Wells began her work by \"compil[ing] the data, the social science and research about how, when and where lynchings were happening to begin to make it stop.\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nSinyangwe is a co-host of Mckesson's podcast ''[[Pod Save the People]]'', which discusses the week's news with a panel of other activists including Mckesson, Packnett and [[Clint Smith (writer)|Clint Smith]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/careers/getting-started/2018/09/11/activist-deray-mckesson-offers-insight-protests-civil-rights-blacks/1258521002/|title=How I became a civil rights activist: DeRay McKesson talks protesting, pursuing justice|last=Hutcheson|first=Susannah|date=September 11, 2018|work=USA Today|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref> The podcast particularly focuses on race, grassroots activism, discrimination and other forms of inequality;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2018/07/26/5-political-podcasts-help-cope-worlds-current-chaos/|title=5 political podcasts to help you cope with the world's current chaos|last=Fadrilan|first=Katrina|date=2018-07-26|work=The Daily Californian|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en-US}}</ref> recommending ''Pod Save The People'' in ''[[GQ]]'', June Diane Raphael of ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]'' wrote, \"The stories they uplift and think critically about are the ones I'm now wondering why I've never been exposed to/exposed myself to.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/best-podcasts-recommendations|title=21 Fresh Podcast Recommendations from All Your Favorite Podcasters|last=Peele|first=Anna|date=2018-07-31|work=GQ|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref> Sinyangwe has also been featured on [[CNN]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/tv/2015/04/15/ctn-sam-singyangwe-police-violence-reports.cnn|title=Researcher: 'Police shootings are on the rise'|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2015|website=|publisher=CNN|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> [[MSNBC]],<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/57833246/ns/msnbc/|title='The Melissa Harris-Perry Show' for Sunday, September 6th, 2015|last=|first=|date=September 6, 2015|website=The Melissa Harris-Perry Show|publisher=MSNBC|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> [[BBC News]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-32740523|title=Why do US police keep killing unarmed black men?|last=|first=|date=May 26, 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> [[FiveThirtyEight]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/blacks-are-killed-at-a-higher-rate-in-south-carolina-and-the-u-s/|title=Blacks Are Killed By Police At A Higher Rate In South Carolina And The U.S.|last=Fischer-Baum|first=Reuben|date=2015-04-08|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Los Angeles Times|''The Los Angeles Times'']],<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-police-campaign-zero-20150821-story.html|title=Activists come up with a plan to end police killings. Here it is.|last1=Pearce|first1=Matt|date=August 21, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> and other publications. He has written for the [[The Huffington Post|''Huffington Post'']] and ''The Guardian''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/13/ferguson-effect-james-comey-fbi-policing|title=Giving the 'Ferguson effect' a new name won't make it truer|last=Sinyangwe|first=Samuel|date=May 13, 2016|website=The Guardian|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and fellowships==\nIn 2017, Sinyangwe was named to the [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]] list for law and policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2017/law-policy/#1148b8761f69|title=30 Under 30 2017: Law & Policy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> He was also a 2017 Echoing Green Black Male Achievement Fellow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/samuel-sinyangwe|title=Samuel Sinyangwe|last=|first=|date=|website=www.echoinggreen.org|publisher=Echoing Green|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSinyangwe lives in New York City.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbcblk28-2017/nbcblk28-samuel-sinyangwe-number-cruncher-fight-against-systemic-racism-n714771|title=#NBCBLK28: Samuel Sinyangwe: Number cruncher in the fight against systemic racism|last=Simon|first=Mashaun D.|date=February 8, 2017|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected writings==\n\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/samuel-sinyangwe/stop-pretending-the-ferguson-effect-is-real_b_8403786.html|title=Stop Pretending the 'Ferguson Effect' is Real|date=May 13, 2016|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2 December 2016}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/13/ferguson-effect-james-comey-fbi-policing|work=The Guardian|title=Giving the 'Ferguson effect' a new name won't make it truer|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=2 December 2016}}\n*[http://useofforceproject.org/s/Use-of-Force-Study.pdf \"Examining the Role of Use of Force Policies in Ending Police Violence\"], Police Use of Force Project, September 20, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinyangwe, Samuel}}\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Data scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:1990s births]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:African-American activists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Tanzanian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "RayScript", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and fellowships:echoing green link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Sinyangwe"}
{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 85", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=85\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=320|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 85}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 85 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=21.01\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">{{cite web |url=http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/routelog.htm?routekey=SR85%20NB |title=Massachusetts Route Log Application |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |website=[[MassDOT]] |publisher= |access-date=August 7, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n|length_round=4\n|established=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|MA|16}} in [[Milford, Massachusetts|Milford]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|495}} in Milford\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|135}} in [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts|Hopkinton]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|9|MA|30}} in [[Southborough, Massachusetts|Southborough]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|20}} in [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]]\n}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|MA|117}} in [[Bolton, Massachusetts|Bolton]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=84\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=86\n}}\n\n'''Route 85''' is a {{convert|21.01|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} north&ndash;south [[state highway]] in [[Massachusetts]], United States. It passes through the heart of [[Boston|Boston's]] [[MetroWest]] region, through towns on the eastern edge of [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]] and western edge of [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]], crossing the border between the two counties four times. Throughout its entire distance, Route 85 runs parallel to I-495, never passing more than two miles from it.\n\n==Route description==\nRoute 85 begins in the town of [[Milford, Massachusetts|Milford]] at [[Massachusetts Route 16|Route 16]], just west of the downtown area.  It passes east of Milford Pond before meeting [[Interstate 495 (Massachusetts)|I-495]] at Exit 20.  From there, Route 85 heads northward into [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts|Hopkinton]], passing the eastern side of Echo Lake.  It intersects [[Massachusetts Route 135|Route 135]] at the center of town, less than a quarter mile west of the start line of the [[Boston Marathon]].  It then passes through Hopkinton State Forest and past the Hopkinton Reservoir before entering the town of [[Southborough, Massachusetts|Southborough]].\n\n[[Image:MA Route 85 southbound, Hopkinton MA.jpg|thumb|left|200px|<center>Southbound in Hopkinton</center>]]\nIn Southborough, Route 85 crosses under [[Massachusetts Turnpike|I-90]] (the Mass Pike) without junction; the nearest exit is in neighboring [[Framingham, Massachusetts|Framingham]].  It then meets [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]], the second of the four major east-west routes out of Boston, in an elevated four-way cloverleaf intersection.  It then crosses the [[Sudbury Reservoir]] before meeting [[Massachusetts Route 30|Route 30]] at the center of town.  From there, Route 85 continues northward into [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]], meeting [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] in the downtown area. It then crosses the far western edge of the Fort Meadow Reservoir before crossing into [[Hudson, Massachusetts|Hudson]].  \n\nShortly after entering Hudson, Route 85 meets Hudson Street, the [[super two]] connector road between Route 85 and the junction of [[Interstate 290 (Massachusetts)|I-290]] and I-495 at I-495's Exit 25 and I-290's terminus, Exit 26.  From there Route 85 heads north, crossing the [[Assabet River]] before meeting [[Massachusetts Route 62|Route 62]], passing concurrently with that route through Wood Square before Route 85 continues northward.  After passing into [[Bolton, Massachusetts|Bolton]], the route passes between Little Pond and West Pond before ending at [[Massachusetts Route 117|Route 117]], less than a half mile east of I-495's exit 27.\n\n=== Route 85 Connector ===\nMA&nbsp;85 Connector is a road that goes from the eastern terminus of [[Interstate 290 (Massachusetts)|Interstate&nbsp;290]] (I-290) to a wye with MA&nbsp;85, {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=on}} away in [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]].<ref name=\"ma85connector\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/42.3637771,-71.5837487/42.3712321,-71.5691026/@42.3691474,-71.5811337,14.75z|title=Route 85 Connector|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n{{update|section|date=March 2018}}\n===Improvements to Route 85 in Hudson===\nIn 2011 a $10.8 million project to reconstruct 7,700 feet (1.5 miles) from School Street/Park Street to the Marlborough City Line will begin. The project will consist of {{convert|11|ft|m|adj=on}} travel lanes and {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} bike shoulders with {{convert|5.5|ft|m|adj=on}} concrete sidewalks throughout the project corridor. The Walmart Driveway will be reconstructed with bicycle accommodation, ADA compliance, and a new traffic signal. At the intersection of the Route 85 Connector and Technology Drive, the intersection will be reconstructed. A new northbound left turn lane will be constructed, new through lane constructed on Technology Drive, new through lane on Route 85 Connector and a new wire traffic signal. The section between Route 85 Connector and Broad Street will consist of four lanes (two in each direction) with a {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} raised concrete median. At the intersection of Broad Street, the existing signal will be replaced with a two-lane roundabout. The roadway will be widened to four lanes (two in each direction)from Houghton Street to Broad Street. A new traffic signal will be installed at R.K Town Centre Drive with a new turn lane. A new traffic signal will be installed at Giasson Street. A new northbound left turn lane with a new traffic signal will be installed at Brigham Street. From Brigham Street to Park Street, the roadway will be cold planed and resurfaced with drainage, curbing, sidewalks and driveways included. At Park Street/School Street, a new traffic signal will be installed and a new southbound right turn lane will be constructed.\n\n===Hudson Route 85 Bridge===\nBeginning in 2013, MassDOT will replace the existing structurally deficient arch bridge with a new bridge. The estimated cost is $7 million. The project is funded as part of the Accelerated Bridge Program and will use an innovative construction. The new bridge will consist of new concrete reinforced abutments and a new concrete NEXT beam superstructure.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=2\n|location=Milford\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|16|name1=Main Street|extra=hospital|city1=Uxbridge|city2=Webster|city3=Holliston|city4=Natick}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; serves [[Milford Regional Medical Center]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.3\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|495|city1=Cape Cod|city2=Lowell}}\n|notes=[[Diamond interchange]]; I-495 Exit 20\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|location=Hopkinton\n|mile=5.9\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|135|name1=Main Street|city1=Westboro|city2=Ashland}}\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=2\n|location=Southborough\n|lspan=2\n|mile=10.4\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|city1=Framingham|city2=Boston|city3=Worcester|city4=Amherst}}\n|notes=Cloverleaf interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.4\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|30|city1=Framingham|city2=Westboro}}\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|cspan=4\n|location=Marlborough\n|mile=14.5\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|to2=to|I|495|city1=Northboro|city2=Worcester|city3=Sudbury|city4=Waltham}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Hudson\n|lspan=3\n|mile=16.9\n|road={{jct|state=MA|to1=yes|I|290|I|495|dir1=west|city1=Worcester|location2=[[Norwich, Connecticut|Norwich, CT]]|city3=Lowell|city4=Cape Cod}}\n|notes=Access via {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=on}} Route 85 Connector<ref name=\"ma85connector\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/42.3637771,-71.5837487/42.3712321,-71.5691026/@42.3691474,-71.5811337,14.75z|title=Route 85 Connector|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=18.1\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|name1=Main Street east|road=Felton Street|city1=Stow|city2=Maynard}}\n|notes=Rotary; south end of concurrency with Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=18.105\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=west|name1=Central Street|to2=to|I|495|city1=Berlin|city2=Clinton}}\n|notes=North end of concurrency with Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|location=Bolton\n|mile=21.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|117|name1=Main Street|city1=Lancaster|city2=Stow}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 85}}\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20110728184019/http://www.env.state.ma.us/mepa/mepacerts/2010/sc/enf/14638enf.pdf Reconstruction of State Route 85]\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|085]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Worcester County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=85\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=320|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 85}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 85 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=21.01\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">{{cite web |url=http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/routelog.htm?routekey=SR85%20NB |title=Massachusetts Route Log Application |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |website=[[MassDOT]] |publisher= |access-date=August 7, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n|length_round=4\n|established=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|MA|16}} in [[Milford, Massachusetts|Milford]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|495}} in Milford\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|135}} in [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts|Hopkinton]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|9|MA|30}} in [[Southborough, Massachusetts|Southborough]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|20}} in [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]]\n}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|MA|117}} in [[Bolton, Massachusetts|Bolton]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=84\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=86\n}}\n\n'''Route 85''' is a {{convert|21.01|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} north&ndash;south [[state highway]] in [[Massachusetts]], United States. It passes through the heart of [[Boston|Boston's]] [[MetroWest]] region, through towns on the eastern edge of [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]] and western edge of [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]], crossing the border between the two counties four times. Throughout its entire distance, Route 85 runs parallel to I-495, never passing more than two miles from it.\n\n==Route description==\nRoute 85 begins in the town of [[Milford, Massachusetts|Milford]] at [[Massachusetts Route 16|Route 16]], just west of the downtown area.  It passes east of Milford Pond before meeting [[Interstate 495 (Massachusetts)|I-495]] at Exit 20.  From there, Route 85 heads northward into [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts|Hopkinton]], passing the eastern side of Echo Lake.  It intersects [[Massachusetts Route 135|Route 135]] at the center of town, less than a quarter mile west of the start line of the [[Boston Marathon]].  It then passes through Hopkinton State Forest and past the Hopkinton Reservoir before entering the town of [[Southborough, Massachusetts|Southborough]].\n\n[[Image:MA Route 85 southbound, Hopkinton MA.jpg|thumb|left|200px|<center>Southbound in Hopkinton</center>]]\nIn Southborough, Route 85 crosses under [[Massachusetts Turnpike|I-90]] (the Mass Pike) without junction; the nearest exit is in neighboring [[Framingham, Massachusetts|Framingham]].  It then meets [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]], the second of the four major east-west routes out of Boston, in an elevated four-way cloverleaf intersection.  It then crosses the [[Sudbury Reservoir]] before meeting [[Massachusetts Route 30|Route 30]] at the center of town.  From there, Route 85 continues northward into [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]], meeting [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] in the downtown area. It then crosses the far western edge of the Fort Meadow Reservoir before crossing into [[Hudson, Massachusetts|Hudson]].  \n\nShortly after entering Hudson, Route 85 meets Hudson Street, the [[super two]] connector road between Route 85 and the junction of [[Interstate 290 (Massachusetts)|I-290]] and I-495 at I-495's Exit 25 and I-290's terminus, Exit 26.  From there Route 85 heads north, crossing the [[Assabet River]] before meeting [[Massachusetts Route 62|Route 62]], passing concurrently with that route through Wood Square before Route 85 continues northward.  After passing into [[Bolton, Massachusetts|Bolton]], the route passes between Little Pond and West Pond before ending at [[Massachusetts Route 117|Route 117]], less than a half mile east of I-495's exit 27.\n\n=== Route 85 Connector ===\nMA&nbsp;85 Connector is a road that goes from the eastern terminus of [[Interstate 290 (Massachusetts)|Interstate&nbsp;290]] (I-290) to a wye with MA&nbsp;85, {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=on}} away in [[Marlborough, Massachusetts|Marlborough]].<ref name=\"ma85connector\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/42.3637771,-71.5837487/42.3712321,-71.5691026/@42.3691474,-71.5811337,14.75z|title=Route 85 Connector|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n{{update|section|date=March 2018}}\n===Improvements to Route 85 in Hudson===\nIn 2011 a $10.8 million project to reconstruct 7,700 feet (1.5 miles) from School Street/Park Street to the Marlborough City Line will begin. The project will consist of {{convert|11|ft|m|adj=on}} travel lanes and {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} bike shoulders with {{convert|5.5|ft|m|adj=on}} concrete sidewalks throughout the project corridor. The Walmart Driveway will be reconstructed with bicycle accommodation, ADA compliance, and a new traffic signal. At the intersection of the Route 85 Connector and Technology Drive, the intersection will be reconstructed. A new northbound left turn lane will be constructed, new through lane constructed on Technology Drive, new through lane on Route 85 Connector and a new wire traffic signal. The section between Route 85 Connector and Broad Street will consist of four lanes (two in each direction) with a {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} raised concrete median. At the intersection of Broad Street, the existing signal will be replaced with a two-lane roundabout. The roadway will be widened to four lanes (two in each direction)from Houghton Street to Broad Street. A new traffic signal will be installed at R.K Town Centre Drive with a new turn lane. A new traffic signal will be installed at Giasson Street. A new northbound left turn lane with a new traffic signal will be installed at Brigham Street. From Brigham Street to Park Street, the roadway will be cold planed and resurfaced with drainage, curbing, sidewalks and driveways included. At Park Street/School Street, a new traffic signal will be installed and a new southbound right turn lane will be constructed.\n\n===Hudson Route 85 Bridge===\nBeginning in 2013, MassDOT will replace the existing structurally deficient arch bridge with a new bridge. The estimated cost is $7 million. The project is funded as part of the Accelerated Bridge Program and will use an innovative construction. The new bridge will consist of new concrete reinforced abutments and a new concrete NEXT beam superstructure.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=2\n|location=Milford\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|16|name1=Main Street|extra=hospital|city1=Uxbridge|city2=Webster|city3=Holliston|city4=Natick}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; serves [[Milford Regional Medical Center]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.3\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|495|city1=Cape Cod|city2=Lowell}}\n|notes=[[Diamond interchange]]; I-495 Exit 20\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|location=Hopkinton\n|mile=5.9\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|135|name1=Main Street|city1=Westboro|city2=Ashland}}\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=2\n|location=Southborough\n|lspan=2\n|mile=10.4\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|city1=Framingham|city2=Boston|city3=Worcester|city4=Amherst}}\n|notes=Cloverleaf interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.4\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|30|city1=Framingham|city2=Westboro}}\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|cspan=4\n|location=Marlborough\n|mile=14.5\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|to2=to|I|495|city1=Northboro|city2=Worcester|city3=Sudbury|city4=Waltham}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Hudson\n|lspan=3\n|mile=16.9\n|road={{jct|state=MA|to1=yes|I|290|I|495|dir1=west|city1=Worcester|location2=[[Norwich, Connecticut|Norwich, CT]]|city3=Lowell|city4=Cape Cod}}\n|notes=Access via {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=on}} Route 85 Connector<ref name=\"ma85connector\">{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/42.3637771,-71.5837487/42.3712321,-71.5691026/@42.3691474,-71.5811337,14.75z|title=Route 85 Connector|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=18.1\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|name1=Main Street east|road=Felton Street|city1=Stow|city2=Maynard}}\n|notes=Rotary; south end of concurrency with Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=18.105\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=west|name1=Central Street|to2=to|I|495|city1=Berlin|city2=Clinton}}\n|notes=North end of concurrency with Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|location=Bolton\n|mile=21.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|117|name1=Main Street|city1=Bolton|city2=Lancaster|city3=Stow}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\