t the [[1964 Australian Senate election|5 December 1964 half Senate election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1965 and finishing on 30 June 1971.  The process for filling casual vacancies was complex. While senators were elected for a six-year term, people appointed to a casual vacancy only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Senator'''\n! colspan=2 | '''Party'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''End term'''\n! '''Years in Office'''\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ken|Anderson|Ken Anderson (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[New South Wales]] || 1971 || 1953\u20131975\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Archie|Benn}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[Queensland]] || 1968 || 1950\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Reg|Bishop}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[South Australia]] || 1968 || 1962\u20131981\n|-\n|| {{sortname|George|Branson}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[Western Australia]] || 1971 || 1958\u20131971\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Marie|Breen}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] || 1968 || 1962\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Tom|Bull}} || {{Australian party style|National}}|&nbsp; || [[National Party of Australia|Country]] || New South Wales || 1971 || 1965\u20131971\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Harry|Cant}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || Western Australia || 1971 || 1959\u20131974\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Jim|Cavanagh}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || South Australia || 1968 || 1962\u20131981\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Sam|Cohen|Sam Cohen (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian 