tics/party colours|National}}|border=darkgray}} [[National Party of Australia|Country Party]] (6) <br />\n<br />\n'''[[Opposition (Australia)|Opposition]] (27)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Labor}}|border=darkgray}} [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (27) <br />\n<br />\n'''[[Crossbencher|Crossbench]] (3)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Democratic Labor}}|border=darkgray}}  [[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|DLP]] (2) <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Independent}}|border=darkgray}} [[Independent politician|Independents]] (1) <br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nChanges in composition\n{{notelist-lr}}\n| width = 265px| align=}}\nThis is a list of '''members of the [[Australian Senate]]''' from 1965 to 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate 1965 |url=http://biography.senate.gov.au/?search-class=DB_CustomSearch_Widget-db_customsearch_widget&widget_number=3&cs-dates-0=1965&search=Search |publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]] |access-date=21 March 2017}}</ref> Half of its members were elected at the [[1961 Australian federal election|9 December 1961 election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1962 and finishing on 30 June 1968; the other half were elected at the [[1964 Australian Senate election|5 December 1964 half Senate election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1965 and finishing on 30 June 1971.  The process for filling casual vacancies was complex. While senators were elected for a six year term, people appointed to a casual vacancy only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Senator'''\n! colspan=2 | '''Party'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''End term'''\n! '''Years in Office'''\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ken|Anderson|Ken Anderson (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[N