e Minister]] on 10 January 1968 after the disappearance of [[Harold Holt]] and is the only senator to be Prime Minister. Convention required the Prime Minister to be a member of the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] and Gorton resigned from the Senate on 1 February 1968 to successfully contest Holt's old seat. Liberal member [[Ivor Greenwood]] was appointed to fill the ensuing Senate vacancy on 21 February until a special election at the [[1969 Australian federal election|October 1969 House of Representatives election]], when he was elected to complete the term until 30 June 1971.}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || Victoria || 1971 || 1950\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ivor|Greenwood}} {{efn|name=Gorton}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || Victoria || 1969,{{efn|name=Appointment}} 1971 || 1968\u20131976\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Clive|Hannaford}} {{efn|name=Hannaford|Liberal Senator [[Clive Hannaford]] died on 24 October 1967; Liberal member [[Condor Laucke]] was appointed to fill the ensuing vacancy on 2 November to complete the term until 30 June 1968.}}  || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || South Australia || 1968 || 1950\u20131967\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Bill|Heatley}} {{efn|name=Sherrington}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || Queensland || 1966,{{efn|name=Appointment}} 1968 || 1966\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Bert|Hendrickson}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || Victoria || 1971 || 1947\u20131971\n|-\n|| {{sort|Henty, Denham|Hon. [[Denham Henty]]}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || Tasmania || 1968 || 1950\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Jim|Keeffe}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]