{"title_page": "Jesmond", "text_new": "{{for|the places in Australia and Canada|Jesmond, New South Wales|Jesmond, British Columbia}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{infobox UK place\n|country = England \n|official_name = Jesmond \n|map_type = Tyne and Wear \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.9829|-1.6038|display=inline,title}}\n| population = \n| population_ref = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Jesmond ward]]: 11,849 <br/> ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])\n |population_density = 5584/km\u00b2\n|london_distance = {{convert|242|mi|km}}\n|metropolitan_borough = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] \n|metropolitan_county = [[Tyne and Wear]] \n|region = North East England \n|constituency_westminster = [[Newcastle upon Tyne East (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]]\n|post_town = NEWCASTLE UPON TYNE \n|postcode_district = NE2\n|postcode_area = NE \n|dial_code = [[0191]] \n|static_image_name = West Jesmond - geograph.org.uk - 1215315.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Panoramic view of West Jesmond\n|os_grid_reference = NZ253654\n| councillor1 = '''North Jesmond'''<br>Wendy Young ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Stella Artois ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Gerry Keating ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]])\n| councillor2 = '''South Jesmond'''<br>Lesley Storey ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Felicity Mendelson MBE ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Arlene Ainsley ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])\n}}\n\n'''Jesmond''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|\u025b|z|m|\u0259n|d}} is a largely residential suburb immediately to the north of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] city centre, in [[North East England|North East England.]] It has a population of about 12,000 and is split into two [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral wards.]] [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Northumberland]], it is adjacent to the East side of the [[Town Moor, Newcastle upon Tyne|Town Moor]], providing pedestrian and cycle paths to [[Spital Tongues]] and the city's two universities. It is widely considered to be the most affluent suburb of Newcastle and is home to a large student population. <ref name=\"nechronicleadministrator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/ten-interesting-facts-jesmond--1342141|title=Ten interesting facts about Jesmond & Sandyford|author=nechronicle Administrator|date=1 January 2012|work=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Disputed section|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:St. Georges Church Jesmond Newcastle.jpg|left|thumb|St. Georges Church Jesmond Newcastle]]\nAccording to local tradition, some time shortly after the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman conquest]] there occurred in the valley of the [[Ouseburn|Ouse]] an apparition of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]]. It seems reasonable to suppose that the Virgin was beheld with the infant [[Christ]], because up until that time Jesmond had been known as Gese Muth \"the mouth of the Ouse\" while afterwards the name was popularly interpreted as \"the hill of Jesus\", or \"Jesus Mound\". {{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} The ruins of St Mary's Chapel, first recorded in 1272, are in [[Jesmond Dene]]<ref name=\"nechronicleadministrator\" /> on the west side of the valley.\n\nA trace of the processions to the shrine which occurred during the Middle Ages is found in the name of that section of the former [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]] running north of the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] called Pilgrim Street. During a period in which the shrine was in need of repair it was endowed with indulgences by a [[rescript]] or edict of [[Pope Martin V]] on certain feasts of the liturgical year. A spring known as St Mary's Well of uncertain date may also be found near to the chapel. It has the word \"Gratia\" inscribed upon the stone above it. The greater part of the history of the shrine, its origins and the miracles which were said to have occurred there, were lost in the 16th century when the chapel was suppressed in the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] and fell into ruin. The ruin and its grounds later passed through various owners (one of whom tried to turn the well into a bathing pool). It was acquired by [[William George Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|Lord Armstrong]] in the 19th century and given by him to the City of Newcastle. [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] is now offered there on occasion by the local Roman Catholic priest and the Roman Catholic [[Bishop of Hexham and Newcastle]]. Flowers along with letters and candles are often left in the ruins by pilgrims and others. A booklet outlining the surviving history of the chapel may be obtained from the Roman Catholic Church of the [[Holy Name parish, Jesmond|Holy Name]] on North Jesmond Avenue.\n\n[[The Beatles]] began writing their second hit single [[She Loves You]] in the Imperial Hotel in Jesmond, [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] on 27 June 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sclews.me.uk/beatles.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930032424/http://www.sclews.me.uk/beatles.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 September 2015|title=The Beatles|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Areas of Jesmond==\n[[File:St Georges Terrace Jesmond Newcastle.JPG|thumb|right|200px|St George's Terrace, in Jesmond's commercial area]]\nThe area is notable for [[Jesmond Parish Church]], Holy Trinity Church, Jesmond Dene woodland and the [[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle|Royal Grammar School]]. The area's principal commercial area forms around Osborne Road, Acorn Road and St George's Terrace, the former being dominated by hotels and bars, and the latter by shops and cafes.\n\nNewcastle City Council has designated <ref>[http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/hes.nsf/a/herlistca Conservation Areas in the City], Newcastle City Council</ref> three conservation areas within Jesmond; Brandling Village, South Jesmond and Jesmond Dene.\n\nThe Mansion House was owned by a wealthy industrialist [[Arthur Sutherland]], 1st Baronet, and is one of the most impressive residential properties in Jesmond. Built in 1887, the property was donated to the city by Sutherland in 1953 and is now the official residence of the Lord Mayor and can be used for private events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/communities-and-neighbourhoods/births-deaths-and-marriages/marriages-and-civil-partnerships/mansion-house-jesmond|title=The Mansion House in Jesmond|publisher=}}</ref> The house, situated in the centre of Jesmond previously sat in {{convert|5|acre|m2}} of land. One acre of the land including previous stables were sold as a private property, now owned by relatives of Arthur Sutherland.\n\nAlong with [[Leeds]] and [[Belfast]], Newcastle is experiencing [[College town|studentification]].<ref>[http://www.wardhadaway.com/legal/read.php?id=280 Halting the Proliferation of Student Housing], WardHadaway Solicitors {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506043502/http://www.wardhadaway.com/legal/read.php?id=280 |date=6 May 2006 }}</ref> Jesmond is a popular residential area for students attending [[Newcastle University]] and [[Northumbria University]]. Osborne Road in Jesmond has a strong student population with a selection of student bars, restaurants and housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roseworth.co.uk/newcastle/jesmond|title=Student Accommodation in Jesmond|author=Roseworth|first=|date=|website=Roseworth Student Lettings|accessdate=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nNewcastle Cricket Club plays its home games at [[Osborne Avenue]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcastlecc.org.uk/|title=Newcastle Cricket Club|publisher=www.newcastlecc.org.uk|accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> which is also a home venue for [[Northumberland County Cricket Club]]. The cricket club is currently on a 50-year lease to Newcastle Royal Grammar School. The Jesmond Lawn Tennis club is also popular for socialising.\nBehind the back of Manor House Road, an illegal chicken fighting ring is known to take place every Friday at 21:00. Whilst this road is known for its luxurious housing, residents are known to bet their homes on the outcome of certain chicken fights. It was once said the owner of R&Ks once wagered his entire enterprise on one jelly snake and won.\n\nJesmond is one of the 26 areas in England to have a [[real tennis]] club which is used to hold events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdrtc.co.uk/|title=home|website=Jesmond Dene Real Tennis Club - Newcastle}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable Jesmond residents have included the industrialist [[William George Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|William Armstrong]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.williamarmstrong.info/jesmond-dene-visitor-centre|title=William Armstrong - Jesmond Dene|publisher=}}</ref> the golfer [[Lee Westwood]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jesmondlocal.com/2016/06/ryder-cup-legend-lee-westwood-opens-new-facilities-in-jesmond/|title=Westwood opens Jesmond facilities|publisher=}}</ref> philosopher [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twsitelines.info/smr/13288|title=Jesmond, Brandling Park, No. 28 - sitelines.newcastle.gov.uk|publisher=}}</ref> actor [[James Scott (actor)|James Scott]], English Rugby Union player [[Mathew Tait]], footballers [[Shola Ameobi]], [[Kevin Nolan]] and [[Jon\u00e1s Guti\u00e9rrez]], journalist and broadcaster [[Nancy Spain]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/60418|title=Spain, Nancy Brooker (1917-1964), journalist and broadcaster|publisher=}}</ref> concert pianist [[Denis Matthews]], writer [[Catherine Cookson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/former-home-catherine-cookson-up-1403549|title=Former home of Catherine Cookson up for sale|author=nechronicle Administrator|date=28 August 2011|work=nechronicle}}</ref> writer and poet [[Michael Roberts (writer)|Michael Roberts]], singers [[Bryan Ferry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecourieronline.co.uk/exclusive-bryan-ferry-interview-newcastle-was-a-wonderful-place-to-be-2/|title=Exclusive Bryan Ferry interview: \"Newcastle was a wonderful place to be\"|author=Tom Nicholson|date=15 July 2014|work=The Courier Online|access-date=13 March 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150315072520/http://thecourieronline.co.uk/exclusive-bryan-ferry-interview-newcastle-was-a-wonderful-place-to-be-2/|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], countertenor [[James Bowman (countertenor)|James Bowman]], TV/Radio broadcaster [[Bill Steel]], songwriter and record producer [[Steve Hillier]], novelists [[Eva Ibbotson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/eva-ibbotsons-son-speaks-legacy-4431585|title=Eva Ibbotson's son speaks about her legacy|author=journallive Administrator|date=10 May 2011|work=journallive}}</ref> [[Yevgeny Zamyatin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/arnold-schwarzenegger-giuseppe-garibaldi-fascinating-10621607|title=From Arnold Schwarzenegger to Giuseppe Garibaldi fascinating Tyneside connections you never knew|author=Mike Kelly|date=20 December 2015|work=nechronicle}}</ref> and [[Denis MacEoin]] (aka Daniel Easterman and Jonathan Aycliffe).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bestselling-author-denis-maceoin-bankrupt-1453862|title=Bestselling author Denis MacEoin is bankrupt|author=Coreena Ford|date=2 May 2009|work=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\n[[Arthur Sutherland]] 1st Baronet; former owner of the Mansion House. The only Briton to die{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} in the [[The Killing Fields|Killing Fields]] of [[Cambodia]], [[John Dawson Dewhirst|John Dewhirst]], was born in Jesmond. [[Chris Donald]] and [[Simon Donald]], the founders of [[Viz (comic)|Viz]], spent their early lives on Lily Crescent in Jesmond. Theoretical physicist [[Peter Higgs]] lived in Jesmond as a small child. Businesswoman [[Margaret Barbour]] lives in Jesmond.\n\n==Jesmond schools==\n\n=== Primary schools ===\n\n*West Jesmond Primary School\n:West Jesmond is a 4-11 primary school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schoolguide.co.uk/schools/west-jesmond-primary-national-teaching-school-newcastle-upon-tyne|title=West Jesmond Primary National Teaching School review - School Guide|website=schoolguide.co.uk}}</ref> The original building was demolished in 2008 and a new school rebuilt on the same site. The new school building opened on 2 March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westjesmondprimary.org.uk/our-school|title=Our School - West Jesmond Primary School|website=www.westjesmondprimary.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Independent schools===\n*[[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/newcastle-royal-grammar-school-headteacher-8542013|title=Newcastle Royal Grammar School headteacher criticises 'madness' of league tables|first=Ruth|last=Lognonne|date=29 January 2015|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n*[[Central Newcastle High School]] (girls only) \u2013 merged into new school\n*[[Newcastle upon Tyne Church High School|Church High School]] (girls only) \u2013 merged into new school\n*Central Newcastle High School and Church High School merged in September 2014 to create [[Newcastle High School for Girls]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/newcastle-girls-schools-merger-shocks-4398784|title=Newcastle girls' schools merger shocks parents and pupils - The Journal|first=Liz|last=Walker|website=www.thejournal.co.uk}}</ref> \n*Northern Counties School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncs.percyhedley.org.uk/how-to-find-us/|title=How to find us|website=Northern Counties School}}</ref>\n*Newcastle Preparatory School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/school/108540/newcastle-preparatory-school/primary|title=Newcastle Preparatory School|publisher=Gov.uk|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings==\n[[File:Jesmond Parish Church, Newcastle upon Tyne.jpg|thumb|Jesmond Parish Church, Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n\n* [[Jesmond Synagogue]]\n* [[Jesmond Parish Church]]\n*[[Jesmond Library]]\n\n==Film==\n\nThe [[La Sagesse School]] in Jesmond (now closed and converted into housing) was used as a set for ''[[The Dumping Ground]]'', a spin-off of the popular children's television series ''[[Tracy Beaker Returns]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/news/north-east-news/2009/08/30/tracy-beaker-heads-north-to-film-at-la-sagesse-79310-24565777/|title=Sunday Sun|work=nechronicle}}</ref> starring [[Dani Harmer]].\n\n==Metro stations==\n[[File:Jesmond Metro station, 9 August 2013 (1).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Entrance to the Jesmond Metro station]]\nJesmond is served by the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]], with stations at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], [[West Jesmond Metro station|West Jesmond]] and [[Ilford Road Metro station|Ilford Road]]. Jesmond station is the point at which Metro trains travelling north emerge from the underground section. Trains travel southbound to [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] or [[South Shields]] via [[Newcastle upon Tyne City Centre|city centre]] and [[Gateshead]] and northbound to the [[Newcastle International Airport|airport]] via [[Kingston Park]], or to [[Whitley Bay]]. Jesmond also has an extra section of non-passenger track called the Manors Stock Curve, used for re-routing trains. The old Jesmond station, which formed part of the suburban rail network prior to the Tyne and Wear Metro network, is situated on the Manors Stock Curve and can be observed from Osborne Terrace with intact platforms.\n\n==Religion==\nThere has been an active [[Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed]] community in Jesmond for over 25 years, Jesmond is also home to the only [[Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed]] Centre in [[North East England]], located on Victoria Square near the civic centre.\n\nOne of the largest [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] [[Anglican]] churches in the UK is [[Jesmond Parish Church]], which is affiliated with the controversial [[Christian Institute]] (based in nearby [[Gosforth]]), and has attracted several [[picketing|pickets]], particularly over its stance opposing active [[homosexuality]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Nightlife==\nDue to a rising population of students and young professionals, Osborne Road has in recent years become a popular venue for nightlife, eating and socialising. With a large number of bars and restaurants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastlegateshead.com/plan-your-visit/about-the-area/jesmond|title=Jesmond|publisher=}}</ref> in one location it can become congested on busy nights. The road also has a number of medium-sized hotels.\n\n==References==\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2007}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://jesmondlocal.com JesmondLocal: Hyperlocal news site covering Jesmond]\n* [http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/core.nsf/a/wardinfonorthjesmond Newcastle Council Ward Info: North Jesmond].\n* [http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/core.nsf/a/wardinfosouthjesmond Newcastle Council Ward Info: South Jesmond]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060803042247/http://www.jesmond.uk.net/www.jesmond.uk.net/ Jesmond Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090306173845/http://www.whatsinjesmond.com/ What's in Jesmond]\n* [http://www.jesmondresidents.org  JRA]\n{{T&W places}}\n\n[[Category:Student quarters]]\n[[Category:Districts of Newcastle upon Tyne|Jesmond (North and South)]]\n[[Category:Wards of Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Northumbria University]]\n[[Category:Marian apparitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the places in Australia and Canada|Jesmond, New South Wales|Jesmond, British Columbia}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{infobox UK place\n|country = England \n|official_name = Jesmond \n|map_type = Tyne and Wear \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.9829|-1.6038|display=inline,title}}\n| population = \n| population_ref = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Jesmond ward]]: 11,849 <br/> ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])\n |population_density = 5584/km\u00b2\n|london_distance = {{convert|242|mi|km}}\n|metropolitan_borough = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] \n|metropolitan_county = [[Tyne and Wear]] \n|region = North East England \n|constituency_westminster = [[Newcastle upon Tyne East (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]]\n|post_town = NEWCASTLE UPON TYNE \n|postcode_district = NE2\n|postcode_area = NE \n|dial_code = [[0191]] \n|static_image_name = West Jesmond - geograph.org.uk - 1215315.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Panoramic view of West Jesmond\n|os_grid_reference = NZ253654\n| councillor1 = '''North Jesmond'''<br>Wendy Young ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Stella Artois ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Gerry Keating ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]])\n| councillor2 = '''South Jesmond'''<br>Lesley Storey ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Felicity Mendelson MBE ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])<br>Arlene Ainsley ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])\n}}\n\n'''Jesmond''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|\u025b|z|m|\u0259n|d}} is a largely residential suburb immediately to the north of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] city centre, in [[North East England|North East England.]] It has a population of about 12,000 and is split into two [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral wards.]] [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Northumberland]], it is adjacent to the East side of the [[Town Moor, Newcastle upon Tyne|Town Moor]], providing pedestrian and cycle paths to [[Spital Tongues]] and the city's two universities. It is widely considered to be the most affluent suburb of Newcastle and is home to a large student population. <ref name=\"nechronicleadministrator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/ten-interesting-facts-jesmond--1342141|title=Ten interesting facts about Jesmond & Sandyford|author=nechronicle Administrator|date=1 January 2012|work=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Disputed section|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:St. Georges Church Jesmond Newcastle.jpg|left|thumb|St. Georges Church Jesmond Newcastle]]\nAccording to local tradition, some time shortly after the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman conquest]] there occurred in the valley of the [[Ouseburn|Ouse]] an apparition of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]]. It seems reasonable to suppose that the Virgin was beheld with the infant [[Christ]], because up until that time Jesmond had been known as Gese Muth \"the mouth of the Ouse\" while afterwards the name was popularly interpreted as \"the hill of Jesus\", or \"Jesus Mound\". {{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} The ruins of St Mary's Chapel, first recorded in 1272, are in [[Jesmond Dene]]<ref name=\"nechronicleadministrator\" /> on the west side of the valley.\n\nA trace of the processions to the shrine which occurred during the Middle Ages is found in the name of that section of the former [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]] running north of the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] called Pilgrim Street. During a period in which the shrine was in need of repair it was endowed with indulgences by a [[rescript]] or edict of [[Pope Martin V]] on certain feasts of the liturgical year. A spring known as St Mary's Well of uncertain date may also be found near to the chapel. It has the word \"Gratia\" inscribed upon the stone above it. The greater part of the history of the shrine, its origins and the miracles which were said to have occurred there, were lost in the 16th century when the chapel was suppressed in the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] and fell into ruin. The ruin and its grounds later passed through various owners (one of whom tried to turn the well into a bathing pool). It was acquired by [[William George Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|Lord Armstrong]] in the 19th century and given by him to the City of Newcastle. [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] is now offered there on occasion by the local Roman Catholic priest and the Roman Catholic [[Bishop of Hexham and Newcastle]]. Flowers along with letters and candles are often left in the ruins by pilgrims and others. A booklet outlining the surviving history of the chapel may be obtained from the Roman Catholic Church of the [[Holy Name parish, Jesmond|Holy Name]] on North Jesmond Avenue.\n\n[[The Beatles]] began writing their second hit single [[She Loves You]] in the Imperial Hotel in Jesmond, [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] on 27 June 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sclews.me.uk/beatles.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930032424/http://www.sclews.me.uk/beatles.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 September 2015|title=The Beatles|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Areas of Jesmond==\n[[File:St Georges Terrace Jesmond Newcastle.JPG|thumb|right|200px|St George's Terrace, in Jesmond's commercial area]]\nThe area is notable for [[Jesmond Parish Church]], Holy Trinity Church, Jesmond Dene woodland and the [[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle|Royal Grammar School]]. The area's principal commercial area forms around Osborne Road, Acorn Road and St George's Terrace, the former being dominated by hotels and bars, and the latter by shops and cafes.\n\nNewcastle City Council has designated <ref>[http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/hes.nsf/a/herlistca Conservation Areas in the City], Newcastle City Council</ref> three conservation areas within Jesmond; Brandling Village, South Jesmond and Jesmond Dene.\n\nThe Mansion House was owned by a wealthy industrialist [[Arthur Sutherland]], 1st Baronet, and is one of the most impressive residential properties in Jesmond. Built in 1887, the property was donated to the city by Sutherland in 1953 and is now the official residence of the Lord Mayor and can be used for private events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/communities-and-neighbourhoods/births-deaths-and-marriages/marriages-and-civil-partnerships/mansion-house-jesmond|title=The Mansion House in Jesmond|publisher=}}</ref> The house, situated in the centre of Jesmond previously sat in {{convert|5|acre|m2}} of land. One acre of the land including previous stables were sold as a private property, now owned by relatives of Arthur Sutherland.\n\nAlong with [[Leeds]] and [[Belfast]], Newcastle is experiencing [[College town|studentification]].<ref>[http://www.wardhadaway.com/legal/read.php?id=280 Halting the Proliferation of Student Housing], WardHadaway Solicitors {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506043502/http://www.wardhadaway.com/legal/read.php?id=280 |date=6 May 2006 }}</ref> Jesmond is a popular residential area for students attending [[Newcastle University]] and [[Northumbria University]]. Osborne Road in Jesmond has a strong student population with a selection of student bars, restaurants and housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roseworth.co.uk/newcastle/jesmond|title=Student Accommodation in Jesmond|author=Roseworth|first=|date=|website=Roseworth Student Lettings|accessdate=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nNewcastle Cricket Club plays its home games at [[Osborne Avenue]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcastlecc.org.uk/|title=Newcastle Cricket Club|publisher=www.newcastlecc.org.uk|accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> which is also a home venue for [[Northumberland County Cricket Club]]. The cricket club is currently on a 50-year lease to Newcastle Royal Grammar School. The Jesmond Lawn Tennis club is also popular for socialising.\n\nJesmond is one of the 26 areas in England to have a [[real tennis]] club which is used to hold events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdrtc.co.uk/|title=home|website=Jesmond Dene Real Tennis Club - Newcastle}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable Jesmond residents have included the industrialist [[William George Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|William Armstrong]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.williamarmstrong.info/jesmond-dene-visitor-centre|title=William Armstrong - Jesmond Dene|publisher=}}</ref> the golfer [[Lee Westwood]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jesmondlocal.com/2016/06/ryder-cup-legend-lee-westwood-opens-new-facilities-in-jesmond/|title=Westwood opens Jesmond facilities|publisher=}}</ref> philosopher [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twsitelines.info/smr/13288|title=Jesmond, Brandling Park, No. 28 - sitelines.newcastle.gov.uk|publisher=}}</ref> actor [[James Scott (actor)|James Scott]], English Rugby Union player [[Mathew Tait]], footballers [[Shola Ameobi]], [[Kevin Nolan]] and [[Jon\u00e1s Guti\u00e9rrez]], journalist and broadcaster [[Nancy Spain]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/60418|title=Spain, Nancy Brooker (1917-1964), journalist and broadcaster|publisher=}}</ref> concert pianist [[Denis Matthews]], writer [[Catherine Cookson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/former-home-catherine-cookson-up-1403549|title=Former home of Catherine Cookson up for sale|author=nechronicle Administrator|date=28 August 2011|work=nechronicle}}</ref> writer and poet [[Michael Roberts (writer)|Michael Roberts]], singers [[Bryan Ferry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecourieronline.co.uk/exclusive-bryan-ferry-interview-newcastle-was-a-wonderful-place-to-be-2/|title=Exclusive Bryan Ferry interview: \"Newcastle was a wonderful place to be\"|author=Tom Nicholson|date=15 July 2014|work=The Courier Online|access-date=13 March 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150315072520/http://thecourieronline.co.uk/exclusive-bryan-ferry-interview-newcastle-was-a-wonderful-place-to-be-2/|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], countertenor [[James Bowman (countertenor)|James Bowman]], TV/Radio broadcaster [[Bill Steel]], songwriter and record producer [[Steve Hillier]], novelists [[Eva Ibbotson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/eva-ibbotsons-son-speaks-legacy-4431585|title=Eva Ibbotson's son speaks about her legacy|author=journallive Administrator|date=10 May 2011|work=journallive}}</ref> [[Yevgeny Zamyatin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/arnold-schwarzenegger-giuseppe-garibaldi-fascinating-10621607|title=From Arnold Schwarzenegger to Giuseppe Garibaldi fascinating Tyneside connections you never knew|author=Mike Kelly|date=20 December 2015|work=nechronicle}}</ref> and [[Denis MacEoin]] (aka Daniel Easterman and Jonathan Aycliffe).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bestselling-author-denis-maceoin-bankrupt-1453862|title=Bestselling author Denis MacEoin is bankrupt|author=Coreena Ford|date=2 May 2009|work=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\n[[Arthur Sutherland]] 1st Baronet; former owner of the Mansion House. The only Briton to die{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} in the [[The Killing Fields|Killing Fields]] of [[Cambodia]], [[John Dawson Dewhirst|John Dewhirst]], was born in Jesmond. [[Chris Donald]] and [[Simon Donald]], the founders of [[Viz (comic)|Viz]], spent their early lives on Lily Crescent in Jesmond. Theoretical physicist [[Peter Higgs]] lived in Jesmond as a small child. Businesswoman [[Margaret Barbour]] lives in Jesmond.\n\n==Jesmond schools==\n\n=== Primary schools ===\n\n*West Jesmond Primary School\n:West Jesmond is a 4-11 primary school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schoolguide.co.uk/schools/west-jesmond-primary-national-teaching-school-newcastle-upon-tyne|title=West Jesmond Primary National Teaching School review - School Guide|website=schoolguide.co.uk}}</ref> The original building was demolished in 2008 and a new school rebuilt on the same site. The new school building opened on 2 March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westjesmondprimary.org.uk/our-school|title=Our School - West Jesmond Primary School|website=www.westjesmondprimary.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Independent schools===\n*[[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/newcastle-royal-grammar-school-headteacher-8542013|title=Newcastle Royal Grammar School headteacher criticises 'madness' of league tables|first=Ruth|last=Lognonne|date=29 January 2015|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n*[[Central Newcastle High School]] (girls only) \u2013 merged into new school\n*[[Newcastle upon Tyne Church High School|Church High School]] (girls only) \u2013 merged into new school\n*Central Newcastle High School and Church High School merged in September 2014 to create [[Newcastle High School for Girls]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/newcastle-girls-schools-merger-shocks-4398784|title=Newcastle girls' schools merger shocks parents and pupils - The Journal|first=Liz|last=Walker|website=www.thejournal.co.uk}}</ref> \n*Northern Counties School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncs.percyhedley.org.uk/how-to-find-us/|title=How to find us|website=Northern Counties School}}</ref>\n*Newcastle Preparatory School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/school/108540/newcastle-preparatory-school/primary|title=Newcastle Preparatory School|publisher=Gov.uk|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings==\n[[File:Jesmond Parish Church, Newcastle upon Tyne.jpg|thumb|Jesmond Parish Church, Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n\n* [[Jesmond Synagogue]]\n* [[Jesmond Parish Church]]\n*[[Jesmond Library]]\n\n==Film==\n\nThe [[La Sagesse School]] in Jesmond (now closed and converted into housing) was used as a set for ''[[The Dumping Ground]]'', a spin-off of the popular children's television series ''[[Tracy Beaker Returns]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/news/north-east-news/2009/08/30/tracy-beaker-heads-north-to-film-at-la-sagesse-79310-24565777/|title=Sunday Sun|work=nechronicle}}</ref> starring [[Dani Harmer]].\n\n==Metro stations==\n[[File:Jesmond Metro station, 9 August 2013 (1).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Entrance to the Jesmond Metro station]]\nJesmond is served by the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]], with stations at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], [[West Jesmond Metro station|West Jesmond]] and [[Ilford Road Metro station|Ilford Road]]. Jesmond station is the point at which Metro trains travelling north emerge from the underground section. Trains travel southbound to [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] or [[South Shields]] via [[Newcastle upon Tyne City Centre|city centre]] and [[Gateshead]] and northbound to the [[Newcastle International Airport|airport]] via [[Kingston Park]], or to [[Whitley Bay]]. Jesmond also has an extra section of non-passenger track called the Manors Stock Curve, used for re-routing trains. The old Jesmond station, which formed part of the suburban rail network prior to the Tyne and Wear Metro network, is situated on the Manors Stock Curve and can be observed from Osborne Terrace with intact platforms.\n\n==Religion==\nThere has been an active [[Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed]] community in Jesmond for over 25 years, Jesmond is also home to the only [[Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed]] Centre in [[North East England]], located on Victoria Square near the civic centre.\n\nOne of the largest [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] [[Anglican]] churches in the UK is [[Jesmond Parish Church]], which is affiliated with the controversial [[Christian Institute]] (based in nearby [[Gosforth]]), and has attracted several [[picketing|pickets]], particularly over its stance opposing active [[homosexuality]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Nightlife==\nDue to a rising population of students and young professionals, Osborne Road has in recent years become a popular venue for nightlife, eating and socialising. With a large number of bars and restaurants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastlegateshead.com/plan-your-visit/about-the-area/jesmond|title=Jesmond|publisher=}}</ref> in one location it can become congested on busy nights. The road also has a number of medium-sized hotels.\n\n==References==\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2007}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://jesmondlocal.com JesmondLocal: Hyperlocal news site covering Jesmond]\n* [http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/core.nsf/a/wardinfonorthjesmond Newcastle Council Ward Info: North Jesmond].\n* [http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/core.nsf/a/wardinfosouthjesmond Newcastle Council Ward Info: South Jesmond]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060803042247/http://www.jesmond.uk.net/www.jesmond.uk.net/ Jesmond Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090306173845/http://www.whatsinjesmond.com/ What's in Jesmond]\n* [http://www.jesmondresidents.org  JRA]\n{{T&W places}}\n\n[[Category:Student quarters]]\n[[Category:Districts of Newcastle upon Tyne|Jesmond (North and South)]]\n[[Category:Wards of Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Northumbria University]]\n[[Category:Marian apparitions]]\n", "name_user": "147.147.122.32", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAreas of Jesmond:Factual)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesmond"}
{"title_page": "Members of the Australian Senate, 1959\u20131962", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Quote box|quote ='''Senate composition at 1 July 1959''' <br />'''[[Government of Australia|Government]] (32)''' - (1 seat majority) <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Liberal}}|border=darkgray}} [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] (25) <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|National}}|border=darkgray}} [[National Party of Australia|Country Party]] (7) <br />\n<br />\n'''[[Opposition (Australia)|Opposition]] (26)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Labor}}|border=darkgray}} [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (26) <br />\n<br />\n'''[[Crossbencher|Crossbench]] (2)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Democratic Labor}}|border=darkgray}}  [[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|DLP]] (2) \n| width = 265px| align=}}This is a list of '''members of the [[Australian Senate]]''' from 1959 to 1962.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate 1959 |url=http://biography.senate.gov.au/?search-class=DB_CustomSearch_Widget-db_customsearch_widget&widget_number=3&cs-dates-0=1959&search=Search |publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]] |access-date=21 March 2017}}</ref> Half of its members were elected at the [[1955 Australian federal election|10 December 1955 election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1956 and finishing on 30 June 1962; the other half were elected at the [[1958 Australian federal election|22 November 1958 election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1959 and finishing on 30 June 1965. The process for filling casual vacancies was complex. While senators were elected for a six-year term, people appointed to a casual vacancy only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Senator'''\n! colspan=2 | '''Party'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''End term'''\n! '''Years in Office'''\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Stan|Amour}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[New South Wales]] || 1965 || 1938\u20131965\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ken|Anderson|Ken Anderson (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || New South Wales || 1965 || 1953\u20131975\n|-\n|| {{sort|Armstrong, John|Hon. [[John Armstrong (Australian politician)|John Armstrong]]}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || New South Wales || 1962 || 1938\u20131962\n|-\n|| {{sortname|James|Arnold |James Arnold (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || New South Wales || 1965 || 1941\u20131965\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Bill|Aylett}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[Tasmania]] || 1965 || 1938\u20131965\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Archie|Benn}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]|| [[Queensland]] || 1962 || 1950\u20131968\n|-\n|| {{sortname|George|Branson}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[Western Australia]] || 1965 || 1958\u20131971\n|-\n|| {{sort|Brown, Gordon|Hon. [[Gordon Brown (Australian politician)|Gordon Brown]]}} {{efn|name=Father|[[Father of the Australian Senate|Father of the Senate]]}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || Queensland || 1965 || 1932\u20131965\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Nancy|Buttfield}} {{efn|name=Pearson}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[South Australia]] || 1962, 1965 || 1955\u20131965, 1968\u20131974\n|-\n|| {{sort|Cameron, Don|Hon. [[Don Cameron (Victorian politician)|Don Cameron]]}} || {{Aus