{"title_page": "Members of the Australian Senate, 1956\u20131959", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Quote box|quote ='''Senate composition at 1 July 1956'''\n<br />\n'''[[Government of Australia|Government]] (30)''' - (1 seat minority){{efn-lr|name=Ormonde}} <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Liberal}}|border=darkgray}} [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] (24) <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|National}}|border=darkgray}} [[National Party of Australia|Country Party]] (6) {{efn-lr|At the [[1958 Australian federal election|November 1958 election]] Country Party Senator [[Tom Drake-Brockman]] was elected to a full term from 1 July 1959 to 30 June 1965 and Liberal candidate [[George Branson]] was elected to fill the balance of the casual vacancy ending on 30 June 1959.}}<br />\n<br />\n'''[[Opposition (Australia)|Opposition]] (28)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Labor}}|border=darkgray}} [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (28) {{efn-lr|name=Ormonde|At the [[1958 Australian federal election|November 1958 election]] Labor senator [[James Ormonde (Australian politician)|James Ormonde]] was elected to a full term seat, from 1 July 1959 to 30 June 1965 and Country Party candidate [[Colin McKellar]] was elected to fill the casual vacancy ending on 30 June 1962, giving the government a majority in the Senate.}} {{efn-lr|[[Condon Byrne]] split from the Labor Party in 1957, joining the [[Queensland Labor Party]].}} <br />\n<br />\n'''[[Crossbencher|Crossbench]] (2)''' <br />\n{{Color box|{{Australian politics/party colours|Democratic Labor}}|border=darkgray}}  [[Australian Labor Party (Anti-Communist)|ALP (Anti-Communist)]]/[[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|DLP]] (2) {{efn-lr|The Australian Labor Party (Anti-Communist) changed its name to the [[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|Democratic Labour Party]] in 1957.}}<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nChanges in composition\n{{notelist-lr}}\n| width = 265px| align=}}\nThis is a list of '''members of the [[Australian Senate]]''' from 1956 to 1959.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate 1956 |url=http://biography.senate.gov.au/?search-class=DB_CustomSearch_Widget-db_customsearch_widget&widget_number=3&cs-dates-0=1956&search=Search |publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]] |access-date=21 March 2017}}</ref> Half of its members were elected at the [[1953 Australian Senate election|9 May 1953 election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1953 and finishing on 30 June 1959; the other half were elected at the [[1955 Australian federal election|10 December 1955 election]] and had terms starting on 1 July 1956 and finishing on 30 June 1962. The process for filling casual vacancies was complex. While senators were elected for a six-year term, people appointed to a casual vacancy only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Senator'''\n! colspan=2 | '''Party'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''End term'''\n! '''Years in Office'''\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Stan|Amour}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[New South Wales]] || 1959 || 1938\u20131965\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ken|Anderson|Ken Anderson (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || New South Wales || 1959 || 1953\u20131975\n|-\n|| {{sort|Armstrong, John |Hon. [[John Armstrong (Australian politician)|John Armstrong]]}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || New South Wales || 1962 || 1938\u20131962\n|-\n|| {{sortname|James|Arnold|James Arnold (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || New South Wales || 1959 || 1941\u