08 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725081044/http://www.aph.gov.au/library/handbook/historical/senate/index.htm \n |archivedate=25 July 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}\n\n{{Members of the Parliament of Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Members of the Australian Senate, 1956-1959}}\n[[Category:Members of Australian parliaments by term]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Australian Senate lists]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: six year \u2192 six-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Members_of_the_Australian_Senate,_1956%E2%80%931959"}
{"title_page": "Katie Redford", "text_new": "'''Katharine \"Katie\" Redford''' (born March 7, 1978) is an American human rights lawyer and activist who is credited with spearheading a movement to hold international companies accountable for overseas abuse in their home court jurisdictions in the Western world, and in doing so, opened up new possibilities in [[#Human Rights Law|human rights law]]. Along with her husband, Burmese human rights activist [[Ka Hsaw Wa]], she is the co-founder and US Office Director of [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International] (ERI), a non-profit group of activists, organizers, and lawyers with expertise in human rights, the environment, and corporate/government accountability.\n\nRedford is a graduate of the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] (UVA), where she received the Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights and Public Service. She is a member of the Massachusetts State Bar and served as counsel to plaintiffs in ERI's landmark case [[Doe v. Unocal]]. Redford received an [[Echoing Green]] Fellowship<ref name=\"Echoing Green\">Echoing Green website, 2005 Fellows (http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019125825/http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford |date=2008-10-19 }})</ref> in 1995 to establish ERI, and since that time has split her time between ERI's [[Thailand]] and US offices. In addition to working on ERI's litigation and teaching at the EarthRights Schools, Redford currently serves as an adjunct professor of law at both UVA<ref>University of Virginia website, Human Rights Program (http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2003_fall/humanrightsprogram.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030950/http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2003_fall/humanrightsprogram.htm |date=2016-03-04 }})</ref> and the [[Washington College of Law]] at [[American University]].<ref>Washing College of Law website, Faculty (http://www.wcl.american.edu/faculty/redford/)</ref> She has published on various issues associated with human rights and corporate accountability, in addition to co-authoring ERI reports such as ''In Our Court'', ''Shock and Law'', and ''Total Denial Continues''. In 2006, Redford was selected as an [[Ashoka: Innovators for the Public|Ashoka Global Fellow]].<ref>Ashoka Website, 2006 Fellows (http://ashoka.org/node/3710)</ref>\n\n==Human Rights Law==\nRedford introduced a simple and powerful idea into the human rights movement: that corporations can be brought to court for their role in overseas abuse. While American and European courts have customarily declined to hear cases where abuses have occurred outside their jurisdiction, Redford and her team at [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International] (ERI) broke their reluctance by uncovering legal tools and strategies that overcome the barrier of jurisdiction.\n\nIn 1994 Redford turned in a law school paper suggesting the use of an ancient federal statute to fight human rights abuses in [[Burma]], The [[Alien Torts Statute|Alien Torts Claims Act]]. The act dates back to 1789, when [[George Washington]] signed the fledgling nation's first [[Judiciary Act of 1789|Judiciary Act]]. An obscure provision in it appears to give foreigners the right to sue in federal court over violations of international law. Though the act has been used to sue individuals, it has never been used successfully to sue a corporation for human rights abuses.  Her professor gave her an A but warned that such a case would never occur. That student paper, ''\"Using the Alien Torts Claims Act: [[Unocal]] v. [[Burma]],\"'' became the basis of the groundbreaking case John Doe I, et al. v. Unocal Corp., et al.  In March 1997 it became the first case in which jurisdiction was granted over a corporation for human rights abuses overseas.   [[Unocal]] eventually settled the case out of court.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">Bloomberg News, December 14, 2004, \"Unocal Settles Rights Suit in Myanmar\" (https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/14/business/14unocal.html?_r=2&scp=1&sq=unocal+settles+burma&st=nyt&oref=slogin&oref=slogin)</ref>\n\nIn 1995 Redford received seed money from Echoing Green<ref name=\"Echoing Green\"/> to launch [http://www.earthrights.org/ EarthRights International] (ERI) with Tyler Giannini and [[Ka Hsaw Wa]]. ERI began its work with offices in [[Thailand]] and [[Washington, D.C.]], as a nonprofit organization that works at the intersection of human rights and the environment\u2014which it defines as \"earth rights\"\u2014by documenting abuses, mounting legal actions against the perpetrators of earth rights abuses, providing training for grassroots and community leaders, and launching advocacy campaigns.\n\nERI brought the case of John Doe I, et al. v. Unocal Corp., et al., to both state and federal courts in [[California]]. Most legal experts believed the case would never fly and at first it appeared they may be right. But seeing possibilities where the experts could not, Redford persevered throughout the protracted, ten-year-long legal battle. ERI had their case dismissed in 2000, fought back and won by appeal,<ref name=\"nytimes\">New York Times, September 19, 2002, \"Court Tells Unocal to Face Rights Charges\" (https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E5D91330F93AA2575AC0A9649C8B63&scp=2&sq=unocal+human+rights&st=nyt)</ref><ref>Appeal from the United States District Court for the Central District of California, Richard A. Paez and Ronald S.W. Lew, District Judges, Presiding, Argued and Submitted December 3, 2001, Filed September 18, 2002(http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/ca9/newopinions.nsf/3D534390583B882F88256C380004FE18/$file/0056603.pdf?openelement)</ref> the right to continue.\n\nAs the years passed, the case gained traction. Redford trudged forward, putting in countless hours of legal work, fundraising and research, and building coalitions with likeminded organizations such as [[Center for Constitutional Rights]]. After several years of fighting an uphill battle without losing hope, the rewards finally came, in 2004. [[Unocal]] agreed to settle the lawsuit.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\"/><ref>Environment News Service, December 17, 2004 \"Unocal Settles Out of Court With Myanmar Villagers\" (http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/dec2004/2004-12-17-02.asp)</ref> It was the first time in history that a major multinational corporation had settled a case of this type for monetary damages.\n\nIn the landmark settlement, the company agreed to compensate the Burmese villagers who sued the firm for complicity in forced labor, rape, and murder. By combining human rights law and environmental law, ERI had come up with a new and untested strategy that succeeded where older solutions had failed.  Their story was documented in the 2006 documentary film ''[[Total Denial]]''.\n\nEqually importantly, the [[Unocal]] case set a strong legal precedent. As a result of ERI's efforts, a series of rulings in the California Federal Court<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> established that a corporation can indeed be held liable in U.S. courts for encouraging human rights violations by a foreign government. This put corporations on notice and forced them to consider their actions abroad.\nUnocal attempted to recover the damages from its insurer.<ref>EarthRights International website, Legal Feature (http://www.earthrights.org/legalfeature/us_court_calls_abuses_committed_in_construction_of_chevrons_pipeline_military_terrorism.html)</ref> The insurer did not pay, but instead reviewed its policies to ensure that it would not be liable to cover damages for murder, rape, and torture. Then banks began reviewing their liability for funding the projects. Thus, liability for abuse becomes an important business issue, not merely the preoccupation of a few activists.\n\nToday Redford and her team at ERI use the [[Unocal]] case as a model to fight corporate misbehavior. Working in partnership with other legal organizations and private lawyers, they seeks to remedy abuses of earth rights\u2014all over the world. For instance, Redford and ERI are currently working with the victims of human rights abuses associated with the activities of the oil company [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] in [[Nigeria]] to fight the [[Bowoto v. Chevron Corp.|case]] against [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] in federal court in [[San Francisco]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on March 7, 1968, she was raised in [[Wellesley, MA]] and in 1986 she graduated from [[Wellesley High School]].  Redford attended [[Colgate University]]<ref>The Colgate Scene, November 1996 Issue \"Colgate's Earthrights Crusader\" (http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/nov1996/redford.html)</ref> in rural upstate New York where she was a member of the swimming and diving teams.  She found spending six hours a day in the water too much and later quit and began playing rugby, a Division I sport at Colgate.\n\nAfter graduating from college in 1990, Redford signed on with the [[WorldTeach]] program and found herself teaching English in a village on the Thai-Burmese border.\n\nOn her summer break she visited a Thai refugee camp and lived with a family who had fled the Burmese military dictatorship. There she taught English in a bamboo hut. Along the border, bombs would explode from battles between the military and its opposition. Every day brought new streams of refugees, with tales of rape, torture, killing, and forced labor.\n\nShe headed home and in the fall of 1992, Redford enrolled at the [[University of Virginia Law School]] to study human rights and environmental law but as soon as school was out for the summer, she left again for Thailand.  This time she went as an intern for [[Human Rights Watch]], documenting abuses associated with forced labor. She returned to the same refugee camp to live with the same Burmese family she had stayed with the summer before. The father, a pro-democracy activist, arranged to sneak her into [[Burma]]. (The military, which staged a coup in 1988, officially changed the country's name to [[Myanmar]] the following year.)\n\nThat year Redford met [[Ka Hsaw Wa]], a [[Karen people|Karen]] student activist who had fled to the jungle and was collecting villagers' tales of abuse under the junta.  She spent three weeks with him and a small group paddling up the [[Salween River]], stopping at villages near the front lines of fighting between the military and the opposition and gathering villagers' stories.\n\nThe summer after their second year, she and two classmates got a fellowship to look at the [[World Bank]]'s presence in [[Thailand]] and [[Burma]]. But Ka Hsaw Wa told them the real story was the [[Yadana Pipeline]], being built by French company [[Total S.A.]] and [[Unocal]], which is headquartered in [[El Segundo, CA]]. The 39-mile natural gas line cuts through the Burmese jungle to the Thai border.\n\nHer third year, she did an independent research project on the [[Alien Torts Claims Act]] and Unocal's role in the Burmese pipeline, the paper that earned her an A. She also wrote a grant proposal to start [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International], a nonprofit human rights organization. The day after she took the bar examination, in 1995, she returned to [[Thailand]] to live and run the newly formed group with Ka Hsaw Wa and a fellow law school graduate.\n\nIn November 1996, Redford and [[Ka Hsaw Wa]] were married in a Thai village; they honeymooned in [[Phuket Province|Phuket]]. The following October, she filed [[Doe v. Unocal]], and in March 1997 it became the first case in which jurisdiction was granted over a corporation for human rights abuses overseas. This case was documented in the 2006 film ''[[Total Denial]]''.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.earthrights.org/ EarthRights International]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090715024320/http://www.earthrights.org/site_blurbs/doe_v._unocal_case_history.html \"Doe v. Unocal Case History\", EarthRights International, January 30, 2006]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/shows/345/video.html Now on PBS, Episode 345, November 19, 2007 (video)]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/transcript/345.html Now on PBS, Episode 345, November 19, 2007 (transcript)]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/politics/alientortdebate.html \"Debating the Alien Tort Claims Act\", Now on PBS, January 9, 2004]\n* [http://ccrjustice.org/newsroom/press-releases/historic-advance-universal-human-rights%3A-unocal-compensate-burmese-villagers \"Historic Advance for Universal Human Rights: Unocal to Compensate Burmese Villagers\", Center for Constitutional Rights]\n* [http://ccrjustice.org/newsroom/press-releases/court-orders-unocal-stand-trial-abuses-burma \"Court Orders Unocal to Stand Trial for Abuses in Burma\", Center for Constitutional Rights]\n* [http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/ca9/newopinions.nsf/3D534390583B882F88256C380004FE18/$file/0056603.pdf?openelement \"Appeal from the United States District Court for the Central District of California\", Richard A. Paez and Ronald S.W. Lew, District Judges, Presiding, Argued and Submitted December 3, 2001, Filed September 18, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061001230830/http://www.theconnection.org/shows/2003/09/20030930_b_main.asp The Connection from WBUR and NPR, September 30, 2003]\n* [https://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2003/10/22/katie_redfords_pipe_dream/ Bella English, \"Katie Redford's pipe dream\", Boston Globe, October 22, 2003]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080828033058/http://www.bebold.org/The_Book/Chapter_One/Slaying_Giants_with_Torts_94.html \"Slaying Giants with Torts\", Be Bold]\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2007/10/12/oil_giant_chevron_urged_to_cut \"Oil Giant Chevron Urged to Cut Ties with Burmese Military Junta\", Democracy Now, October 12, 2007]\n* [http://abcnewsstore.go.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/DSIProductDisplay?catalogId=11002&storeId=20051&productId=2004212&langId=-1&categoryId=100041 \"The Giant Slayers\", ABC News Nightline, May 5, 2005]\n* [http://www.chicagopublicradio.org/audio_library/wv_rajan07.asp#24 \"Burma\u2014Ending Forced Labor on Oil Pipelines\", Chicago Public Radio - Worldview, January 24, 2007]\n* [http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2005_spr/ps_redford.htm \"Redford Appeals to Law Students to Fight Human Rights Abuses\" University of Virginia Law School, Conference on Public Service and the Law, February 18, 2005]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/14/business/14unocal.html?r=2&scp=1&sq=unocal+settles+burma&st=nyt&oref=slogin&oref=slogin \"Unocal Settles Rights Suit in Myanmar\", Bloomberg News, December 14, 2004]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E5D91330F93AA2575AC0A9649C8B63&scp=2&sq=unocal+human+rights&st=nyt \"Court Tells Unocal to Face Rights Charges\", New York Times, September 19, 2002]\n* [http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/nov1996/redford.html \"Colgate's Earthrights Crusader\" The Colgate Scene, November 1996 Issue]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081019125825/http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford Echoing Green Fellowships]\n* [http://ashoka.org/node/3710 Ashoka Global Fellowships]\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070923203221/http://www.totaldenialfilm.com/ \"Total Denial\", Documentary, 2006]\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redford, Katie}}\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wellesley High School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Colgate University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Katharine \"Katie\" Redford''' (born March 7, 1978) is an American human rights lawyer and activist who is credited with spearheading a movement to hold international companies accountable for overseas abuse in their home court jurisdictions in the Western world, and in doing so, opened up new possibilities in [[#Human Rights Law|human rights law]]. Along with her husband, Burmese human rights activist [[Ka Hsaw Wa]], she is the co-founder and US Office Director of [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International] (ERI), a non-profit group of activists, organizers, and lawyers with expertise in human rights, the environment, and corporate/government accountability.\n\nRedford is a graduate of the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] (UVA), where she received the Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights and Public Service. She is a member of the Massachusetts State Bar and served as counsel to plaintiffs in ERI's landmark case [[Doe v. Unocal]]. Redford received an  Echoing Green Fellowship<ref name=\"Echoing Green\">Echoing Green website, 2005 Fellows (http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019125825/http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford |date=2008-10-19 }})</ref> in 1995 to establish ERI, and since that time has split her time between ERI's [[Thailand]] and US offices. In addition to working on ERI's litigation and teaching at the EarthRights Schools, Redford currently serves as an adjunct professor of law at both UVA<ref>University of Virginia website, Human Rights Program (http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2003_fall/humanrightsprogram.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030950/http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2003_fall/humanrightsprogram.htm |date=2016-03-04 }})</ref> and the [[Washington College of Law]] at [[American University]].<ref>Washing College of Law website, Faculty (http://www.wcl.american.edu/faculty/redford/)</ref> She has published on various issues associated with human rights and corporate accountability, in addition to co-authoring ERI reports such as ''In Our Court'', ''Shock and Law'', and ''Total Denial Continues''. In 2006, Redford was selected as an [[Ashoka: Innovators for the Public|Ashoka Global Fellow]].<ref>Ashoka Website, 2006 Fellows (http://ashoka.org/node/3710)</ref>\n\n==Human Rights Law==\nRedford introduced a simple and powerful idea into the human rights movement: that corporations can be brought to court for their role in overseas abuse. While American and European courts have customarily declined to hear cases where abuses have occurred outside their jurisdiction, Redford and her team at [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International] (ERI) broke their reluctance by uncovering legal tools and strategies that overcome the barrier of jurisdiction.\n\nIn 1994 Redford turned in a law school paper suggesting the use of an ancient federal statute to fight human rights abuses in [[Burma]], The [[Alien Torts Statute|Alien Torts Claims Act]]. The act dates back to 1789, when [[George Washington]] signed the fledgling nation's first [[Judiciary Act of 1789|Judiciary Act]]. An obscure provision in it appears to give foreigners the right to sue in federal court over violations of international law. Though the act has been used to sue individuals, it has never been used successfully to sue a corporation for human rights abuses.  Her professor gave her an A but warned that such a case would never occur. That student paper, ''\"Using the Alien Torts Claims Act: [[Unocal]] v. [[Burma]],\"'' became the basis of the groundbreaking case John Doe I, et al. v. Unocal Corp., et al.  In March 1997 it became the first case in which jurisdiction was granted over a corporation for human rights abuses overseas.   [[Unocal]] eventually settled the case out of court.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">Bloomberg News, December 14, 2004, \"Unocal Settles Rights Suit in Myanmar\" (https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/14/business/14unocal.html?_r=2&scp=1&sq=unocal+settles+burma&st=nyt&oref=slogin&oref=slogin)</ref>\n\nIn 1995 Redford received seed money from Echoing Green<ref name=\"Echoing Green\"/> to launch [http://www.earthrights.org/ EarthRights International] (ERI) with Tyler Giannini and [[Ka Hsaw Wa]]. ERI began its work with offices in [[Thailand]] and [[Washington, D.C.]], as a nonprofit organization that works at the intersection of human rights and the environment\u2014which it defines as \"earth rights\"\u2014by documenting abuses, mounting legal actions against the perpetrators of earth rights abuses, providing training for grassroots and community leaders, and launching advocacy campaigns.\n\nERI brought the case of John Doe I, et al. v. Unocal Corp., et al., to both state and federal courts in [[California]]. Most legal experts believed the case would never fly and at first it appeared they may be right. But seeing possibilities where the experts could not, Redford persevered throughout the protracted, ten-year-long legal battle. ERI had their case dismissed in 2000, fought back and won by appeal,<ref name=\"nytimes\">New York Times, September 19, 2002, \"Court Tells Unocal to Face Rights Charges\" (https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E5D91330F93AA2575AC0A9649C8B63&scp=2&sq=unocal+human+rights&st=nyt)</ref><ref>Appeal from the United States District Court for the Central District of California, Richard A. Paez and Ronald S.W. Lew, District Judges, Presiding, Argued and Submitted December 3, 2001, Filed September 18, 2002(http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/ca9/newopinions.nsf/3D534390583B882F88256C380004FE18/$file/0056603.pdf?openelement)</ref> the right to continue.\n\nAs the years passed, the case gained traction. Redford trudged forward, putting in countless hours of legal work, fundraising and research, and building coalitions with likeminded organizations such as [[Center for Constitutional Rights]]. After several years of fighting an uphill battle without losing hope, the rewards finally came, in 2004. [[Unocal]] agreed to settle the lawsuit.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\"/><ref>Environment News Service, December 17, 2004 \"Unocal Settles Out of Court With Myanmar Villagers\" (http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/dec2004/2004-12-17-02.asp)</ref> It was the first time in history that a major multinational corporation had settled a case of this type for monetary damages.\n\nIn the landmark settlement, the company agreed to compensate the Burmese villagers who sued the firm for complicity in forced labor, rape, and murder. By combining human rights law and environmental law, ERI had come up with a new and untested strategy that succeeded where older solutions had failed.  Their story was documented in the 2006 documentary film ''[[Total Denial]]''.\n\nEqually importantly, the [[Unocal]] case set a strong legal precedent. As a result of ERI's efforts, a series of rulings in the California Federal Court<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> established that a corporation can indeed be held liable in U.S. courts for encouraging human rights violations by a foreign government. This put corporations on notice and forced them to consider their actions abroad.\nUnocal attempted to recover the damages from its insurer.<ref>EarthRights International website, Legal Feature (http://www.earthrights.org/legalfeature/us_court_calls_abuses_committed_in_construction_of_chevrons_pipeline_military_terrorism.html)</ref> The insurer did not pay, but instead reviewed its policies to ensure that it would not be liable to cover damages for murder, rape, and torture. Then banks began reviewing their liability for funding the projects. Thus, liability for abuse becomes an important business issue, not merely the preoccupation of a few activists.\n\nToday Redford and her team at ERI use the [[Unocal]] case as a model to fight corporate misbehavior. Working in partnership with other legal organizations and private lawyers, they seeks to remedy abuses of earth rights\u2014all over the world. For instance, Redford and ERI are currently working with the victims of human rights abuses associated with the activities of the oil company [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] in [[Nigeria]] to fight the [[Bowoto v. Chevron Corp.|case]] against [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] in federal court in [[San Francisco]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on March 7, 1968, she was raised in [[Wellesley, MA]] and in 1986 she graduated from [[Wellesley High School]].  Redford attended [[Colgate University]]<ref>The Colgate Scene, November 1996 Issue \"Colgate's Earthrights Crusader\" (http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/nov1996/redford.html)</ref> in rural upstate New York where she was a member of the swimming and diving teams.  She found spending six hours a day in the water too much and later quit and began playing rugby, a Division I sport at Colgate.\n\nAfter graduating from college in 1990, Redford signed on with the [[WorldTeach]] program and found herself teaching English in a village on the Thai-Burmese border.\n\nOn her summer break she visited a Thai refugee camp and lived with a family who had fled the Burmese military dictatorship. There she taught English in a bamboo hut. Along the border, bombs would explode from battles between the military and its opposition. Every day brought new streams of refugees, with tales of rape, torture, killing, and forced labor.\n\nShe headed home and in the fall of 1992, Redford enrolled at the [[University of Virginia Law School]] to study human rights and environmental law but as soon as school was out for the summer, she left again for Thailand.  This time she went as an intern for [[Human Rights Watch]], documenting abuses associated with forced labor. She returned to the same refugee camp to live with the same Burmese family she had stayed with the summer before. The father, a pro-democracy activist, arranged to sneak her into [[Burma]]. (The military, which staged a coup in 1988, officially changed the country's name to [[Myanmar]] the following year.)\n\nThat year Redford met [[Ka Hsaw Wa]], a [[Karen people|Karen]] student activist who had fled to the jungle and was collecting villagers' tales of abuse under the junta.  She spent three weeks with him and a small group paddling up the [[Salween River]], stopping at villages near the front lines of fighting between the military and the opposition and gathering villagers' stories.\n\nThe summer after their second year, she and two classmates got a fellowship to look at the [[World Bank]]'s presence in [[Thailand]] and [[Burma]]. But Ka Hsaw Wa told them the real story was the [[Yadana Pipeline]], being built by French company [[Total S.A.]] and [[Unocal]], which is headquartered in [[El Segundo, CA]]. The 39-mile natural gas line cuts through the Burmese jungle to the Thai border.\n\nHer third year, she did an independent research project on the [[Alien Torts Claims Act]] and Unocal's role in the Burmese pipeline, the paper that earned her an A. She also wrote a grant proposal to start [http://www.earthrights.org EarthRights International], a nonprofit human rights organization. The day after she took the bar examination, in 1995, she returned to [[Thailand]] to live and run the newly formed group with Ka Hsaw Wa and a fellow law school graduate.\n\nIn November 1996, Redford and [[Ka Hsaw Wa]] were married in a Thai village; they honeymooned in [[Phuket Province|Phuket]]. The following October, she filed [[Doe v. Unocal]], and in March 1997 it became the first case in which jurisdiction was granted over a corporation for human rights abuses overseas. This case was documented in the 2006 film ''[[Total Denial]]''.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.earthrights.org/ EarthRights International]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090715024320/http://www.earthrights.org/site_blurbs/doe_v._unocal_case_history.html \"Doe v. Unocal Case History\", EarthRights International, January 30, 2006]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/shows/345/video.html Now on PBS, Episode 345, November 19, 2007 (video)]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/transcript/345.html Now on PBS, Episode 345, November 19, 2007 (transcript)]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/politics/alientortdebate.html \"Debating the Alien Tort Claims Act\", Now on PBS, January 9, 2004]\n* [http://ccrjustice.org/newsroom/press-releases/historic-advance-universal-human-rights%3A-unocal-compensate-burmese-villagers \"Historic Advance for Universal Human Rights: Unocal to Compensate Burmese Villagers\", Center for Constitutional Rights]\n* [http://ccrjustice.org/newsroom/press-releases/court-orders-unocal-stand-trial-abuses-burma \"Court Orders Unocal to Stand Trial for Abuses in Burma\", Center for Constitutional Rights]\n* [http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/ca9/newopinions.nsf/3D534390583B882F88256C380004FE18/$file/0056603.pdf?openelement \"Appeal from the United States District Court for the Central District of California\", Richard A. Paez and Ronald S.W. Lew, District Judges, Presiding, Argued and Submitted December 3, 2001, Filed September 18, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061001230830/http://www.theconnection.org/shows/2003/09/20030930_b_main.asp The Connection from WBUR and NPR, September 30, 2003]\n* [https://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2003/10/22/katie_redfords_pipe_dream/ Bella English, \"Katie Redford's pipe dream\", Boston Globe, October 22, 2003]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080828033058/http://www.bebold.org/The_Book/Chapter_One/Slaying_Giants_with_Torts_94.html \"Slaying Giants with Torts\", Be Bold]\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2007/10/12/oil_giant_chevron_urged_to_cut \"Oil Giant Chevron Urged to Cut Ties with Burmese Military Junta\", Democracy Now, October 12, 2007]\n* [http://abcnewsstore.go.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/DSIProductDisplay?catalogId=11002&storeId=20051&productId=2004212&langId=-1&categoryId=100041 \"The Giant Slayers\", ABC News Nightline, May 5, 2005]\n* [http://www.chicagopublicradio.org/audio_library/wv_rajan07.asp#24 \"Burma\u2014Ending Forced Labor on Oil Pipelines\", Chicago Public Radio - Worldview, January 24, 2007]\n* [http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2005_spr/ps_redford.htm \"Redford Appeals to Law Students to Fight Human Rights Abuses\" University of Virginia Law School, Conference on Public Service and the Law, February 18, 2005]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/14/business/14unocal.html?r=2&scp=1&sq=unocal+settles+burma&st=nyt&oref=slogin&oref=slogin \"Unocal Settles Rights Suit in Myanmar\", Bloomberg News, December 14, 2004]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E5D91330F93AA2575AC0A9649C8B63&scp=2&sq=unocal+human+rights&st=nyt \"Court Tells Unocal to Face Rights Charges\", New York Times, September 19, 2002]\n* [http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/nov1996/redford.html \"Colgate's Earthrights Crusader\" The Colgate Scene, November 1996 Issue]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081019125825/http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/katherine-redford Echoing Green Fellowships]\n* [http://ashoka.org/node/3710 Ashoka Global Fellowships]\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070923203221/http://www.totaldenialfilm.com/ \"Total Denial\", Documentary, 2006]\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redford, Katie}}\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wellesley High School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Colgate University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "RayScript", "label": "safe", "comment": "echoing green link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katie_Redford"}
{"title_page": "Amapiano", "text_new": "{{short description|genre of Electronic dance music}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Amapiano\n| bgcolor = Indigo\n| color = White\n| stylistic_origins = {{hlist|[[Deep house]] | [[kwaito]] | [[jazz]] | [[lounge music|lounge]]}}\n| cultural_origins = Mid-2010s [[Gauteng]], South Africa\n| instruments = {{hlist|[[Piano]]|[[drums]]|[[synthesizer]]}}\n| local_scenes = {{hlist|[[Pretoria]]|[[Mamelodi]]|[[Atteridgeville]]|[[Alexandra]]|[[Soweto]]|[[Katlehong]]|[[KwaThema]]}}\n| derivatives = {{hlist|[[House music|House]]|[[kwaito]]}}\n| subgenres = \n| fusiongenres = \n}}\n\n'''Amapiano''' is a genre of [[House (music)|house]] music that emerged in [[South Africa]] in 2016. Amapiano is a sophisticated hybrid of [[deep house]], [[jazz]] and [[Lounge music|lounge]] music characterized by synths, airy pads and wide basslines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/amapiano-best-songs-2019/|title=The 10 Best Amapiano Songs of 2019|date=2019-12-17|website=OkayAfrica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> It is distinguished by high pitched piano melodies, Kwaito basslines, low tempo 90s South African house rhythms and [[Percussion notation|percussions]] from another local subgenre of house known as [[Music of South Africa|Bacardi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prospect.zone/en/new-age-house-music-the-rise-of-amapiano/|title=New age house music: the rise of \u201camapiano\u201d|last=Prspct|date=2018-11-21|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nAlthough it is known the genre gained popularity in [[Gauteng]], there is a lot of ambiguity in terms of where the Amapiano style of music originates, with various accounts of the musical style in [[Johannesburg]] townships, [[Soweto]], [[Alexandra, Gauteng|Alexandra]], [[Vosloorus]] and [[Katlehong]] where it is most common. Because of the genre's similarities with Barcadi, some people assert the genre began in the [[Pretoria]] area with DJ Mojava which was made popular by Pretoria taxi drivers by the likes of the late Wallash(CBF) & Soshanguve Universal Taxi Rank\n,and has been an on going debate about the origin of Amapiano.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/lifestyle/2019-07-07-amapiano-a-township-sound-with-staying-power/|title=Amapiano: a township sound with staying power|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Joyce |first1=Liam Karabo |title=Meet the vocalist featured on the biggest amapiano tracks |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/music/local/meet-the-vocalist-featured-on-the-biggest-amapiano-tracks-35610310 |publisher=Independent Online |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sundayworld/lifestyle/2019-05-28-amapiano-a-new-movement-period/|title=Amapiano a new movement... Period|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n\nVarious accounts as to who formed the popular genre make it impossible to accurately pinpoint its origins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2019-10-02/charting-the-meteoric-rise-of-south-africas-amapiano/|title=Charting the Meteoric Rise of South Africa\u2019s AmaPiano|date=2019-10-02|website=Spotify|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Popularity ==\nInitially, Amapiano<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zamusic.org/tag/amapiano/|title=Amapiano Songs, Albums And Mixtapes|last=|first=|date=|website=ZAMUSIC.ORG|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> was a confined success in the townships, playing in popular pubs and taverns around Gauteng. The sound itself was underground music, being shared around using messaging apps, more commonly [[WhatsApp]], before it became mainstream being recognised by streaming services such as [[Deezer]], [[Spotify]], [[Apple Music]]. The genre was further popularised by DJs who would transform popular music hits and incorporating the jazzy low-tempo into those tracks, including DJ Ganyani, Sun-El Musician, [[DJ Maphorisa]] and [[Kabza De Small]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopza.com/dj-maphorisa-kabza-de-small-scorpion-kings-live-at-sun-arena-11-april/|title= Dj Maphorisa & Kabza De Small \u2013 Scorpion Kings Live at Sun Arena 11 April|website=Hiphopza|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nAmapiano is getting more mainstream across Africa as of 2020, there are several dedicated charts now, more playlists on digital platforms not just by South Africans alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinamag.com/songs/amapiano/|title=Amapiano 2020: Download New Amapiano Mix,Songs,Music Video Fakaza|website=TINAMAG.COM|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zkhiphani.co.za/2019-the-year-of-the-yanos-how-amapiano-blow-up/|title=2019 The Year Of The Yanos, How Amapiano Blow up|last=Machaieie|first=Mario|date=2019-10-21|website=Online Youth Magazine {{!}} Zkhiphani.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Amapiano |title=Top Amapiano Songs 2020 |url=https://www.amapiano.org/download-mp3/top-10-list-of-amapiano-tracks-songs-2019-hottest/ |website=Amapiano.Org |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sound is filled with some melodious piano tunes coupled with gong gong sound making it up to what is called \u201dAmapiano\u201d. Some DJs and producers do mix it up with [[Gqom]].\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn January 2019, German-born American-based DJ Lars Behrenroth criticized the genre and its artists on [[Twitter]].\n{{Quote|text=\u201cFinally checked it out for the first time and all i can say is Amapiano & Godf#$! of Deep House = same WhatsApp group\u2026 what a snoozefest..eeeekkk\u201d.|sign=Lars Behrenroth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2019-01-28-these-are-black-children-trying-to-eat-prince-kaybee-joins-amapiano-debate/&grqid=HJ-Ds6Bg&s=1&hl=en-ZA|title=Prince kaybee defends amapiano after Lars Behrenroth throws shade|date=2019-01-28|publisher=timeslive.co.za|accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref>}}\n\nThe tweet caused a major uproar of many fans of the genre. His comment also prompted several artists such as [[Black Coffee (DJ)|Black Coffee]], [[Zakes Bantwini]], Kid Fonque, [[Busiswa]] and [[Cassper Nyovest]] to defend the genre and laughed off Lars' criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/Entertainment/more-celebs-defend-amapiano-music-20190122|title=MORE CELEBS DEFEND AMAPIANO MUSIC|website=DailySun|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=\u201cI am a fan of Kwaito, Gqom, and Amapiano. I am not ashamed. I\u2019m a House head but these genres are pure South African and need to be supported by every South African,\u201d|sign=Zakes Bantwini|source=}}\n\nPrince Kaybee also took to Twitter to slam Lars's comment and told him to \"leave us and our music alone\".{{Quote|text=South Africans shouldn\u2019t let caucasian house music DJs talk bad about a proudly black pioneered sound like amapiano. Protect what's yours, with this mentality we are far from exporting music!These are black children trying to eat, bro. Let them shine! If you don\u2019t like it shut up and move on, don\u2019t say anything negative to try and slow down the growth of a proudly South African genre.\"|sign=Prince Kaybee|source=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2019-01-28-these-are-black-children-trying-to-eat-prince-kaybee-joins-amapiano-debate/|title=These are black children trying to eat: Prince Kaybee joins amapiano debate|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Electronic dance music genres]] \n[[Category:South African culture]] \n[[Category:House music genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|genre of Electronic dance music}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Amapiano\n| bgcolor = Indigo\n| color = White\n| stylistic_origins = {{hlist|[[Deep house]] | [[kwaito]] | [[jazz]] | [[lounge music|lounge]]}}\n| cultural_origins = Mid-2010s [[Gauteng]], South Africa\n| instruments = {{hlist|[[Piano]]|[[drums]]|[[synthesizer]]}}\n| local_scenes = {{hlist|[[Pretoria]]|[[Mamelodi]]|[[Atteridgeville]]|[[Alexandra]]|[[Soweto]]|[[Katlehong]]|[[KwaThema]]}}\n| derivatives = {{hlist|[[House music|House]]|[[kwaito]]}}\n| subgenres = \n| fusiongenres = \n}}\n\n'''Amapiano''' is a genre of [[House (music)|house]] music that emerged in [[South Africa]] in 2016. Amapiano is a sophisticated hybrid of [[deep house]], [[jazz]] and [[Lounge music|lounge]] music characterized by synths, airy pads and wide basslines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/amapiano-best-songs-2019/|title=The 10 Best Amapiano Songs of 2019|date=2019-12-17|website=OkayAfrica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> It is distinguished by high pitched piano melodies, Kwaito basslines, low tempo 90s South African house rhythms and [[Percussion notation|percussions]] from another local subgenre of house known as [[Music of South Africa|Bacardi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prospect.zone/en/new-age-house-music-the-rise-of-amapiano/|title=New age house music: the rise of \u201camapiano\u201d|last=Prspct|date=2018-11-21|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nAlthough it is known the genre gained popularity in [[Gauteng]], there is a lot of ambiguity in terms of where the Amapiano style of music originates, with various accounts of the musical style in [[Johannesburg]] townships, [[Soweto]], [[Alexandra, Gauteng|Alexandra]], [[Vosloorus]] and [[Katlehong]] where it is most common. Because of the genre's similarities with Barcadi, some people assert the genre began in the [[Pretoria]] area with DJ Mojava which was made popular by Pretoria taxi drivers by the likes of the late Wallash(CBF) & Soshanguve Universal Taxi Rank\n,and has been an on going debate about the origin of Amapiano.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/lifestyle/2019-07-07-amapiano-a-township-sound-with-staying-power/|title=Amapiano: a township sound with staying power|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Joyce |first1=Liam Karabo |title=Meet the vocalist featured on the biggest amapiano tracks |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/music/local/meet-the-vocalist-featured-on-the-biggest-amapiano-tracks-35610310 |publisher=Independent Online |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sundayworld/lifestyle/2019-05-28-amapiano-a-new-movement-period/|title=Amapiano a new movement... Period|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n\nVarious accounts as to who formed the popular genre make it impossible to accurately pinpoint its origins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2019-10-02/charting-the-meteoric-rise-of-south-africas-amapiano/|title=Charting the Meteoric Rise of South Africa\u2019s AmaPiano|date=2019-10-02|website=Spotify|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Popularity ==\nInitially, Amapiano<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zamusic.org/tag/amapiano/|title=Amapiano Songs, Albums And Mixtapes|last=|first=|date=|website=ZAMUSIC.ORG|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> was a confined success in the townships, playing in popular pubs and taverns around Gauteng. The sound itself was underground music, being shared around using messaging apps, more commonly [[WhatsApp]], before it became mainstream being recognised by streaming services such as [[Deezer]], [[Spotify]], [[Apple Music]]. The genre was further popularised by DJ's who would transform popular music hits and incorporating the jazzy low-tempo into those tracks, including DJ Ganyani, Sun-El Musician, [[DJ Maphorisa]] and [[Kabza De Small]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopza.com/dj-maphorisa-kabza-de-small-scorpion-kings-live-at-sun-arena-11-april/|title= Dj Maphorisa & Kabza De Small \u2013 Scorpion Kings Live at Sun Arena 11 April|website=Hiphopza|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nAmapiano is getting more mainstream across Africa as of 2020, there are several dedicated charts now, more playlists on digital platforms not just by South Africans alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinamag.com/songs/amapiano/|title=Amapiano 2020: Download New Amapiano Mix,Songs,Music Video Fakaza|website=TINAMAG.COM|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zkhiphani.co.za/2019-the-year-of-the-yanos-how-amapiano-blow-up/|title=2019 The Year Of The Yanos, How Amapiano Blow up|last=Machaieie|first=Mario|date=2019-10-21|website=Online Youth Magazine {{!}} Zkhiphani.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Amapiano |title=Top Amapiano Songs 2020 |url=https://www.amapiano.org/download-mp3/top-10-list-of-amapiano-tracks-songs-2019-hottest/ |website=Amapiano.Org |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sound is filled with some melodious piano tunes coupled with gong gong sound making it up to what is called \u201dAmapiano\u201d. Some DJ\u2019s and producers do mix it up with [[Gqom]].\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn January 2019, German-born American-based DJ Lars Behrenroth criticized the genre and its artists on [[Twitter]].\n{{Quote|text=\u201cFinally checked it out for the first time and all i can say is Amapiano & Godf#$! of Deep House = same WhatsApp group\u2026 what a snoozefest..eeeekkk\u201d.|sign=Lars Behrenroth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2019-01-28-these-are-black-children-trying-to-eat-prince-kaybee-joins-amapiano-debate/&grqid=HJ-Ds6Bg&s=1&hl=en-ZA|title=Prince kaybee defends amapiano after Lars Behrenroth throws shade|date=2019-01-28|publisher=timeslive.co.za|accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref>}}\n\nThe tweet caused a major uproar of many fans of the genre. His comment also prompted several artists such as [[Black Coffee (DJ)|Black Coffee]], [[Zakes Bantwini]], Kid Fonque, [[Busiswa]] and [[Cassper Nyovest]] to defend the genre and laughed off Lars' criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/Entertainment/more-celebs-defend-amapiano-music-20190122|title=MORE CELEBS DEFEND AMAPIANO MUSIC|website=DailySun|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=\u201cI am a fan of Kwaito, Gqom, and Amapiano. I am not ashamed. I\u2019m a House head but these genres are pure South African and need to be supported by every South African,\u201d|sign=Zakes Bantwini|source=}}\n\nPrince Kaybee also took to Twitter to slam Lars's comment and told him to \"leave us and our music alone\".{{Quote|text=South Africans shouldn\u2019t let caucasian house music DJs talk bad about a proudly black pioneered sound like amapiano. Protect what's yours, with this mentality we are far from exporting music!These are black children trying to eat, bro. Let them shine! If you don\u2019t like it shut up and move on, don\u2019t say anything negative to try and slow down the growth of a proudly South African genre.\"|sign=Prince Kaybee|source=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/tshisa-live/tshisa-live/2019-01-28-these-are-black-children-trying-to-eat-prince-kaybee-joins-amapiano-debate/|title=These are black children trying to eat: Prince Kaybee joins amapiano debate|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Electronic dance music genres]] \n[[Category:South African culture]] \n[[Category:House music genres]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amapiano"}
{"title_page": "Allison Jolly", "text_new": "{{short description|American sailor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Allison Jolly\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Allison Blair Jolly \n| birth_date = {{birth-date and age|August 4, 1956}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], U.S.\n| headercolor = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Women's [[sailing (sport)|sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | [[Sailing at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 470 Female|470 class]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Allison Blair Jolly ''' (born August 4, 1956) is an [[United States|American]] [[sailor]] and Olympic champion. Born in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], Jolly began sailing at the age of 10 and attended the [[Florida State University]] where she won the National Collegiate sailing championships in 1975 and 1976. In 1976 she placed second in the European women's championship, and also took second place in the Timmy Angsten Regatta. In 1977, at the age of 20, she became the youngest woman ever to win the Yachtswoman of the Year Award from the [[New York Yacht Club]], \"considered the top prize in yachting.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Miss Jolly, North Capture Top Awards in Yachting |first=John |last=Radosta |work=The New York Times |date=March 2, 1977 |page=41}}</ref>\n\nAfter college, Jolly worked as a [[computer programmer]] in [[Valencia, California]] to support her sailing.  She bought her first boat with $8,000 that she and her husband had saved for a [[down payment]] on a house.<ref>{{cite news |title=It Was No Breeze for Olympic Skippers |first=Barbara |last=Lloyd |work=The New York Times |date=August 9, 1988 |page=B8}}</ref>  Her husband, Mark Elliot, also worked as a computer programmer and raced as a sailor.<ref name = \"nobreak\">{{cite news |title=After Howling Winds of Pusan Bay, Gold Medal-Winning Sailor Gets No Break |first=Angus |last=Phillips |work=The Washington Post |date=October 12, 1988 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Jolly and her sailing partner [[Lynne Jewell]] entered the Olympic trials for the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].  Despite a poor start in the qualifiers, the two rose to the top and won a spot.<ref>{{cite news |title=Close Match in Olympic Trials |first=Barbara |last=Lloyd |work=The New York Times |page=S10 |date=July 17, 1988}}</ref>  After qualifying, Jolly was \"considered a long shot\" in the event.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yachting |work=The New York Times |date=September 11, 1988 |page=OL16}}</ref>  In the first race of the games, Jolly and Jewell placed third,<ref>{{cite news |title=Clear Sailing as the Regatta Gets Going; Yachting |work=The New York Times |first=George |last=Vecsey |date=September 21, 1988 |page=A14}}</ref> and in the next race, their boat capsized twice, but the two managed to stay in contention.<ref>{{cite news |title=McClain, McConnell Shoot U.S. Women Into Quarterfinals |work=The Washington Post |date=September 25, 1988 |page=D14}}</ref> After finishing strong in their remaining races, the two won the gold medal in the ''[[470 (dinghy)|470 Class]]'' with a convincing lead over the competition, causing the ''Washington Post'' to write that they \"blew the competition out of the water.\"<ref name = \"nobreak\"/><ref name=db-ol1988-sailing>{{cite web|url=http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=22&sp=YAT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031065851/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=22&sp=YAT |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 31, 2006 |title=1988 Summer Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Seoul, South Korea&nbsp;\u2013 Sailing |work=DatabaseOlympics.com |accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref> Jolly and Jewel were the only American sailors, male or female, to win a gold medal in the games.  Their victory helped to promote the involvement of more women in sailing competitions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Women Take the Helm and Make Waves |first=Millineaux |last=Lisa |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=July 14, 1991 |page=E4}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after returning from the Olympics, Jolly continued sailing, entering the US Yacht Racing Union's Championship of Champions with her husband only three days later.  In the Championship of Champions, Jolly raced a [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] instead of the 470 she had raced in the Olympics and had a difficult time adjusting to the boat differences. As a result, she and Elliot placed ninth.<ref name = \"nobreak\"/>  In 1994, Jolly applied to join the first-ever all female team in the [[America's Cup]] yachting race, organized by [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill Koch]].<ref>{{cite news |title=America's Cup: At last, an All-Female Crew |work=The New York Times |first=Robert |last=Thomas |page=B21 |date=March 10, 1994}}</ref> In a decision that shocked the yachting world, Jolly was cut from the team after tryouts and training, as was [[Lynne Jewell]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Female Crew Has Surprises |work=The New York Times |date=May 25, 1994 |page=B13}}</ref>\n\nJolly continues her sailing passion working at the [[University of South Florida St. Petersburg|University of South Florida St. Petersburg Campus]] as a sailing coach for the Women's Varsity team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.usfsp.edu/sailingteam/coaches.htm |title=USF Sailing Team Coaches |work=USFSP.edu |date=November 20, 2009 |accessdate=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212160710/http://www1.usfsp.edu/sailingteam/coaches.htm |archivedate=December 12, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJolly was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] on November 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nshof.org/inductees/jolly-allison/|title=Jolly, Allison 2019 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{sports links}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Women's 470}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jolly, Allison}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Alamitos Bay Yacht Club sailors]]\n[[Category:American female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles sailors]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Snipe class sailors]]\n[[Category:US Sailor of the Year]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American sailor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Allison Jolly\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Allison Blair Jolly \n| birth_date = {{birth-date and age|August 4, 1956}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], U.S.\n| headercolor = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Women's [[sailing (sport)|sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | [[Sailing at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 470 Female|470 class]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Allison Blair Jolly ''' (born August 4, 1956) is an [[United States|American]] [[sailor]] and Olympic champion. Born in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], Jolly began sailing at the age of 10 and attended the [[Florida State University]] where she won the National Collegiate sailing championships in 1975 and 1976. In 1976 she placed second in the European women's championship, and also took second place in the Timmy Angsten Regatta. In 1977, at the age of 20, she became the youngest woman ever to win the Yachtswoman of the Year Award from the [[New York Yacht Club]], \"considered the top prize in yachting.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Miss Jolly, North Capture Top Awards in Yachting |first=John |last=Radosta |work=The New York Times |date=March 2, 1977 |page=41}}</ref>\n\nAfter college, Jolly worked as a [[computer programmer]] in [[Valencia, California]] to support her sailing.  She bought her first boat with $8,000 that she and her husband had saved for a [[down payment]] on a house.<ref>{{cite news |title=It Was No Breeze for Olympic Skippers |first=Barbara |last=Lloyd |work=The New York Times |date=August 9, 1988 |page=B8}}</ref>  Her husband, Mark Elliot, also worked as a computer programmer and raced as a sailor.<ref name = \"nobreak\">{{cite news |title=After Howling Winds of Pusan Bay, Gold Medal-Winning Sailor Gets No Break |first=Angus |last=Phillips |work=The Washington Post |date=October 12, 1988 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Jolly and her sailing partner [[Lynne Jewell]] entered the Olympic trials for the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].  Despite a poor start in the qualifiers, the two rose to the top and won a spot.<ref>{{cite news |title=Close Match in Olympic Trials |first=Barbara |last=Lloyd |work=The New York Times |page=S10 |date=July 17, 1988}}</ref>  After qualifying, Jolly was \"considered a long shot\" in the event.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yachting |work=The New York Times |date=September 11, 1988 |page=OL16}}</ref>  In the first race of the games, Jolly and Jewell placed third,<ref>{{cite news |title=Clear Sailing as the Regatta Gets Going; Yachting |work=The New York Times |first=George |last=Vecsey |date=September 21, 1988 |page=A14}}</ref> and in the next race, their boat capsized twice, but the two managed to stay in contention.<ref>{{cite news |title=McClain, McConnell Shoot U.S. Women Into Quarterfinals |work=The Washington Post |date=September 25, 1988 |page=D14}}</ref> After finishing strong in their remaining races, the two won the gold medal in the ''[[470 (dinghy)|470 Class]]'' with a convincing lead over the competition, causing the ''Washington Post'' to write that they \"blew the competition out of the water.\"<ref name = \"nobreak\"/><ref name=db-ol1988-sailing>{{cite web|url=http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=22&sp=YAT |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031065851/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=22&sp=YAT |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 31, 2006 |title=1988 Summer Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Seoul, South Korea&nbsp;\u2013 Sailing |work=DatabaseOlympics.com |accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref> Jolly and Jewel were the only American sailors, male or female, to win a gold medal in the games.  Their victory helped to promote the involvement of more women in sailing competitions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Women Take the Helm and Make Waves |first=Millineaux |last=Lisa |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=July 14, 1991 |page=E4}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after returning from the Olympics, Jolly continued sailing, entering the US Yacht Racing Union's Championship of Champions with her husband only three days later.  In the Championship of Champions, Jolly raced a [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] instead of the 470 she had raced in the Olympics and had a difficult time adjusting to the boat differences. As a result, she and Elliot placed ninth.<ref name = \"nobreak\"/>  In 1994, Jolly applied to join the first-ever all female team in the [[America's Cup]] yachting race, organized by [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill Koch]].<ref>{{cite news |title=America's Cup: At last, an All-Female Crew |work=The New York Times |first=Robert |last=Thomas |page=B21 |date=March 10, 1994}}</ref> In a decision that shocked the yachting world, Jolly was cut from the team after tryouts and training, as was [[Lynne Jewell]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Female Crew Has Surprises |work=The New York Times |date=May 25, 1994 |page=B13}}</ref>\n\nJolly continues her sailing passion working at the [[University of South Florida St. Petersburg|University of South Florida St. Petersburg Campus]] as a sailing coach for the Women's Varsity team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.usfsp.edu/sailingteam/coaches.htm |title=USF Sailing Team Coaches |work=USFSP.edu |date=November 20, 2009 |accessdate=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212160710/http://www1.usfsp.edu/sailingteam/coaches.htm |archivedate=December 12, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJolly was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] on November 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nshof.org/inductees/jolly-allison/ |title=Jolly, Allison 2019 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2020}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{sports links}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Women's 470}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jolly, Allison}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Alamitos Bay Yacht Club sailors]]\n[[Category:American female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles sailors]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Snipe class sailors]]\n[[Category:US Sailor of the Year]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Cajohnson56", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed NSHOF reference link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allison_Jolly"}
{"title_page": "Teuta", "text_new": "{{short description|Queen regent of the Ardiaei}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name            = Queen Teuta of Illyria\n| succession      = Queen{{Cref2|A|1}} of the [[Ardiaei]]\n| image           = File:Teuta.jpg\n| caption         = Statue of Queen Teuta and her stepson Pinnes in [[Tirana]], [[Albania]]\n| reign           = 231\u2013227 BC<ref name=wrtta/>\n| successor       = [[Gentius]]\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| spouse          = [[Agron (king)|Agron]]\n| issue           =\n| full name       =\n| house           = [[Ardiaei]]\n| father          =\n| mother          =\n| image_size      = 230px\n| heir            =\n| place of burial = Unknown, tomb undiscovered.\n|}}\n'''Teuta''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a4\u03b5\u03cd\u03c4\u03b1}}) was the [[queen regent]]{{Cref2|A|2}} of the [[Ardiaei]] tribe in [[Illyria]],<ref>{{harvnb|Polybius|Scott-Kilvert|Walbank|1979|loc=pp. 114\u2013122}}; {{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|pages=80, 129, 167}}.</ref> who reigned approximately from 231 BC to 227 BC.<ref name=wrtta>{{harvnb|Jackson-Laufer|1999|loc=\"Teuta\", pp. 382\u2013383}}.</ref>{{better source|date=February 2015}}\n\n==Reign==\nAfter the death of her husband [[Agron (king)|Agron]], (250\u2013231 BC)<ref>{{harnvb|Hammond|1993|p=105}}.</ref> the former king of the [[Ardiaei]], she inherited the [[Ardiaean kingdom]], which included much of Illyria proper, though its exact extent remains unknown,<ref>{{harvnb|Berranger|Cabanes|Berranger-Auserve|2007|p=136}}.</ref> and she acted as regent for her young stepson [[Pinnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=167}}.</ref> According to [[Polybius]], she ruled \"by women's reasoning\".<ref name=\"Eckstein1995\">{{cite book|author=Arthur M. Eckstein|title=Moral Vision in the Histories of Polybius|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ky57ps7jjMEC&pg=PA154|date=2 January 1995|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91469-8|page=154|quote=Such is the case, of course, with his presentation of Queen Teuta, ruler of the Illyrian Ardiaei (2.4-1 1). Teuta succeeded her husband, Agron (himself a drunkard; cf. 2.4.6), in 231. Polybius sneers that she ruled \"by women's reasoning\" ...}}</ref> Teuta started to address the neighbouring [[Nation state|states]] malevolently, supporting the piratical [[Raid (military)|raid]]s of her subjects. She also gave the Romans their first pretext to cross the Adriatic with an army; this occurred as they started the conquest of the eastern Mediterranean.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Amazons to Fighter Pilots - A Biographical Dictionary of Military Woman (Volume Two)|last=Pennington|first=Reina|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2003|isbn=0-313-32708-4|location=Westport, Connecticut|pages=430}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Illyria.jpg|thumb|Illyrian land prior to Roman conquest]]\n\nIllyrians soon captured and later fortified [[Dyrrachium]] (modern-day [[Durr\u00ebs]], [[Albania]]) and [[Phoenice]] (which was soon liberated with a truce and a [[fee]]).<ref name=\"Wilkes 1995 158\">{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=158}}.</ref> While her ships were off the coast of [[Sarand\u00eb|Onchesmos]], they intercepted and [[plunder]]ed<ref name=\"Wilkes 1995 158\"/> some [[Roman Republic|Roman]] [[merchant vessel]]s. Teuta's forces extended their operations further southward into the [[Ionian Sea]], defeating the combined [[Achaean League|Achaean]] and [[Aetolian League|Aetolian]] fleet in the [[battle of Paxos]] and capturing the island of [[Korkyra (polis)|Corcyra]], which put them in position to breach the important [[trade route]]s between the mainland of [[Greece]] and the [[Magna Graecia|Greek cities in Italy]].<ref name=wrtta/>\n\nBecause the [[Roman Republic]] felt threatened by the opposing side of the Adriatic in the very vicinity of its territories (where most of the raids occurred),<ref name=rrar>{{harvnb|Strickland|Strickland|1854|pages=290\u2013291}}.</ref> the [[Roman Senate|senate]] was compelled to dispatch two [[Ambassador (diplomacy)|ambassadors]] to the city of [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scodra]] to solicit [[Reparation (legal)|reparations]] and demand an end to all pirate expeditions. Queen Teuta told the ambassadors that according to the law of the [[Illyrians]], [[piracy]] was a lawful trade and that her [[government]] had no right to interfere with this as a [[private enterprise]]. She also implied that \"it was never the custom of [[Royal family|royalty]] to prevent the advantage of its subjects they could get from the sea\".<ref name=rrar/> One of the envoys reportedly replied that Rome would make it her business to introduce better law among the Illyrians as \"we have an excellent custom of punishing private wrongs by public revenge\".<ref name=rrar/> At any rate, one of the two present ambassadors expressed himself to the queen so disrespectfully that her attendants were ordered to seize the ambassadors' ship as it embarked back for Rome.<ref name=ahositcw>{{harvnb|Meijer|1986|p=167}}.</ref> One of the ambassadors was killed and the other was put in captivity.<ref name=wrtta/>\n\n===War with Rome===\n{{Main|Illyrian Wars}}\nIn 229 BC, Rome declared war<ref name=thor/><ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=160}}.</ref><ref name=hofg>{{harvnb|Freeman|1863|pages=418\u2013419}}.</ref> on [[Illyria]] and for the first time armies crossed the Adriatic to Illyria (the western regions of the [[Balkan Peninsula]] in modern usage). An army consisting of approximately 20,000 [[troops]], 200 [[cavalry]] units and an entire [[Roman navy|Roman fleet]] of 200 ships was sent to conquer Illyria.<ref name=ahositcw/> When the fleet showed up by [[Korkyra (polis)|Corcyra]], Teuta's [[governor]], [[Demetrius of Pharos|Demetrius]] surrendered the city and sided with the Romans as their advisor for the remaining time of the war;<ref name=Ceka180/> at the end of the war (228 BC) the Romans awarded him, resulting in Demetrius' becoming the governor of Pharos and the adjacent coasts.<ref name=Jacques121>{{harvnb|Jacques|2009|pages=121}}.</ref><ref name=Ceka180/> The remainder of the Roman army in the meantime landed further north at [[Apollonia, Illyria|Apollonia]].<ref name=Ceka180/> The combined army and navy proceeded northward together, subduing one town after another and eventually [[siege|besieging]] the capital Scodra. Teuta herself had retreated to [[Rhizon]], the principal base of the Illyrian fleet,<ref name=Ceka180>{{harvnb|Ceka|2013|pages=180}}.</ref> and finally surrendered in 227 BC, having to accept an ignominious peace. The Romans allowed her to continue her reign but restricted<ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=161}}.</ref> her to a narrow region around [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scodra]], deprived her of all her other holdings, and forbade her to sail an armed ship south of [[Lezh\u00eb|Lissus]].<ref name=hofg/><ref>{{harvnb|Evans|2006|p=277}}.</ref> They also required her to pay an annual tribute<ref name=wrtta/><ref>Polybius. ''Histories'', 2.12.</ref> and to acknowledge the final authority of Rome.\n\nHer rule was finally ended by the [[politician]] [[Lucius Postumius Albinus (consul 234 BC)|Lucius Postumius Albinus]], after she opted against Roman suppression.<ref name=hofg/> Very little is known of the rest of her life. According to the folklore of the modern inhabitants of [[Risan]], Teuta ended her life in grief by throwing herself from [[Orjen]] Peak.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Illyrian warfare]]\n*[[List of rulers of Illyria]]\n\n==Annotations==\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}}\n{{Cnote2|A|She was never referred to as a \"[[Queen consort|queen]]\" by [[Appian]] since she was a regent to [[Pinnes]].<ref name=thor>{{harvnb|Arnold|1846|p=259}}.</ref><ref name=eim>{{harvnb|Berranger|Cabanes|Berranger-Auserve|2007|p=133}}.</ref> }}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Arnold|first=Thomas|title=The History of Rome|publisher=D. Appleton & Co|year=1846|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j74oAAAAYAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Berranger|first1=Dani\u00e8le|last2=Cabanes|first2=Pierre|last3=Berranger-Auserve|first3=Dani\u00e8le|title=\u00c9pire, Illyrie, Mac\u00e9doine: M\u00e9langes offerts au Professeur Pierre Cabanes|publisher=Presses Universitaire Blaise Pascal|year=2007|isbn=2845163517|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I_kFU6h77ssC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ceka|first=Neritan|title=The Illyrians to the Albanians|publisher=Migjeni|year=2013|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Druett|first=Joan|title=She Captains: Heroines and Hellions of the Sea|publisher=Barnes & Noble Books|year=2005|isbn=0760766916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GoR-gJ5NzegC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Evans|first=Arthur|title=Ancient Illyria: An Archaeological Exploration|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2006|isbn=9781845111670|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3J96wSxMaeYC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Edward Augustus|title=History of Federal Government: From the Foundation of the Achaian League to the Disruption of the United States|publisher=Macmillan and Co|year=1863|url=https://archive.org/details/historyfederalg00freegoog|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Studies concerning Epirus and Macedonia before Alexander|publisher=Hakkert|year=1993|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWwiAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jackson-Laufer|first=Guida Myrl|title=Women Rulers throughout the Ages: An Illustrated Guide|publisher=ABC-CLIO, Inc|year=1999|location=New York|isbn=1576070913|url =https://archive.org/details/isbn_9791576070917|url-access=registration|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jacques|first=Edwin|title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present|publisher=McFarland|year=2009|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Meijer|first=Fik|title=A History of Seafaring in the Classical World|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=1986|isbn=0312000758|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_VxQgAACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Polybius|last2=Scott-Kilvert|first2=Ian|last3=Walbank|first3=Frank William|title=The Rise of the Roman Empire|publisher=Penguin Classics|year=1979|isbn=0140443622|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hKcUVrE4tAIC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Strickland|first1=Jane Margaret|last2=Strickland|first2=Agnes|title=Rome, Regal and Republican: A Family History of Rome|publisher=A. Hall|year=1854|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmQZAAAAYAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=John|title=The Illyrians|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=1995|isbn=0631198075|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Nv6SPRKqs8C|ref=harv}}\n{{refend|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons|Illyria & Illyrians}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Prodanovi\u0107|first1=Nada \u0106ur\u010dija|author-link=Nada \u0106ur\u010dija Prodanovi\u0107|last2=Risti\u0107|first2=Dus\u0306an|title=Teuta, Queen of Illyria|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1973|isbn=0192713531|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6_OOPQAACAAJ}}\n*{{cite book|last=Grant DePauw|first=Linda|author-link=Linda Grant DePauw|title=Battle Cries and Lullabies: Women in War from Prehistory to the Present|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=2000|isbn=0806132884|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tHeoE5iJ1-sC}}\n*{{cite book|last=Walbank|first=Frank William|title=The Cambridge Ancient History: The Hellenistic World (Volume 7, Part 1)|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1984|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IcDaRAAACAAJ}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jones|first=David E.|title=Women Warriors: A History|publisher=Brassey's|year=2000|isbn=9781574882063|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AEF6t0wDRKQC}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Ardiaean kingdom]]||Unknown||Unknown}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Agron (king)|Agron]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Queen of the Ardiaei (regent to [[Pinnes]])|years=231\u2013227 BC{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Gentius]]}}\n{{End}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teuta of Issa}}\n[[Category:Illyrian queens]]\n[[Category:Bay of Kotor]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC women rulers]]\n[[Category:Illyrian Albania]]\n[[Category:Illyrian Croatia]]\n[[Category:Illyrian Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Ancient piracy]]\n[[Category:Piracy in the Mediterranean]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Queen regent of the Ardiaei}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name            = Queen Teuta of Illyria\n| succession      = Queen{{Cref2|A|1}} of the [[Ardiaei]]\n| image           = File:Teuta.jpg\n| caption         = Statue of Queen Teuta and her stepson Pinnes in [[Tirana]], [[Albania]]\n| reign           = 231\u2013227 BC<ref name=wrtta/>\n| successor       = [[Gentius]]\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| spouse          = [[Agron (king)|Agron]]\n| issue           =\n| full name       =\n| house           = [[Ardiaei]]\n| father          =\n| mother          =\n| image_size      = 230px\n| heir            =\n| place of burial = Unknown, tomb undiscovered.\n|}}\n'''Teuta''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a4\u03b5\u03cd\u03c4\u03b1}}) was the [[queen regent]]{{Cref2|A|2}} of the [[Ardiaei]] tribe in [[Illyria]],<ref>{{harvnb|Polybius|Scott-Kilvert|Walbank|1979|loc=pp. 114\u2013122}}; {{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|pages=80, 129, 167}}.</ref> who reigned approximately from 231 BC to 227 BC.<ref name=wrtta>{{harvnb|Jackson-Laufer|1999|loc=\"Teuta\", pp. 382\u2013383}}.</ref>{{better source|date=February 2015}}\n\n==Reign==\nAfter the death of her husband [[Agron (king)|Agron]], (250\u2013231 BC)<ref>{{harnvb|Hammond|1993|p=105}}.</ref> the former king of the [[Ardiaei]], she inherited the [[Ardiaean kingdom]], which included much of Illyria proper, though its exact extent remains unknown,<ref>{{harvnb|Berranger|Cabanes|Berranger-Auserve|2007|p=136}}.</ref> and she acted as regent for her young stepson [[Pinnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=167}}.</ref> According to [[Polybius]], she ruled \"by women's reasoning\".<ref name=\"Eckstein1995\">{{cite book|author=Arthur M. Eckstein|title=Moral Vision in the Histories of Polybius|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ky57ps7jjMEC&pg=PA154|date=2 January 1995|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91469-8|page=154|quote=Such is the case, of course, with his presentation of Queen Teuta, ruler of the Illyrian Ardiaei (2.4-1 1). Teuta succeeded her husband, Agron (himself a drunkard; cf. 2.4.6), in 231. Polybius sneers that she ruled \"by women's reasoning\" ...}}</ref> Teuta started to address the neighbouring [[Nation state|states]] malevolently, supporting the piratical [[Raid (military)|raid]]s of her subjects. She also gave the Romans their first pretext to cross the Adriatic with an army; this occurred as they started the conquest of the eastern Mediterranean.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Amazons to Fighter Pilots - A Biographical Dictionary of Military Woman (Volume Two)|last=Pennington|first=Reina|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2003|isbn=0-313-32708-4|location=Westport, Connecticut|pages=430}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Illyria.jpg|thumb|Illyrian land prior to Roman conquest]]\n\nIllyrians soon captured and later fortified [[Dyrrachium]] (modern-day [[Durr\u00ebs]], [[Albania]]) and [[Phoenice]] (which was soon liberated with a truce and a [[fee]]).<ref name=\"Wilkes 1995 158\">{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=158}}.</ref> While her ships were off the coast of [[Sarand\u00eb|Onchesmos]], they intercepted and [[plunder]]ed<ref name=\"Wilkes 1995 158\"/> some [[Roman Republic|Roman]] [[merchant vessel]]s. Teuta's forces extended their operations further southward into the [[Ionian Sea]], defeating the combined [[Achaean League|Achaean]] and [[Aetolian League|Aetolian]] fleet in the [[battle of Paxos]] and capturing the island of [[Korkyra (polis)|Corcyra]], which put them in position to breach the important [[trade route]]s between the mainland of [[Greece]] and the [[Magna Graecia|Greek cities in Italy]].<ref name=wrtta/>\n\nBecause the [[Roman Republic]] felt threatened by the opposing side of the Adriatic in the very vicinity of its territories (where most of the raids occurred),<ref name=rrar>{{harvnb|Strickland|Strickland|1854|pages=290\u2013291}}.</ref> the [[Roman Senate|senate]] was compelled to dispatch two [[Ambassador (diplomacy)|ambassadors]] to the city of [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scodra]] to solicit [[Reparation (legal)|reparations]] and demand an end to all pirate expeditions. Queen Teuta told the ambassadors that according to the law of the [[Illyrians]], [[piracy]] was a lawful trade and that her [[government]] had no right to interfere with this as a [[private enterprise]]. She also implied that \"it was never the custom of [[Royal family|royalty]] to prevent the advantage of its subjects they could get from the sea\".<ref name=rrar/> One of the envoys reportedly replied that Rome would make it her business to introduce better law among the Illyrians as \"we have an excellent custom of punishing private wrongs by public revenge\".<ref name=rrar/> At any rate, one of the two present ambassadors expressed himself to the queen so disrespectfully that her attendants were ordered to seize the ambassadors' ship as it embarked back for Rome.<ref name=ahositcw>{{harvnb|Meijer|1986|p=167}}.</ref> One of the ambassadors was killed and the other was put in captivity.<ref name=wrtta/>\n\n===War with Rome===\n{{Main|Illyrian Wars}}\nIn 229 BC, Rome declared war<ref name=thor/><ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=160}}.</ref><ref name=hofg>{{harvnb|Freeman|1863|pages=418\u2013419}}.</ref> on [[Illyria]] and for the first time armies crossed the Adriatic to Illyria (the western regions of the [[Balkan Peninsula]] in modern usage). An army consisting of approximately 20,000 [[troops]], 200 [[cavalry]] units and an entire [[Roman navy|Roman fleet]] of 200 ships was sent to conquer Illyria.<ref name=ahositcw/> When the fleet showed up by [[Korkyra (polis)|Corcyra]], Teuta's [[governor]], [[Demetrius of Pharos|Demetrius]] surrendered the city and sided with the Romans as their advisor for the remaining time of the war;<ref name=Ceka180/> at the end of the war (228 BC) the Romans awarded him, resulting in Demetrius' becoming the governor of Pharos and the adjacent coasts.<ref name=Jacques121>{{harvnb|Jacques|2009|pages=121}}.</ref><ref name=Ceka180/> The remainder of the Roman army in the meantime landed further north at [[Apollonia, Illyria|Apollonia]].<ref name=Ceka180/> The combined army and navy proceeded northward together, subduing one town after another and eventually [[siege|besieging]] the capital Scodra. Teuta herself had retreated to [[Rhizon]], the principal base of the Illyrian fleet,<ref name=Ceka180>{{harvnb|Ceka|2013|pages=180}}.</ref> and finally surrendered in 227 BC, having to accept an ignominious peace. The Romans allowed her to continue her reign but restricted<ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=161}}.</ref> her to a narrow region around [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scodra]], deprived her of all her other holdings, and forbade her to sail an armed ship south of [[Lezh\u00eb|Lissus]].<ref name=hofg/><ref>{{harvnb|Evans|2006|p=277}}.</ref> They also required her to pay an annual tribute<ref name=wrtta/><ref>Polybius. ''Histories'', 2.12.</ref> and to acknowledge the final authority of Rome.\n\nHer rule was finally ended by the [[politician]] [[Lucius Postumius Albinus (consul 234 BC)|Lucius Postumius Albinus]], after she opted against Roman suppression.<ref name=hofg/> Very little is known of the rest of her life. According to the folklore of the modern inhabitants of [[Risan]], Teuta ended her life in grief by throwing herself from [[Orjen]] Peak.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Illyrian warfare]]\n*[[List of rulers of Illyria]]\n\n==Annotations==\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}}\n{{Cnote2|A|She was never referred to as a \"[[Queen consort|queen]]\" by [[Appian]] since she was a regent to [[Pinnes]].<ref name=thor>{{harvnb|Arnold|1846|p=259}}.</ref><ref name=eim>{{harvnb|Berranger|Cabanes|Berranger-Auserve|2007|p=133}}.</ref> }}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Arnold|first=Thomas|title=The History of Rome|publisher=D. Appleton & Co|year=1846|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j74oAAAAYAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Berranger|first1=Dani\u00e8le|last2=Cabanes|first2=Pierre|last3=Berranger-Auserve|first3=Dani\u00e8le|title=\u00c9pire, Illyrie, Mac\u00e9doine: M\u00e9langes offerts au Professeur Pierre Cabanes|publisher=Presses Universitaire Blaise Pascal|year=2007|isbn=2845163517|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I_kFU6h77ssC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ceka|first=Neritan|title=The Illyrians to the Albanians|publisher=Migjeni|year=2013|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Druett|first=Joan|title=She Captains: Heroines and Hellions of the Sea|publisher=Barnes & Noble Books|year=2005|isbn=0760766916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GoR-gJ5NzegC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Evans|first=Arthur|title=Ancient Illyria: An Archaeological Exploration|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2006|isbn=9781845111670|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3J96wSxMaeYC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Edward Augustus|title=History of Federal Government: From the Foundation of the Achaian League to the Disruption of the United States|publisher=Macmillan and Co|year=1863|url=https://archive.org/details/historyfederalg00freegoog|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Studies concerning Epirus and Macedonia before Alexander|publisher=Hakkert|year=1993|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWwiAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jackson-Laufer|first=Guida Myrl|title=Women Rulers throughout the Ages: An Illustrated Guide|publisher=ABC-CLIO, Inc|year=1999|location=New York|isbn=1576070913|url =https://archive.org/details/isbn_9