{"title_page": "XXL (club)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2009}}\n{{unbalanced|date=December 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''XXL''' was a [[gay]] [[nightclub]] in [[London]] and [[Birmingham]] which catered to the [[bear community|bear]] sub-group.<ref name=\"Cochran2009\">{{cite book|author=Jason Cochran|title=Pauline Frommer's London: Spend Less, See More|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780470308691|url-access=registration|date=5 February 2009|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-46511-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780470308691/page/320 320]}}</ref><ref name=\"Out2014\">{{cite book|author=Editors of Time Out|title=Time Out London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWkSxQ5Dt6sC&pg=PT581|date=2 January 2014|publisher=Time Out Guides Limited|isbn=978-1-84670-426-0|page=581}}</ref><ref name=\"PlanetFilou2013\">{{cite book|author1=Lonely Planet|author2=Emilie Filou|author3=Steve Fallon |author4=Damian Harper |author5=Vesna Maric|title=Lonely Planet London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SfzhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT285|date=1 October 2013|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications|isbn=978-1-74321-833-4|page=285}}</ref> The club was founded by Mark Ames and his then partner David Dindol in 2000. They separated in 2005, after which Mark purchased his ex-partner's share of the club. It was the largest dedicated \"bear\" venue in the [[United Kingdom]] and the world{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}. It was not just the bear scene's longest-running weekly disco but London's too, having not missed a night in over 16 years{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}.\n\nBetween 2012<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxl-london.com/history-and-highlights/|title=History and Highlights {{!}} XXL London|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref> and 2019, XXL London was based at Pulse, which closed in September 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mixmag.net/read/xxl-being-forced-to-close-news|title=XXL, one of London's leading gay clubs, is being forced to close|website=Mixmag|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boyz.co.uk/xxl-the-last-dance-at-pulse-saturday-21st-september/|title=XXL The Last Dance at Pulse: Saturday 21st September|last=Cross|first=Dave|date=2019-10-04|website=Boyz|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref> to make way for a future development of luxury apartments. There are currently no public plans for a future venue but it is understood that discussions are ongoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boyz.co.uk/xxl-last-dance-at-pulse-this-saturday/|title=XXL Last Dance at Pulse this Saturday|last=Cross|first=Dave|date=2019-09-18|website=Boyz|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Venue ==\nXXL was based at Pulse in [[Southwark]], on the corner of  Southwark Street and Blackfriars Road. Pulse was on the same street as the previous venue, Arcadia. Both consist of a number of railway arches.\n\nAfter Arcadia became unsafe due to a structural fault in the railway arches, XXL moved to Pulse in March 2012, one of the capital's largest entertainment venues that was developed and converted by Ames and his team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.outmag.co.uk/site/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=247:xxl-moves-home&catid=19:main-news&Itemid=39|title=XXL club moves home|work=Out in the City|date=9 March 2012|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMark Ames created XXL as he felt disillusioned with how little there was for the London Bear Community outside of one bar in [[Soho]]<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nIn 2003, XXL in London created [[Bear Necessities]], now called XXL London Bear Pride, a weekend-long celebration of everything \"big, gay and hairy\" with events around the country. A year later this turned into London Bear Pride. In 2006 this was expanded to include the [[leather subculture|leather community]] in Bear and Leather Pride. The two subcultures do have a large overlap and a number of leather [[Sexual fetishism|fetishists]] patronize XXL.\n\nXXL also operates internationally both in Europe and the US as well as a monthly night in the UK's second city Birmingham and has other events too. In 2014, XXL launched a monthly event in Glasgow.\n\n[[Opinion poll]]s in magazines such as ''[[Gay Times]]'', the ''[[Pink Paper]]'' and ''[[Boyz (magazine)|Boyz]]'' regularly put XXL in the top two night clubs in London.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} XXL was also the title sponsor of the 2006 [[Mark Kendall Bingham Memorial Tournament|Bingham Cup]] in New York.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}  In 2007 the club expanded and also diversified the brand by launching new nights, extending its appeal far beyond the core audience.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} In 2009 Ames became the gay promoter of the year according to the London Boyz Magazine readers' poll and was named as a gay icon in London's ''[[QX (British magazine)|QX]]'' magazine.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} In the 2017 Boyz Awards, XXL was voted best club, with two of the XXL DJs (Joe Egg and David Robson) appearing in the Top 10 most popular DJs.\n\nThere were four resident DJs at XXL; Alex Logan (from 2004), Joe Egg (from 2007), David Robson (from 2015) and Paul Morrell (from 2016). Logan and Morrell play contemporary house and dance mixes with a tribal edge in the main room; occasionally joined by Mark Ames himself. Egg and Robson play an eclectic set of contemporary and retro pop, rock, indie, soul, R&B, bashment and disco in the smaller room, known as 'The Fur Lounge'.\n\nIn 2015 it was announced that regular guest DJs would play in the main room rotating on a monthly basis in between the weekly residents' sessions. These DJs are currently The Hoxton Whores (began residency 11 July 2015), Moto Blanco (beginning summer 2015), Fat Tony (from 2017) and Pagano, who first guested in the summer of 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qxmagazine.com/issue/issue-1059/|title=QX Gay London Issue 1059|work=Interview with Mark Ames|date=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was announced that XXL was being evicted from Pulse, as the building was being redeveloped into flats and a shopping mall, by the landlords, Native Land. The last XXL at Pulse was on Saturday 21 September 2019.\n\n== Criticisms ==\n\nIn June 2010 the UK gay press reported on comments written by Mark Ames on his Facebook page in which he stated that he would boycott Muslim businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3316|title=EXCLUSIVE: XXL owner Mark Ames slammed for Muslim boycott|date=30 June 2010|work=PinkPaper.com|first1=Peter|last1=Lloyd|first2=Tris|last2=Reid-Smith|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716163718/http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3316|archivedate=16 July 2011}}</ref> He issued an unreserved apology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3329|title=YOU READ IT HERE FIRST: XXL's Mark Ames makes heartfelt apology|work=PinkPaper.com|date=1 July 2010 |first=Peter |last=Lloyd |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716163704/http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3329 |archivedate=16 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAmes caused controversy again in 2018 after a customer was turned away from XXL whilst wearing high heels. After responding to the controversy on Facebook, protests were organised in other LGBT venues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/09/12/xxl-london-gay-club-femme-clothing-protest/|title=London gay club XXL's controversial door policy banning femme clothing sparks protest - PinkNews \u00b7 PinkNews|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://xxl-london.com/}}\n*{{website|http://www.hoxtonwhores.com/}}\n*{{website|https://www.facebook.com/motoblancouk/}}\n*{{website|https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165402/http://www.funkybearmartin.com/}}\n\n{{coords|51.5071|-0.1038|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xxl (Club)}}\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 2000]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:2000 in London]]\n[[Category:Bear (gay culture)]]\n[[Category:LGBT nightclubs in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2009}}\n{{unbalanced|date=December 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''XXL''' was a [[gay]] [[nightclub]] in [[London]] and [[Birmingham]] which catered to the [[bear community|bear]] sub-group.<ref name=\"Cochran2009\">{{cite book|author=Jason Cochran|title=Pauline Frommer's London: Spend Less, See More|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780470308691|url-access=registration|date=5 February 2009|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-46511-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780470308691/page/320 320]}}</ref><ref name=\"Out2014\">{{cite book|author=Editors of Time Out|title=Time Out London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWkSxQ5Dt6sC&pg=PT581|date=2 January 2014|publisher=Time Out Guides Limited|isbn=978-1-84670-426-0|page=581}}</ref><ref name=\"PlanetFilou2013\">{{cite book|author1=Lonely Planet|author2=Emilie Filou|author3=Steve Fallon |author4=Damian Harper |author5=Vesna Maric|title=Lonely Planet London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SfzhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT285|date=1 October 2013|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications|isbn=978-1-74321-833-4|page=285}}</ref> The club was founded by Mark Ames and his then partner David Dindol in 2000. They separated in 2005, after which Mark purchased his ex-partner's share of the club. It was the largest dedicated \"bear\" venue in the [[United Kingdom]] and the world{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}. It was not just the bear scene's longest-running weekly disco but London's too, having not missed a night in over 16 years{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}.\n\nBetween 2012<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxl-london.com/history-and-highlights/|title=History and Highlights {{!}} XXL London|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref> and 2019, XXL London was based at Pulse, which closed in September 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mixmag.net/read/xxl-being-forced-to-close-news|title=XXL, one of London's leading gay clubs, is being forced to close|website=Mixmag|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boyz.co.uk/xxl-the-last-dance-at-pulse-saturday-21st-september/|title=XXL The Last Dance at Pulse: Saturday 21st September|last=Cross|first=Dave|date=2019-10-04|website=Boyz|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref> to make way for a future development of luxury apartments. There are currently no public plans for a future venue but it is understood that discussions are ongoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boyz.co.uk/xxl-last-dance-at-pulse-this-saturday/|title=XXL Last Dance at Pulse this Saturday|last=Cross|first=Dave|date=2019-09-18|website=Boyz|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Venue ==\nXXL was based at Pulse in [[Southwark]], on the corner of  Southwark Street and Blackfriars Road. Pulse was on the same street as the previous venue, Arcadia. Both consist of a number of railway arches.\n\nAfter Arcadia became unsafe due to a structural fault in the railway arches, XXL moved to Pulse in March 2012, one of the capital's largest entertainment venues that was developed and converted by Ames and his team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.outmag.co.uk/site/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=247:xxl-moves-home&catid=19:main-news&Itemid=39|title=XXL club moves home|work=Out in the City|date=9 March 2012|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMark Ames created XXL as he felt disillusioned with how little there was for the London Bear Community outside of one bar in [[Soho]]<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nIn 2003, XXL in London created [[Bear Necessities]], now called XXL London Bear Pride, a weekend-long celebration of everything \"big, gay and hairy\" with events around the country. A year later this turned into London Bear Pride. In 2006 this was expanded to include the [[leather subculture|leather community]] in Bear and Leather Pride. The two subcultures do have a large overlap and a number of leather [[Sexual fetishism|fetishists]] patronize XXL.\n\nXXL also operates internationally both in Europe and the US as well as a monthly night in the UK's second city Birmingham and has other events too. In 2014, XXL launched a monthly event in Glasgow.\n\n[[Opinion poll]]s in magazines such as ''[[Gay Times]]'', the ''[[Pink Paper]]'' and ''[[Boyz (magazine)|Boyz]]'' regularly put XXL in the top two night clubs in London.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} XXL was also the title sponsor of the 2006 [[Mark Kendall Bingham Memorial Tournament|Bingham Cup]] in New York.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}  In 2007 the club expanded and also diversified the brand by launching new nights, extending its appeal far beyond the core audience.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} In 2009 Ames became the gay promoter of the year according to the London Boyz Magazine readers' poll and was named as a gay icon in London's ''[[QX (British magazine)|QX]]'' magazine.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} In the 2017 Boyz Awards, XXL was voted best club, with two of the XXL DJ's (Joe Egg and David Robson) appearing in the Top 10 most popular DJ's.\n\nThere were four resident DJ's at XXL; Alex Logan (from 2004), Joe Egg (from 2007), David Robson (from 2015) and Paul Morrell (from 2016). Logan and Morrell play contemporary house and dance mixes with a tribal edge in the main room; occasionally joined by Mark Ames himself. Egg and Robson play an eclectic set of contemporary and retro pop, rock, indie, soul, R&B, bashment and disco in the smaller room, known as 'The Fur Lounge'.\n\nIn 2015 it was announced that regular guest DJ's would play in the main room rotating on a monthly basis in between the weekly residents' sessions. These DJs are currently The Hoxton Whores (began residency 11 July 2015), Moto Blanco (beginning summer 2015), Fat Tony (from 2017) and Pagano, who first guested in the summer of 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qxmagazine.com/issue/issue-1059/|title=QX Gay London Issue 1059|work=Interview with Mark Ames|date=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was announced that XXL was being evicted from Pulse, as the building was being redeveloped into flats and a shopping mall, by the landlords, Native Land. The last XXL at Pulse was on Saturday 21 September 2019.\n\n== Criticisms ==\n\nIn June 2010 the UK gay press reported on comments written by Mark Ames on his Facebook page in which he stated that he would boycott Muslim businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3316|title=EXCLUSIVE: XXL owner Mark Ames slammed for Muslim boycott|date=30 June 2010|work=PinkPaper.com|first1=Peter|last1=Lloyd|first2=Tris|last2=Reid-Smith|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716163718/http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3316|archivedate=16 July 2011}}</ref> He issued an unreserved apology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3329|title=YOU READ IT HERE FIRST: XXL's Mark Ames makes heartfelt apology|work=PinkPaper.com|date=1 July 2010 |first=Peter |last=Lloyd |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716163704/http://news.pinkpaper.com/NewsStory.aspx?id=3329 |archivedate=16 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAmes caused controversy again in 2018 after a customer was turned away from XXL whilst wearing high heels. After responding to the controversy on Facebook, protests were organised in other LGBT venues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/09/12/xxl-london-gay-club-femme-clothing-protest/|title=London gay club XXL's controversial door policy banning femme clothing sparks protest - PinkNews \u00b7 PinkNews|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*