{"title_page": "The Planets", "text_new": "{{short description|Orchestral suite by Gustav Holst}}\n{{About|the orchestral suite by Gustav Holst|the celestial body|Planet|the planets in the solar system|Solar System|other uses|Planet (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n|name=''The Planets''\n|type=[[Orchestral suite]]\n|composer=[[Gustav Holst]]\n|image=Gustav Holst.jpg\n|opus=32\n|based_on=[[Planets in ]]\n|composed={{start date|1914}}\u201316\n|movements=seven\n|scoring=[[Orchestra]]\n|premiere_date={{start date|1918|09|29|df=y}}\n|premiere_conductor=[[Adrian Boult]]\n|premiere_location=[[Queen's Hall]], London}}\n'''''The Planets''''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 32, is a seven-[[Movement (music)|movement]] orchestral [[Suite (music)|suite]] by the English composer [[Gustav Holst]], written between 1914 and 1916. Each movement of the suite is named after a [[planet]] of the [[solar system]] and its corresponding [[planets in astrology|astrological]] character as defined by Holst.\n\nFrom its premiere to the present day, the suite has been enduringly popular, influential, widely performed and frequently recorded. The work was not heard in a complete public performance, however, until some years after it was completed. Although there were four performances between September 1918 and October 1920, they were all either private (the first performance, in London) or incomplete (two others in London and one in [[Birmingham]]). The premiere was at the [[Queen's Hall]] on 29 September 1918,{{sfn|Lebrecht|2008|p=240}} conducted by Holst's friend [[Adrian Boult]] before an invited audience of about 250 people. The first complete public performance was finally given in London by [[Albert Coates (musician)|Albert Coates]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] on 15 November 1920.<ref name=musical-times/>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Queen's Hall London.jpg|thumb|300px|right| The [[Queen's Hall]], in London, where ''The Planets'' premiered in 1918]]\nThe concept of the work is [[Astrology|astrological]]<ref name=HolstLM>\"HOLST Suite: The Planets\" (compares compositions & history), Len Mullenger, Olton Recorded Music Society, January 2000, webpage: [http://www.musicweb.uk.net/holst.htm MusicWebUK-Holst]: in 1913 [[Gustav Holst|Holst]] went on holiday to [[Majorca]] with [[Balfour Gardiner]], [[Arnold Bax]], and his brother [[Clifford Bax]], and who spent the entire holiday discussing astrology.</ref> rather than [[astronomy|astronomical]] (which is why [[Earth]] is not included, although [[Planets in astrology#Sun|Sun and Moon]] are also not included while including the non-traditional Uranus and Neptune): each movement is intended to convey ideas and emotions associated with the [[Planets in astrology|influence of the planets on the psyche]], not the [[Dii Consentes|Roman deities]]. The idea of the work was suggested to Holst by [[Clifford Bax]], who introduced him to astrology when the two were part of a small group of English artists holidaying in [[Majorca]] in the spring of 1913; Holst became quite a devotee of the subject, and would cast his friends' horoscopes for fun.<ref name=HolstLM/><ref name=Imogen/> Holst also used [[Alan Leo]]'s<ref name=HolstLM/> book ''What is a Horoscope?'' as a springboard for his own ideas, as well as for the subtitles (e.g., \"The Bringer of...\") for the movements.\n\nOn 17 January 1914 Holst attended a performance of [[Arnold Schoenberg]]'s ''[[Five Pieces for Orchestra]]'', at the Queen's Hall, conducted by Schoenberg's pupil [[Edward Clark (conductor)|Edward Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoenberg.at/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1014&Itemid=726&lang=en|title=1914 \u2022 Herr Sch\u00f6nberg in London|website=www.schoenberg.at}}</ref><ref name=keller>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wo4LhjGd-c4C&pg=PA21&lpg=PA21&dq=edward+clark+schoenberg&source=bl&ots=QiyjCnfRPT&sig=TxCP-0cN1hG86dsaiLr7tQLzsfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Xh8JUYfnAu2cmQWPyoG4DQ&ved=0CFUQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=edward+clark+schoenberg&f=false|title=Hans Keller and the BBC: The Musical Conscience of British Broadcasting, 1959\u201379|first=Alison|last=Garnham|date=23 October 2003|publisher=Ashgate|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CVCtkShvDSkC&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=Peter+Eckersley+edward+clark&source=bl&ots=G54LQFEhBQ&sig=3Hc2HGDA3blOjFRYYyTvdOH-EoM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eSsKUfW0CKaLmwX28YD4Dg&sqi=2&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=clark&f=false|title=The BBC and Ultra-Modern Music, 1922\u20131936: Shaping a Nation's Tastes|first1=Jennifer|last1=Doctor|first2=Jennifer Ruth|last2=Doctor|date=23 October 1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> Holst quickly acquired a copy of the score, the only Schoenberg score he ever owned. This influenced Holst at least to the degree that the working title of his own composition was ''Seven Pieces for Large Orchestra''.<ref>[http://www.schoenberg.at/library/index.php/attachments/single/1634 David Lambourn, \"Henry Wood and Schoenberg\", The Musical Times, Vol. 128, No. 1734 (August 1987), pp. 422\u201327]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>\n\nWhen composing ''The Planets'' Holst initially scored the work for four hands, two pianos, except for Neptune, which was scored for a [[Organ (music)|single organ]], as Holst believed that the sound of the piano was too percussive for a world as mysterious and distant as Neptune. Holst then scored the suite for a large orchestra, in which form it became enormously popular. Holst's use of orchestration was very imaginative and colourful, showing the influence of such contemporary composers as [[Igor Stravinsky]]<ref>Short, p. 131</ref> and [[Arnold Schoenberg]],<ref name=HolstLM/> as well as such late Russian romantics as [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] and [[Alexander Glazunov]]. Its novel sonorities helped make the work an immediate success with audiences at home and abroad. Although ''The Planets'' remains Holst's most popular work, the composer himself did not count it among his best creations and later in life complained that its popularity had completely surpassed his other works. He was, however, partial to his own favourite movement, Saturn.<ref>Boult, Sir Adrian (1967), Liner note to EMI CD 5 66934 2</ref>\n\n==Premieres==\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center|quote =Just before the Armistice, Gustav Holst burst into my office: \"Adrian, the YMCA are sending me to [[Thessaloniki|Salonika]] quite soon and [[H. Balfour Gardiner|Balfour Gardiner]], bless his heart, has given me a parting present consisting of the [[Queen's Hall]], full of the Queen's Hall Orchestra for the whole of a Sunday morning. So we're going to do ''The Planets'', and you've got to conduct.\" | source =  Adrian Boult<ref name=boult35>Boult p. 35</ref>| align=right| width=33%}}\n\nThe orchestral premiere of ''The Planets'' suite, conducted at Holst's request by [[Adrian Boult]], was held at short notice on 29&nbsp;September 1918, during the last weeks of World War I, in the [[Queen's Hall]] with the financial support of Holst's friend and fellow composer [[H. Balfour Gardiner]]. It was hastily rehearsed; the musicians of the Queen's Hall Orchestra first saw the complicated music only two hours before the performance, and the choir for Neptune was recruited from pupils from [[Morley College]] and [[St Paul's Girls' School]] (where Holst taught). It was a comparatively intimate affair, attended by around 250 invited associates,<ref name=Imogen/><ref>\"The Definitive CDs\" (CD 94), of Holst: The Planets (with [[Elgar]]: Enigma Variations), Norman Lebrecht, ''La Scena Musicale'', 1 September 2004, webpage: [http://scena.org/columns/lebrecht/040901-NL-definitivecds.html Scena-Notes-100-CDs].</ref><ref name=DivineArtBoult>{{cite web|title='Sir Adrian Boult' on ''divine-art.com''|url=http://www.divine-art.com/AS/boult.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516211835/http://www.divine-art.com/AS/boult.htm|archivedate=16 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but Holst regarded it as the public premiere, inscribing Boult's copy of the score, \"This copy is the property of Adrian Boult who first caused the Planets to shine in public and thereby earned the gratitude of Gustav Holst.\"<ref name=boult35/>\n[[File:Holst-planets-inscription.jpg|thumb|left|Holst's inscription on Boult's score]]\nA public concert was given in London under the auspices of the [[Royal Philharmonic Society]] on 27 February 1919, conducted by Boult. Five of the seven movements were played in the order Mars, Mercury, Saturn, Uranus, and Jupiter.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/3701637 \"London Concerts\",] ''[[The Musical Times]]'', April 1919, p. 179 {{subscription}}.</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>Holst, Imogen, A Thematic Catalogue of Gustav Holst's Music. Faber, 1974</ref> It was Boult's decision not to play all seven movements at this concert. He felt that when the public were being given a totally new language like that, \"half an hour of it was as much as they could take in\".<ref>Kennedy, p. 68</ref> The anonymous critic in Hazell's Annual called it \"an extraordinarily complex and clever suite\".<ref>Foreman, Lewis, Music in England 1885\u20131920, Thames Publishing, 1994</ref> At a Queen's Hall symphony concert on 22 November of that year, Holst conducted Venus, Mercury and Jupiter (this was the first public performance of Venus).<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/908483 \"London Concerts\",] ''The Musical Times'', January 1920, p. 32 {{subscription}}</ref> There was another incomplete public performance, in [[Birmingham]], on 10 October 1920, with five movements (Mars, Venus, Mercury, Saturn and Jupiter). It is not clear whether this performance was conducted by [[Appleby Matthews]]<ref>Greene (1995), p. 89</ref> or the composer.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/910715 \"Music in the Provinces\",] ''The Musical Times'', 1 November 1920, p. 769; and \"Municipal Music in Birmingham\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', 11 October 1920, p. 6</ref>\n\nHis daughter [[Imogen Holst|Imogen]] recalled, \"He hated incomplete performances of ''The Planets'', though on several occasions he had to agree to conduct three or four movements at Queen's Hall concerts. He particularly disliked having to finish with Jupiter, to make a 'happy ending', for, as he himself said, 'in the real world the end is not happy at all'\".<ref>Holst, Imogen, A Thematic Catalogue of Gustav Holst's Music. Faber, 1974, at page 125</ref>\n\nThe first complete performance of the suite at a public concert did not occur until 15 November 1920; the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO) was conducted by [[Albert Coates (musician)|Albert Coates]]. This was the first time the movement Neptune had been heard in a public performance, all the other movements having been given earlier public airings.<ref name=musical-times>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/910446 \"London Concerts\"'] ''The Musical Times'', December 1920, p. 821 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe composer conducted a complete performance for the first time on 13 October 1923, with the Queen's Hall Orchestra at a Promenade Concert. Holst conducted the LSO in two recorded performances of ''The Planets'': the first was an acoustic recording made in sessions between 1922 and 1924 (now available on Pavilion Records' Pearl label); the second was made in 1926, and utilised the then-new electrical recording process (in 2003, this was released on compact disc by [[IMP records|IMP]] and later on [[Naxos Records|Naxos]] outside the United States).<ref>[http://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.111048 HOLST: Planets (The) (Holst) / VAUGHAN WILLIAMS: Symphony No. 4 (Vaughan Williams) (1926, 1937)] at Naxos.com</ref> Because of the time constraints of the [[78rpm record|78rpm format]], the tempo is often much faster than is usually the case today.<ref>Sanders, Alan, \"Gustav Holst Records The Planets\", ''Gramophone'', September 1976, p. 34</ref>\n\n== Instrumentation ==\nThe work is scored for a large [[orchestra]] consisting of the following instrumentation. The movements vary in the combinations of instruments used.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[Woodwind instrument|Woodwind]]s'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*4 [[western concert flute|flute]]s (third doubling first [[piccolo]] and fourth doubling second [[piccolo]] and \"bass flute in G\", actually an [[alto flute]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hz.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/f/fb/IMSLP53290-PMLP33488-Holst-Planets.Flute34.pdf |title=Combined part of 3rd and 4th flute |format=PDF |accessdate=6 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225203331/http://hz.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/f/fb/IMSLP53290-PMLP33488-Holst-Planets.Flute34.pdf |archive-date=25 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*3 [[oboe]]s (third doubling [[bass oboe]])\n*1 [[Cor anglais]]\n*3 [[clarinet]]s in [[soprano clarinet|B{{music|flat}}]] and A\n*1 [[bass clarinet]] in B{{music|flat}}\n*3 [[bassoon]]s\n*1 [[contrabassoon]]}}\n\n'''[[Brass instrument|Brass]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*6 [[French horn|horns]] in F\n*4 [[trumpet]]s in C\n*2 [[tenor trombone|trombone]]s\n*1 [[bass trombone]]\n*1 [[tuba|tenor tuba]] in B{{music|flat}} (often played on a [[euphonium]])\n*1 [[tuba]]}}\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[Percussion instrument|Percussion]] (4 players)'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*7 [[timpani]] (2 players)\n*[[Bass drum]]\n*[[Snare drum]]\n*[[Cymbal]]s\n*[[triangle (musical instrument)|Triangle]]\n*[[Tam-tam]]\n*[[Tambourine]]\n*[[Glockenspiel]]\n*[[Xylophone]]\n*[[Tubular bells]]}}\n\n'''[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*[[Celesta]]\n*[[Organ (music)|Organ]]}}\n\n'''[[String section|Strings]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*2 [[harp]]s\n*[[Violin]]s I, II\n*[[Viola]]s\n*[[Cello]]s\n*[[Double bass]]es}}\n{{col-end}}\n\nIn \"Neptune\", two three-part [[women's chorus]]es (each comprising two [[soprano]] sections and one [[alto]] section) located in an adjoining room which is to be screened from the audience are added.\n\n== Structure ==\n{{listen\n | filename     = Holst- mars.ogg\n | title        = I. Mars, the Bringer of War\n | description  = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Mars, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n | filename2    = Holst- venus.ogg\n | title2       = II. Venus, the Bringer of Peace\n | description2 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Venus, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format2      = Ogg\n | filename3    = Holst The Planets Mercury.ogg\n | title3       = III. Mercury, the Winged Messenger\n | description3 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Mercury, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | filename4    = Holst The Planets Jupiter.ogg\n | title4       = IV. Jupiter, the Bringer of Jollity\n | description4 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Jupiter, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format4      = [[ogg]]\n | filename5    = Holst- uranus.ogg\n | title5       = VI. Uranus, the Magician\n | description5 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Uranus, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format5      = Ogg\n}}\n\nThe suite has seven movements, each named after a [[planet]] and its corresponding astrological character (see [[Planets in astrology]]):\n\n{{Ordered list|type=upper-roman\n| [[Mars]], the [[Mars (mythology)|Bringer of War]] (1914)\n| [[Venus]], the [[Venus (mythology)|Bringer of Peace]] (1914)\n| [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], the [[Mercury (mythology)|Winged Messenger]] (1916)\n| [[Jupiter]], the [[Jupiter (mythology)|Bringer of Jollity]] (1914)\n| [[Saturn]], the [[Saturn (mythology)|Bringer of Old Age]] (1915)\n| [[Uranus]], the [[Uranus (mythology)|Magician]] (1915)\n| [[Neptune]], the [[Neptune (mythology)|Mystic]] (1915)\n}}\n\nHolst's original title, as seen on the handwritten full score, was \"Seven Pieces for Large Orchestra\".<ref name=Lambourn/> Holst almost certainly attended an early performance of Schoenberg's ''[[Five Pieces for Orchestra]]'' in 1914 (the year he wrote Mars, Venus and Jupiter),{{refn|Holst's appointments diary includes a note of the date of the work's second London performance in January 1914.<ref>Short, p. 103</ref>|group= n}} and owned a score of it,<ref name=CollFacsimEd /><ref>Full score, Bodleian Library MS. Mus.b.18/1-7</ref> the only Schoenberg score he ever owned.<ref name=Lambourn>[http://www.schoenberg.at/library/index.php/attachments/single/1634 David Lambourn, ''Henry Wood and Schoenberg'']{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} from ''The Musical Times'', Vol. 128, No. 1734 (August 1987), pp. 422\u2013427</ref> Each movement of Holst's work was originally called only by the second part of each title (I \"The Bringer of War\", II \"The Bringer of Peace\" and so on); the present titles were added in time for the first (incomplete) public performance in September 1918, though they were never added to the original score.<ref name=CollFacsimEd>''Collected Facsimile Edition'' vol. 3, Faber 1979. Introduction by Imogen Holst</ref>\n\nA typical performance of all seven movements is about fifty minutes long, though Holst's own electric recording from 1926 is just over forty-two and a half minutes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lsBdREh9UEw |title=The Original Original! \"The Planets\" rec. 1926, restored, Holst conducting Holst / London SO |date=2017-03-12 |website=YouTube |access-date=2017-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOne explanation for the suite's structure, presented by Holst scholar Raymond Head, is the ruling of astrological signs of the [[zodiac]] by the planets:<ref>Head (2014): p. 7</ref> if the signs are listed along with their [[ruling planet]]s in the traditional order starting with [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], ignoring duplication and the luminaries (the Sun and Moon), the order of the movements corresponds. Critic [[David Hurwitz (music critic)|David Hurwitz]] offers an alternative explanation for the piece's structure: that Jupiter is the centrepoint of the suite and that the movements on either side are in mirror images. Thus Mars involves motion and Neptune is static; Venus is sublime while Uranus is vulgar, and Mercury is light and ''[[scherzando]]'' while Saturn is heavy and plodding. This hypothesis is lent credence by the fact that the two outer movements, Mars and Neptune, are both written in rather unusual [[quintuple meter]].\n\nHolst suffered neuritis in his right arm, which caused him to seek help from Vally Lasker and Nora Day, two [[amanuenses]], in scoring ''The Planets''.<ref name=CollFacsimEd /><ref>{{cite web |title=Gustav Holst and \u2018The Planets\u2019 |url=https://www.thehistorypress.co.uk/articles/gustav-holst-and-the-planets/ |website=The History Press |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nNeptune was one of the first pieces of orchestral music to have a [[Fade (audio engineering)|fade-out]] ending,<ref>{{cite magazine\n|date= 14 September 2014\n|last= Weir\n|first= William\n|url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2014/09/the_fade_out_in_pop_music_why_don_t_modern_pop_songs_end_by_slowly_reducing.html?wpsrc=fol_tw\n|title= A Little Bit Softer Now, a Little Bit Softer Now \u2026\n|magazine= [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]\n|accessdate= 16 September 2014\n}}</ref> although several composers (including [[Joseph Haydn]] in the finale of his [[Symphony No. 45 (Haydn)|Farewell Symphony]]) had achieved a similar effect by different means. Holst stipulates that the women's choruses are \"to be placed in an adjoining room, the door of which is to be left open until the last bar of the piece, when it is to be slowly and silently closed\", and that the final bar (scored for choruses alone) is \"to be repeated until the sound is lost in the distance\".<ref name=FullScore>\"The Planets\" (full orchestral score): Goodwin & Tabb, Ltd., London, 1921</ref> Although commonplace today, the effect bewitched audiences in the era before widespread recorded sound\u2014after the initial 1918 run-through, Holst's daughter [[Imogen Holst|Imogen]] (in addition to watching the charwomen dancing in the aisles during Jupiter) remarked that the ending was \"unforgettable, with its hidden chorus of women's voices growing fainter and fainter... until the imagination knew no difference between sound and silence\".<ref name=Imogen>\"The Great Composers and Their Music\", Vol. 50, Marshall Cavendish Ltd., London, 1985. I.H. as quoted on p1218</ref>\n\n[[File:St Paul's Girls' School, London 03.jpg|left|thumb|Plaque at [[St Paul's Girls' School]], London]]\n\n==Additions by other composers==\nSeveral attempts have been made, for a variety of reasons, to append further music to Holst's suite, though by far the most common presentation of the music in the concert hall and on record remains Holst's original seven-movement version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philharmonia.co.uk/concerts/1618|title=Holst: The Planets \u2013 Sunday 23 Apr 2017, 3pm \u2013 Royal Festival Hall London \u2013 Philharmonia Orchestra|website=Philharmonia Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/er42mb|title=Prom 14: Holst \u2013 The Planets|website=BBC Music Events}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lso.co.uk/whats-on/icalrepeat.detail/2017/05/18/531/-/holst-the-planets.html|title=London Symphony Orchestra \u2013 Holst The Planets|website=lso.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bachtrack.com/find-concerts/category=1;composer=53;medium=1;work=7161|title=Find classical music concert listings \u2013 Holst \u2013 The Planets, Op.32 \u2013 by Bachtrack for classical music, opera, ballet and dance event reviews|website=bachtrack.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laphil.com/philpedia/music/planets-gustav-holst |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801031731/http://www.laphil.com/philpedia/music/planets-gustav-holst |archive-date=1 August 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Pluto'' ===\n[[Pluto]] was discovered in 1930, four years before Holst's death, and was hailed by [[astronomer]]s as the ninth planet. Holst, however, expressed no interest in writing a movement for the new planet. He had become disillusioned by the popularity of the suite, believing that it took too much attention away from his other works.<ref>Kemp, Linsay (1996) Liner notes to Decca CD 452\u2013303\u20132</ref>\n\nIn the final broadcast of his [[Young People's Concerts]] series in March 1972, the conductor [[Leonard Bernstein]] led the [[New York Philharmonic]] through a fairly straight interpretation of the suite, though he discarded the Saturn movement because he thought the theme of old age was irrelevant to a concert for children. The broadcast concluded with an improvised performance he called \"Pluto, the Unpredictable\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hambrick |first1=Jennifer |title=The Missing Planet: Watch Leonard Bernstein Improvise 'Pluto, the Unpredictable' |url=http://radio.wosu.org/post/missing-planet-watch-leonard-bernstein-improvise-pluto-unpredictable#stream/0 |website=WOSU Public Media |publisher=WOSU Radio |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref> The performance may be viewed on the Kultur DVD set.\n\nIn 2000, the [[The Hall\u00e9|Hall\u00e9 Orchestra]] commissioned the English composer [[Colin Matthews]], an authority on Holst, to write a new eighth movement, which he called \"Pluto, [[Pluto (mythology)|the Renewer]]\". Dedicated to the late [[Imogen Holst]], Gustav Holst's daughter, it was first performed in [[Manchester]] on 11 May 2000, with [[Kent Nagano]] conducting the Hall\u00e9 Orchestra. Matthews also changed the ending of Neptune slightly so that movement would lead directly into Pluto.<ref>Scott Rohan, Michael, [http://www.gramophone.net/Issue/Page/August%202001/50/786842/ Review,] ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'', August 2001, p. 50</ref> Matthews himself has speculated that, the dedication notwithstanding, Imogen Holst \"would have been both amused and dismayed by the venture.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dc.asp?dc=D_CDH55350|title=Holst: The Planets; Matthews: Pluto|website=Hyperion Records}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Earth, from'' The Planets ''by Trouv\u00e8re'' ===\nJapanese composer [[Jun Nagao]] arranged ''The Planets'' for the Trouv\u00e8re Quartet in 2003, including added movements for Earth and Pluto, since the latter was considered a planet at the time. The suite was arranged for concert band and premiered in 2014. The work contains original themes, themes from ''The Planets,'' and other popular Holst melodies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windrep.org/Earth,_The,_from_%22The_Planets%22_by_Trouv%C3%A8re|title=Earth, The, from \"The Planets\" by Trouv\u00e8re|website=Wind Repertory Project|language=en|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\n{{Main|The Planets discography}}\n\n== Adaptations ==\n\n=== Non-orchestral arrangements ===\n*[[Piano four hands|Piano duet (four hands)]] \u2013 an engraved copy of Holst's own piano duet arrangement was found by John York.<ref>Notes from Amazon, webpage: [https://www.amazon.ca/dp/B000058UUS amazon.ca/Planets-World-Premiere].</ref>\n*Two pianos (duo) \u2013 Holst had originally sketched the work for two pianos, due to a need to compensate for the [[neuritis]] in his right arm. His two friends, Nora Day and Vally Lasker, had agreed to play the two-piano arrangement for him as he dictated the details of the orchestral score to them. This they wrote down themselves on the two-piano score, and used as a guide when it was time to create the full orchestral score.<ref>Notes to ''The Planets, Arranged for Two Pianos by the Composer'', J. Curwen & Sons, London.</ref> The two-piano arrangement was published in 1949. Holst's original manuscripts for it are now in the holdings of the Royal College of Music (Mars, Venus, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune), Royal Academy of Music (Mercury) and British Library (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus).<ref>''Holst: Music for Two Pianos'', Naxos catalogue no. 8.554369, [http://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.554369&catNum=554369&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English# ''About This Recording'']</ref>\n*[[Pianola]] \u2013 In the early 1990s an arrangement was made for piano rolls by the English pianolist, Rex Lawson, and published on the Perforetur label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pianola.org/history/history_repertoire.cfm |title=History of the Pianola \u2013 Pianola Repertoire |accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Organ (music)|Organ]] \u2013 American harpsichordist and organist Peter Sykes transcribed ''The Planets'' for organ.<ref>Peter Sykes. \" [http://www.hbdirect.com/album_detail.php?pid=225139 Holst: The Planets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929024606/http://www.hbdirect.com/album_detail.php?pid=225139 |date=29 September 2011 }}.\" HB Direct, Released 1996.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petersykes.com/index1.html |title=Peter Sykes |publisher=Peter Sykes |accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Chamber Orchestra|Ensemble or Chamber Orchestra]] \u2013 English orchestrator George Morton transcribed ''The Planets'' for 15-piece ensemble or chamber orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universaledition.com/The-Planets-Gustav-Holst/composers-and-works/composer/4605/work/15860 |title=Universal Edition |publisher=Universal Edition |accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://georgeconducts.weebly.com/arranging.html |title=George Morton, arranging |publisher=George Morton |accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Synthesizer (music)|Moog]] \u2013 [[Isao Tomita]] adapted ''The Planets'' for a Moog and other synthesizers and electronic devices.<ref>Isao Tomita. \" [http://www.isaotomita.net/recordings/planets.html Tomita's Planets].\" HB Direct, Released 1976</ref> The original LP release prompted legal action from Holst's estate. The composer's daughter, Imogen Holst, worked hard to prevent the recording being distributed in the UK.<ref>Grogan, Christopher. ''Imogen Holst: A Life in Music''. Boydell Press (2010), p. 422</ref> [[Patrick Gleeson]] also recorded an electronic version in 1976 called ''Beyond the Sun''. \n*[[Brass band (British style)|Brass band]] \u2013 Stephen Roberts, associate conductor of the English Symphony Orchestra, transcribed the entire suite for brass band.<ref>[http://www.4barsrest.com/classifieds/cards_detail.asp?id=188 ''Stephen Roberts''] at 4barsrest.com</ref>\n*[[Marching band]] \u2013 the movements Mars, Venus and Jupiter have all been arranged for marching band by [[Jay Bocook]].<ref>[http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/1998/md.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415164416/http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/1998/md.htm |date=15 April 2009 }}</ref> Paul Murtha also arranged the chorale section of Jupiter for marching band.,<ref>[http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/2002/grade2.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725032656/http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/2002/grade2.htm |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref> Kevin Shah and Tony Nunez created a work on Jupiter entitled \"Bringer of Joy\" as well [http://www.projectrisemusic.com/index.php/marching-band/184 Project Rise Music \u00bb Marching Band]\n*[[Concert band]] \u2013 there are numerous transcriptions of the whole Suite for concert band.\n*[[Percussion ensemble]] \u2013 James Ancona arranged ''Mercury'' for a percussion ensemble. It consisted of 2 [[glockenspiel]]s, 2 [[xylophone]]s, 2 [[vibraphone]]s, 2 [[marimba]]s, 5 [[timpani]], a small suspended [[cymbal]], and 2 [[Triangle (musical instrument)|triangles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tapspace.com/Mercury-from-The-Planets-pr-51.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731221534/http://www.tapspace.com/Mercury-from-The-Planets-pr-51.html|url-status=dead|title=Tapspace :: Solo & Ensemble :: Mercury (from \"The Planets\")|archivedate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Drum and bugle corps (modern)|Drum corps]] \u2013 selections from ''The Planets'' were performed by [[The Cavaliers Drum and Bugle Corps|The Cavaliers]] as part of their 1985 repertoire, and as the entirety of their 1995 feature field show, as well as appearing in their 2017 production \"Men Are From Mars\".<ref>[http://www.corpsreps.com/corpsreps.cfm?view=corpsdet&corps=9&corpstype=Junior, \"Song History for The Cavaliers\"], Retrieved 31 March 2013</ref> A similar performance was recorded for CD by [[Star of Indiana]] as part of their ''Brass Theater'' series.\n* [[Rock music|Rock]] bands:\n:*[[King Crimson]] performed a rock arrangement of \"Mars\" at their live shows in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2006/11/king-crimson-mars2.html|title=King Crimson \u2013 Mars|work=Paste Magazine}}</ref> The band intended to make a studio recording of \"Mars\" for their second album, ''[[In the Wake of Poseidon]]'', in 1970.  However, this plan was met with resistance from Holst's estate, and the band instead composed a new piece of similar structure, \"The Devil's Triangle,\" for the album.\n:*[[Emerson, Lake & Powell]], whose bassist [[Greg Lake]] had been a member of King Crimson during 1969\u201370, recorded a version of \"Mars\" for [[Emerson, Lake & Powell (album)|their eponymous studio album]] in 1986.\n:*[[Death metal]] band [[Aeon]] recorded a version of \"Neptune, the Mystic\" for their album ''[[Aeons Black]]''. Though much shorter than the original it was derived from a select few of the main melodies <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalblade.com/us/releases/aeon-aeons-black/|title=Aeon \"Aeons Black\"|work=Metal Blade Records}}</ref>\n:*British Metal bands: the introduction to Diamond Head's \"[[Am I Evil?]]\", as well as the main riff from \"[[Black Sabbath (song)|Black Sabbath]]\" and the bridge from \"[[Children of the Grave]]\" by [[Black Sabbath]], are loosely based on \"Mars.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diamond-head.net/article1.JPG |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825015447/http://www.diamond-head.net/article1.JPG |archivedate=25 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00vlq0y/Classic_Albums_Black_Sabbath_Paranoid/ |title=BBC Two \u2013 Classic Albums, Black Sabbath: Paranoid |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=26 October 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref> On their 1990 tour promoting the album ''[[Tyr (album)|Tyr]]'' parts of \"Mars\" are used as playback during [[Cozy Powell]]'s drum solo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=shFNwPet7v0|title=Black Sabbath Dies Irae [Full Bootleg \u2013 Live in Italy \u2013 1990]|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvgfk9zjGXc|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] used parts of \"Jupiter\" as a taped intro to their gigs in the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rc0wBwkSC6I|title=Saxon \u2013 10 Years Of Denim And Leather 1989 Full Concert|first=|last=Malfarius|date=3 March 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n* Japanese singer [[Ayaka Hirahara]] released a pop version of \"Jupiter\" in December 2003. It went to No. 2 on the [[Oricon]] charts and sold nearly a million copies, making it the third-best-selling single in the [[J-pop|Japanese popular music]] market for 2004. It remained on the charts for over three years.<ref>[http://www.last.fm/music/%E5%B9%B3%E5%8E%9F%E7%B6%BE%E9%A6%99 \u5e73\u539f\u7dbe\u9999 (''Hirahara Ayaka'')] at last.fm {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n\n=== Hymns ===\n{{main|Thaxted (tune)}}\n\nHolst adapted the melody of the central section of ''Jupiter'' in 1921 to fit the metre of a poem beginning \"[[I Vow to Thee, My Country]]\". As a [[hymn tune]] it has the title ''[[Thaxted (tune)|Thaxted]]'', after the [[Thaxted|town in Essex]] where Holst lived for many years, and it has also been used for other hymns, such as \"O God beyond all praising\"<ref>{{cite web|title=O God Beyond All Praising|work=Oremus|url=http://www.oremus.org/hymnal/o/o153.html|accessdate=1 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416033808/http://www.oremus.org/hymnal/o/o153.html|archivedate=16 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and \"We Praise You and Acknowledge You\" with lyrics by Rev. Stephen P. Starke.<ref>{{cite web|title=We Praise You and Acknowledge You, O God|work=Hymnary.org|url=https://hymnary.org/text/we_praise_you_and_acknowledge_you_o_god|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> \n\n\"I Vow to Thee, My Country\" was written between 1908 and 1918 by Sir [[Cecil Spring Rice]] and became known as a response to the human cost of World War I. The hymn was first performed in 1925 and quickly became a patriotic anthem. Although Holst had no such patriotic intentions when he originally composed the music, these adaptations have encouraged others{{Who|date=March 2010}} to draw upon the score in similar ways throughout the 20th century.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nThe melody was also adapted and set to lyrics by [[Charlie Skarbek]] and titled \"[[World in Union]]\".<ref name=\"Raynor\">{{cite news |last1=Rayner |first1=Gordon |title=Rugby World Cup: fans petition ITV to replace 'truly awful' Paloma Faith theme music |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/rugby-world-cup/11888395/Rugby-World-Cup-fans-petition-ITV-to-replace-truly-awful-Paloma-Faith-theme-music.html |accessdate=March 28, 2017 |work=The Telegraph|date=September 24, 2015 |language=en}}</ref> The song is used as the theme song for the [[Rugby World Cup]] and appears in most television coverage and before matches.<ref name=\"Raynor\"/>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* [[Bell's Brewery]] claims that the suite served as an inspiration for its ''The Planets Series'' of beers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gabler |first1=Jay |title=Holst and hops: Bells Brewery releasing beers inspired by \"The Planets\" |url=https://www.classicalmpr.org/blog/classical-notes/2014/07/08/holst_and_hops |website=Classical MPR |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=Jul 8, 2014}}</ref>  \n* [[Robert A. Heinlein]] references ''Mars'' in his novel, [[Stranger in a Strange Land]], used to establish Valentine Michael Smith's credentials when meeting the president.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Heinlein |first1=Robert |title=Stranger in a Strange Land |date=1961 |publisher=G. P. Putnam's Sons |isbn=978-0-441-79034-0 |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/334327/stranger-in-a-strange-land-by-robert-a-heinlein/}}</ref> \n* [[Bill Conti]] was strongly influenced by ''Neptune'' and ''Jupiter'' in his soundtrack for the 1983 film [[The Right Stuff (film)|The Right Stuff]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lochner |first1=Jim |title=CD Review: The Right Stuff |url=https://filmscoreclicktrack.com/cd-review-the-right-stuff/ |website=filmscoreclicktrack.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[King Crimson]]'s song \"The Devil\u2019s Triangle\" from [[In the Wake of Poseidon]] was adapted from ''Mars''.<ref name=\"devils_triangle\">{{cite book|last1=Martin|first1=Bill|title=Listening to the Future: The Time of Progressive Rock, 1968-1978|date=December 1, 1998|publisher=Carus Publishing|location=Chicago and La Salle, Illinois|isbn=9780812693683|page=186}}</ref> \n* [[Doctor Who]] features a brief excerpt from \"The Devil\u2019s Triangle\" in [[The Mind of Evil]].<ref name=\"devils_triangle\"/>\n* [[The Man Who Fell to Earth]] features excerpts of ''Venus'' and ''Mars''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gent |first1=James |title=\u2018The Man Who Fell To Earth: Original Soundtrack\u2019 |url=http://wearecult.rocks/the-man-who-fell-to-earth-original-soundtrack |website=We Are Cult |date=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Jazz fusion band Safety Squad used the famous rhythm from ''Mars'' in their song \"Mr. Mungo's Revenge\"<ref>Safety Squad [https://safetysquad.bandcamp.com/track/mr-mungos-revenge \"Mr Mungo's Revenge\"] (Apr 6, 2018).</ref>  \n* [[The Simpsons]] episode [['Scuse Me While I Miss the Sky]] features extracts of the beginning of ''Jupiter'' due to astronomy being the main subject of the episode.<ref name=\"Simpsons\">{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=James |title=This Flash Mob of Holst's 'Jupiter' Will Bring You Jollity |url=https://www.wqxr.org/story/flash-mob-holst-jupiter-bring-jollity/ |website=wqxr.org |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n* [[The Simpsons]] episode [[The Regina Monologues]] features an extract from ''Mars'' in a flashback scene to World War 2.<ref name=\"Simpsons\"/>\n* [[Mr. Robot]] features ''Neptune'' in the pre-credits sequence of Season 2, Episode 4.<ref name=\"Mr. Robot Soundtrack: S2 \u00b7 E4 \u00b7 eps2.2_init1.asec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/mr-robot/season-2/33420|accessdate=2018-11-22|title=Mr. Robot Soundtrack: S2 \u00b7 E4 \u00b7 eps2.2_init1.asec|publisher=tunefind.com}}</ref>\n* [[John Williams]] used the melodies and instrumentation of ''Mars'' as the inspiration for his soundtrack for the [[Star Wars]] films (specifically \"[[The Imperial March]]\")<ref>Shobe, Michael. and Kim Nowack. [http://www.wqxr.org/story/throwback-thursday-classical-music-influences-inside-john-williams-star-wars-score/ \"The Classical Music Influences Inside John Williams' 'Star Wars' Score,\"] WQXR (Dec 17, 2015).</ref>\n* [[Hans Zimmer]] closely used the melodies, instrumentation and orchestration of ''Mars'' as the inspiration for his soundtrack for the movie [[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]] to the extent that a lawsuit for [[copyright infringement]] was filed by the Holst foundation <ref>Carlsson, Mikael. [http://www.filmmusicmag.com/?p=638 \"Zimmer sued over 'Gladiator' music\"] (Jun 12, 2006).</ref>\n\n==Other Use==\n*[[East Japan Railway Company|JR East]] in [[Japan]] uses several part from \"Jupiter, the Bringer of Jollity\" as [[Train melody|departure Melody]] for some stations in the Greater [[Kant\u014d region]].\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Musica universalis]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist| group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|last=Boult|first=Adrian|title=My Own Trumpet|location=London|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|date=1973|isbn=0-241-02445-5 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Greene|first=Richard|title=Holst: The Planets|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|date=1995|isbn=0-521-45633-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Head|first=Raymond|title=Gustav Holst: The Planets Suite - New Light on a Famous Work|publisher=Sky Dance Press|date=2014|isbn=978-0-9928464-0-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|title=Adrian Boult|url=https://archive.org/details/adrianboult00kenn|url-access=registration|location=London|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|date=1987|isbn=0-333-48752-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lebrecht|first=Norman|title=The Life and Death of Classical Music: Featuring the 100 Best and 20 Worst Recordings Ever Made|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qgTD-NwZ3CYC&pg=PA240|date=2008|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-48746-9|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Short|first=Michael|title=Gustav Holst: The Man and his Music|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1990|isbn=0-19-314154-X}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Links to public domain scores of ''The Planets'':\n** [https://archive.org/details/Holst_ThePlanets The Planets: Suite for Large Orchestra] (Score in the Public Domain)\n** {{IMSLP2|work=The_Planets:_Suite_for_Large_Orchestra_%28Holst%2C_Gustav%29|cname=The Planets}}\n** [http://www.mutopiaproject.org/ftp/HolstGT/Thaxted/Thaxted-let.pdf ''Thaxted'' sheet music] (PDF)\n* Online recordings:\n** [http://www.aquarianage.org/lore/holst.html Free MIDI recordings] of \"The Planets\" (containing some errors, however)\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086116/ IMDB entry for the 1983 Ken Russell documentary ''The Planets'']\n* Sheet music:\n** [https://galaxymusicnotes.com/collections/gustav-holst The Planets Suite] (contains rare complete piano arrangement of Jupiter)\n\n{{Gustav Holst}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Planets, The}}\n[[Category:Suites by Gustav Holst]]\n[[Category:History of astrology]]\n[[Category:Music for orchestra and organ]]\n[[Category:1916 compositions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Orchestral suite by Gustav Holst}}\n{{About|the orchestral suite by Gustav Holst|the celestial body|Planet|the planets in the solar system|Solar System|other uses|Planet (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n|name=''The Planets''\n|type=[[Orchestral suite]]\n|composer=[[Gustav Holst]]\n|image=Gustav Holst.jpg\n|opus=32\n|based_on=[[Planets in astrology]]\n|composed={{start date|1914}}\u201316\n|movements=seven\n|scoring=[[Orchestra]]\n|premiere_date={{start date|1918|09|29|df=y}}\n|premiere_conductor=[[Adrian Boult]]\n|premiere_location=[[Queen's Hall]], London}}\n'''''The Planets''''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 32, is a seven-[[Movement (music)|movement]] orchestral [[Suite (music)|suite]] by the English composer [[Gustav Holst]], written between 1914 and 1916. Each movement of the suite is named after a [[planet]] of the [[solar system]] and its corresponding [[planets in astrology|astrological]] character as defined by Holst.\n\nFrom its premiere to the present day, the suite has been enduringly popular, influential, widely performed and frequently recorded. The work was not heard in a complete public performance, however, until some years after it was completed. Although there were four performances between September 1918 and October 1920, they were all either private (the first performance, in London) or incomplete (two others in London and one in [[Birmingham]]). The premiere was at the [[Queen's Hall]] on 29 September 1918,{{sfn|Lebrecht|2008|p=240}} conducted by Holst's friend [[Adrian Boult]] before an invited audience of about 250 people. The first complete public performance was finally given in London by [[Albert Coates (musician)|Albert Coates]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] on 15 November 1920.<ref name=musical-times/>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Queen's Hall London.jpg|thumb|300px|right| The [[Queen's Hall]], in London, where ''The Planets'' premiered in 1918]]\nThe concept of the work is [[Astrology|astrological]]<ref name=HolstLM>\"HOLST Suite: The Planets\" (compares compositions & history), Len Mullenger, Olton Recorded Music Society, January 2000, webpage: [http://www.musicweb.uk.net/holst.htm MusicWebUK-Holst]: in 1913 [[Gustav Holst|Holst]] went on holiday to [[Majorca]] with [[Balfour Gardiner]], [[Arnold Bax]], and his brother [[Clifford Bax]], and who spent the entire holiday discussing astrology.</ref> rather than [[astronomy|astronomical]] (which is why [[Earth]] is not included, although [[Planets in astrology#Sun|Sun and Moon]] are also not included while including the non-traditional Uranus and Neptune): each movement is intended to convey ideas and emotions associated with the [[Planets in astrology|influence of the planets on the psyche]], not the [[Dii Consentes|Roman deities]]. The idea of the work was suggested to Holst by [[Clifford Bax]], who introduced him to astrology when the two were part of a small group of English artists holidaying in [[Majorca]] in the spring of 1913; Holst became quite a devotee of the subject, and would cast his friends' horoscopes for fun.<ref name=HolstLM/><ref name=Imogen/> Holst also used [[Alan Leo]]'s<ref name=HolstLM/> book ''What is a Horoscope?'' as a springboard for his own ideas, as well as for the subtitles (e.g., \"The Bringer of...\") for the movements.\n\nOn 17 January 1914 Holst attended a performance of [[Arnold Schoenberg]]'s ''[[Five Pieces for Orchestra]]'', at the Queen's Hall, conducted by Schoenberg's pupil [[Edward Clark (conductor)|Edward Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoenberg.at/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1014&Itemid=726&lang=en|title=1914 \u2022 Herr Sch\u00f6nberg in London|website=www.schoenberg.at}}</ref><ref name=keller>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wo4LhjGd-c4C&pg=PA21&lpg=PA21&dq=edward+clark+schoenberg&source=bl&ots=QiyjCnfRPT&sig=TxCP-0cN1hG86dsaiLr7tQLzsfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Xh8JUYfnAu2cmQWPyoG4DQ&ved=0CFUQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=edward+clark+schoenberg&f=false|title=Hans Keller and the BBC: The Musical Conscience of British Broadcasting, 1959\u201379|first=Alison|last=Garnham|date=23 October 2003|publisher=Ashgate|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CVCtkShvDSkC&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=Peter+Eckersley+edward+clark&source=bl&ots=G54LQFEhBQ&sig=3Hc2HGDA3blOjFRYYyTvdOH-EoM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eSsKUfW0CKaLmwX28YD4Dg&sqi=2&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=clark&f=false|title=The BBC and Ultra-Modern Music, 1922\u20131936: Shaping a Nation's Tastes|first1=Jennifer|last1=Doctor|first2=Jennifer Ruth|last2=Doctor|date=23 October 1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> Holst quickly acquired a copy of the score, the only Schoenberg score he ever owned. This influenced Holst at least to the degree that the working title of his own composition was ''Seven Pieces for Large Orchestra''.<ref>[http://www.schoenberg.at/library/index.php/attachments/single/1634 David Lambourn, \"Henry Wood and Schoenberg\", The Musical Times, Vol. 128, No. 1734 (August 1987), pp. 422\u201327]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>\n\nWhen composing ''The Planets'' Holst initially scored the work for four hands, two pianos, except for Neptune, which was scored for a [[Organ (music)|single organ]], as Holst believed that the sound of the piano was too percussive for a world as mysterious and distant as Neptune. Holst then scored the suite for a large orchestra, in which form it became enormously popular. Holst's use of orchestration was very imaginative and colourful, showing the influence of such contemporary composers as [[Igor Stravinsky]]<ref>Short, p. 131</ref> and [[Arnold Schoenberg]],<ref name=HolstLM/> as well as such late Russian romantics as [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] and [[Alexander Glazunov]]. Its novel sonorities helped make the work an immediate success with audiences at home and abroad. Although ''The Planets'' remains Holst's most popular work, the composer himself did not count it among his best creations and later in life complained that its popularity had completely surpassed his other works. He was, however, partial to his own favourite movement, Saturn.<ref>Boult, Sir Adrian (1967), Liner note to EMI CD 5 66934 2</ref>\n\n==Premieres==\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center|quote =Just before the Armistice, Gustav Holst burst into my office: \"Adrian, the YMCA are sending me to [[Thessaloniki|Salonika]] quite soon and [[H. Balfour Gardiner|Balfour Gardiner]], bless his heart, has given me a parting present consisting of the [[Queen's Hall]], full of the Queen's Hall Orchestra for the whole of a Sunday morning. So we're going to do ''The Planets'', and you've got to conduct.\" | source =  Adrian Boult<ref name=boult35>Boult p. 35</ref>| align=right| width=33%}}\n\nThe orchestral premiere of ''The Planets'' suite, conducted at Holst's request by [[Adrian Boult]], was held at short notice on 29&nbsp;September 1918, during the last weeks of World War I, in the [[Queen's Hall]] with the financial support of Holst's friend and fellow composer [[H. Balfour Gardiner]]. It was hastily rehearsed; the musicians of the Queen's Hall Orchestra first saw the complicated music only two hours before the performance, and the choir for Neptune was recruited from pupils from [[Morley College]] and [[St Paul's Girls' School]] (where Holst taught). It was a comparatively intimate affair, attended by around 250 invited associates,<ref name=Imogen/><ref>\"The Definitive CDs\" (CD 94), of Holst: The Planets (with [[Elgar]]: Enigma Variations), Norman Lebrecht, ''La Scena Musicale'', 1 September 2004, webpage: [http://scena.org/columns/lebrecht/040901-NL-definitivecds.html Scena-Notes-100-CDs].</ref><ref name=DivineArtBoult>{{cite web|title='Sir Adrian Boult' on ''divine-art.com''|url=http://www.divine-art.com/AS/boult.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516211835/http://www.divine-art.com/AS/boult.htm|archivedate=16 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but Holst regarded it as the public premiere, inscribing Boult's copy of the score, \"This copy is the property of Adrian Boult who first caused the Planets to shine in public and thereby earned the gratitude of Gustav Holst.\"<ref name=boult35/>\n[[File:Holst-planets-inscription.jpg|thumb|left|Holst's inscription on Boult's score]]\nA public concert was given in London under the auspices of the [[Royal Philharmonic Society]] on 27 February 1919, conducted by Boult. Five of the seven movements were played in the order Mars, Mercury, Saturn, Uranus, and Jupiter.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/3701637 \"London Concerts\",] ''[[The Musical Times]]'', April 1919, p. 179 {{subscription}}.</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>Holst, Imogen, A Thematic Catalogue of Gustav Holst's Music. Faber, 1974</ref> It was Boult's decision not to play all seven movements at this concert. He felt that when the public were being given a totally new language like that, \"half an hour of it was as much as they could take in\".<ref>Kennedy, p. 68</ref> The anonymous critic in Hazell's Annual called it \"an extraordinarily complex and clever suite\".<ref>Foreman, Lewis, Music in England 1885\u20131920, Thames Publishing, 1994</ref> At a Queen's Hall symphony concert on 22 November of that year, Holst conducted Venus, Mercury and Jupiter (this was the first public performance of Venus).<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/908483 \"London Concerts\",] ''The Musical Times'', January 1920, p. 32 {{subscription}}</ref> There was another incomplete public performance, in [[Birmingham]], on 10 October 1920, with five movements (Mars, Venus, Mercury, Saturn and Jupiter). It is not clear whether this performance was conducted by [[Appleby Matthews]]<ref>Greene (1995), p. 89</ref> or the composer.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/910715 \"Music in the Provinces\",] ''The Musical Times'', 1 November 1920, p. 769; and \"Municipal Music in Birmingham\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', 11 October 1920, p. 6</ref>\n\nHis daughter [[Imogen Holst|Imogen]] recalled, \"He hated incomplete performances of ''The Planets'', though on several occasions he had to agree to conduct three or four movements at Queen's Hall concerts. He particularly disliked having to finish with Jupiter, to make a 'happy ending', for, as he himself said, 'in the real world the end is not happy at all'\".<ref>Holst, Imogen, A Thematic Catalogue of Gustav Holst's Music. Faber, 1974, at page 125</ref>\n\nThe first complete performance of the suite at a public concert did not occur until 15 November 1920; the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO) was conducted by [[Albert Coates (musician)|Albert Coates]]. This was the first time the movement Neptune had been heard in a public performance, all the other movements having been given earlier public airings.<ref name=musical-times>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/910446 \"London Concerts\"'] ''The Musical Times'', December 1920, p. 821 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe composer conducted a complete performance for the first time on 13 October 1923, with the Queen's Hall Orchestra at a Promenade Concert. Holst conducted the LSO in two recorded performances of ''The Planets'': the first was an acoustic recording made in sessions between 1922 and 1924 (now available on Pavilion Records' Pearl label); the second was made in 1926, and utilised the then-new electrical recording process (in 2003, this was released on compact disc by [[IMP records|IMP]] and later on [[Naxos Records|Naxos]] outside the United States).<ref>[http://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.111048 HOLST: Planets (The) (Holst) / VAUGHAN WILLIAMS: Symphony No. 4 (Vaughan Williams) (1926, 1937)] at Naxos.com</ref> Because of the time constraints of the [[78rpm record|78rpm format]], the tempo is often much faster than is usually the case today.<ref>Sanders, Alan, \"Gustav Holst Records The Planets\", ''Gramophone'', September 1976, p. 34</ref>\n\n== Instrumentation ==\nThe work is scored for a large [[orchestra]] consisting of the following instrumentation. The movements vary in the combinations of instruments used.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[Woodwind instrument|Woodwind]]s'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*4 [[western concert flute|flute]]s (third doubling first [[piccolo]] and fourth doubling second [[piccolo]] and \"bass flute in G\", actually an [[alto flute]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hz.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/f/fb/IMSLP53290-PMLP33488-Holst-Planets.Flute34.pdf |title=Combined part of 3rd and 4th flute |format=PDF |accessdate=6 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225203331/http://hz.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/f/fb/IMSLP53290-PMLP33488-Holst-Planets.Flute34.pdf |archive-date=25 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*3 [[oboe]]s (third doubling [[bass oboe]])\n*1 [[Cor anglais]]\n*3 [[clarinet]]s in [[soprano clarinet|B{{music|flat}}]] and A\n*1 [[bass clarinet]] in B{{music|flat}}\n*3 [[bassoon]]s\n*1 [[contrabassoon]]}}\n\n'''[[Brass instrument|Brass]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*6 [[French horn|horns]] in F\n*4 [[trumpet]]s in C\n*2 [[tenor trombone|trombone]]s\n*1 [[bass trombone]]\n*1 [[tuba|tenor tuba]] in B{{music|flat}} (often played on a [[euphonium]])\n*1 [[tuba]]}}\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[Percussion instrument|Percussion]] (4 players)'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*7 [[timpani]] (2 players)\n*[[Bass drum]]\n*[[Snare drum]]\n*[[Cymbal]]s\n*[[triangle (musical instrument)|Triangle]]\n*[[Tam-tam]]\n*[[Tambourine]]\n*[[Glockenspiel]]\n*[[Xylophone]]\n*[[Tubular bells]]}}\n\n'''[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*[[Celesta]]\n*[[Organ (music)|Organ]]}}\n\n'''[[String section|Strings]]'''{{plainlist|style=margin-left:1em|\n*2 [[harp]]s\n*[[Violin]]s I, II\n*[[Viola]]s\n*[[Cello]]s\n*[[Double bass]]es}}\n{{col-end}}\n\nIn \"Neptune\", two three-part [[women's chorus]]es (each comprising two [[soprano]] sections and one [[alto]] section) located in an adjoining room which is to be screened from the audience are added.\n\n== Structure ==\n{{listen\n | filename     = Holst- mars.ogg\n | title        = I. Mars, the Bringer of War\n | description  = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Mars, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n | filename2    = Holst- venus.ogg\n | title2       = II. Venus, the Bringer of Peace\n | description2 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Venus, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format2      = Ogg\n | filename3    = Holst The Planets Mercury.ogg\n | title3       = III. Mercury, the Winged Messenger\n | description3 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Mercury, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | filename4    = Holst The Planets Jupiter.ogg\n | title4       = IV. Jupiter, the Bringer of Jollity\n | description4 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Jupiter, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format4      = [[ogg]]\n | filename5    = Holst- uranus.ogg\n | title5       = VI. Uranus, the Magician\n | description5 = A [[concert band]] arrangement of Uranus, from ''The Planets'', performed by the United States Air Force Heritage of America Band\n | format5      = Ogg\n}}\n\nThe suite has seven movements, each named after a [[planet]] and its corresponding astrological character (see [[Planets in astrology]]):\n\n{{Ordered list|type=upper-roman\n| [[Mars]], the [[Mars (mythology)|Bringer of War]] (1914)\n| [[Venus]], the [[Venus (mythology)|Bringer of Peace]] (1914)\n| [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], the [[Mercury (mythology)|Winged Messenger]] (1916)\n| [[Jupiter]], the [[Jupiter (mythology)|Bringer of Jollity]] (1914)\n| [[Saturn]], the [[Saturn (mythology)|Bringer of Old Age]] (1915)\n| [[Uranus]], the [[Uranus (mythology)|Magician]] (1915)\n| [[Neptune]], the [[Neptune (mythology)|Mystic]] (1915)\n}}\n\nHolst's original title, as seen on the handwritten full score, was \"Seven Pieces for Large Orchestra\".<ref name=Lambourn/> Holst almost certainly attended an early performance of Schoenberg's ''[[Five Pieces for Orchestra]]'' in 1914 (the year he wrote Mars, Venus and Jupiter),{{refn|Holst's appointments diary includes a note of the date of the work's second London performance in January 1914.<ref>Short, p. 103</ref>|group= n}} and owned a score of it,<ref name=CollFacsimEd /><ref>Full score, Bodleian Library MS. Mus.b.18/1-7</ref> the only Schoenberg score he ever owned.<ref name=Lambourn>[http://www.schoenberg.at/library/index.php/attachments/single/1634 David Lambourn, ''Henry Wood and Schoenberg'']{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} from ''The Musical Times'', Vol. 128, No. 1734 (August 1987), pp. 422\u2013427</ref> Each movement of Holst's work was originally called only by the second part of each title (I \"The Bringer of War\", II \"The Bringer of Peace\" and so on); the present titles were added in time for the first (incomplete) public performance in September 1918, though they were never added to the original score.<ref name=CollFacsimEd>''Collected Facsimile Edition'' vol. 3, Faber 1979. Introduction by Imogen Holst</ref>\n\nA typical performance of all seven movements is about fifty minutes long, though Holst's own electric recording from 1926 is just over forty-two and a half minutes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lsBdREh9UEw |title=The Original Original! \"The Planets\" rec. 1926, restored, Holst conducting Holst / London SO |date=2017-03-12 |website=YouTube |access-date=2017-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOne explanation for the suite's structure, presented by Holst scholar Raymond Head, is the ruling of astrological signs of the [[zodiac]] by the planets:<ref>Head (2014): p. 7</ref> if the signs are listed along with their [[ruling planet]]s in the traditional order starting with [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], ignoring duplication and the luminaries (the Sun and Moon), the order of the movements corresponds. Critic [[David Hurwitz (music critic)|David Hurwitz]] offers an alternative explanation for the piece's structure: that Jupiter is the centrepoint of the suite and that the movements on either side are in mirror images. Thus Mars involves motion and Neptune is static; Venus is sublime while Uranus is vulgar, and Mercury is light and ''[[scherzando]]'' while Saturn is heavy and plodding. This hypothesis is lent credence by the fact that the two outer movements, Mars and Neptune, are both written in rather unusual [[quintuple meter]].\n\nHolst suffered neuritis in his right arm, which caused him to seek help from Vally Lasker and Nora Day, two [[amanuenses]], in scoring ''The Planets''.<ref name=CollFacsimEd /><ref>{{cite web |title=Gustav Holst and \u2018The Planets\u2019 |url=https://www.thehistorypress.co.uk/articles/gustav-holst-and-the-planets/ |website=The History Press |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nNeptune was one of the first pieces of orchestral music to have a [[Fade (audio engineering)|fade-out]] ending,<ref>{{cite magazine\n|date= 14 September 2014\n|last= Weir\n|first= William\n|url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2014/09/the_fade_out_in_pop_music_why_don_t_modern_pop_songs_end_by_slowly_reducing.html?wpsrc=fol_tw\n|title= A Little Bit Softer Now, a Little Bit Softer Now \u2026\n|magazine= [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]\n|accessdate= 16 September 2014\n}}</ref> although several composers (including [[Joseph Haydn]] in the finale of his [[Symphony No. 45 (Haydn)|Farewell Symphony]]) had achieved a similar effect by different means. Holst stipulates that the women's choruses are \"to be placed in an adjoining room, the door of which is to be left open until the last bar of the piece, when it is to be slowly and silently closed\", and that the final bar (scored for choruses alone) is \"to be repeated until the sound is lost in the distance\".<ref name=FullScore>\"The Planets\" (full orchestral score): Goodwin & Tabb, Ltd., London, 1921</ref> Although commonplace today, the effect bewitched audiences in the era before widespread recorded sound\u2014after the initial 1918 run-through, Holst's daughter [[Imogen Holst|Imogen]] (in addition to watching the charwomen dancing in the aisles during Jupiter) remarked that the ending was \"unforgettable, with its hidden chorus of women's voices growing fainter and fainter... until the imagination knew no difference between sound and silence\".<ref name=Imogen>\"The Great Composers and Their Music\", Vol. 50, Marshall Cavendish Ltd., London, 1985. I.H. as quoted on p1218</ref>\n\n[[File:St Paul's Girls' School, London 03.jpg|left|thumb|Plaque at [[St Paul's Girls' School]], London]]\n\n==Additions by other composers==\nSeveral attempts have been made, for a variety of reasons, to append further music to Holst's suite, though by far the most common presentation of the music in the concert hall and on record remains Holst's original seven-movement version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philharmonia.co.uk/concerts/1618|title=Holst: The Planets \u2013 Sunday 23 Apr 2017, 3pm \u2013 Royal Festival Hall London \u2013 Philharmonia Orchestra|website=Philharmonia Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/er42mb|title=Prom 14: Holst \u2013 The Planets|website=BBC Music Events}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lso.co.uk/whats-on/icalrepeat.detail/2017/05/18/531/-/holst-the-planets.html|title=London Symphony Orchestra \u2013 Holst The Planets|website=lso.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bachtrack.com/find-concerts/category=1;composer=53;medium=1;work=7161|title=Find classical music concert listings \u2013 Holst \u2013 The Planets, Op.32 \u2013 by Bachtrack for classical music, opera, ballet and dance event reviews|website=bachtrack.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laphil.com/philpedia/music/planets-gustav-holst |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801031731/http://www.laphil.com/philpedia/music/planets-gustav-holst |archive-date=1 August 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Pluto'' ===\n[[Pluto]] was discovered in 1930, four years before Holst's death, and was hailed by [[astronomer]]s as the ninth planet. Holst, however, expressed no interest in writing a movement for the new planet. He had become disillusioned by the popularity of the suite, believing that it took too much attention away from his other works.<ref>Kemp, Linsay (1996) Liner notes to Decca CD 452\u2013303\u20132</ref>\n\nIn the final broadcast of his [[Young People's Concerts]] series in March 1972, the conductor [[Leonard Bernstein]] led the [[New York Philharmonic]] through a fairly straight interpretation of the suite, though he discarded the Saturn movement because he thought the theme of old age was irrelevant to a concert for children. The broadcast concluded with an improvised performance he called \"Pluto, the Unpredictable\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hambrick |first1=Jennifer |title=The Missing Planet: Watch Leonard Bernstein Improvise 'Pluto, the Unpredictable' |url=http://radio.wosu.org/post/missing-planet-watch-leonard-bernstein-improvise-pluto-unpredictable#stream/0 |website=WOSU Public Media |publisher=WOSU Radio |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref> The performance may be viewed on the Kultur DVD set.\n\nIn 2000, the [[The Hall\u00e9|Hall\u00e9 Orchestra]] commissioned the English composer [[Colin Matthews]], an authority on Holst, to write a new eighth movement, which he called \"Pluto, [[Pluto (mythology)|the Renewer]]\". Dedicated to the late [[Imogen Holst]], Gustav Holst's daughter, it was first performed in [[Manchester]] on 11 May 2000, with [[Kent Nagano]] conducting the Hall\u00e9 Orchestra. Matthews also changed the ending of Neptune slightly so that movement would lead directly into Pluto.<ref>Scott Rohan, Michael, [http://www.gramophone.net/Issue/Page/August%202001/50/786842/ Review,] ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'', August 2001, p. 50</ref> Matthews himself has speculated that, the dedication notwithstanding, Imogen Holst \"would have been both amused and dismayed by the venture.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dc.asp?dc=D_CDH55350|title=Holst: The Planets; Matthews: Pluto|website=Hyperion Records}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Earth, from'' The Planets ''by Trouv\u00e8re'' ===\nJapanese composer [[Jun Nagao]] arranged ''The Planets'' for the Trouv\u00e8re Quartet in 2003, including added movements for Earth and Pluto, since the latter was considered a planet at the time. The suite was arranged for concert band and premiered in 2014. The work contains original themes, themes from ''The Planets,'' and other popular Holst melodies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windrep.org/Earth,_The,_from_%22The_Planets%22_by_Trouv%C3%A8re|title=Earth, The, from \"The Planets\" by Trouv\u00e8re|website=Wind Repertory Project|language=en|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\n{{Main|The Planets discography}}\n\n== Adaptations ==\n\n=== Non-orchestral arrangements ===\n*[[Piano four hands|Piano duet (four hands)]] \u2013 an engraved copy of Holst's own piano duet arrangement was found by John York.<ref>Notes from Amazon, webpage: [https://www.amazon.ca/dp/B000058UUS amazon.ca/Planets-World-Premiere].</ref>\n*Two pianos (duo) \u2013 Holst had originally sketched the work for two pianos, due to a need to compensate for the [[neuritis]] in his right arm. His two friends, Nora Day and Vally Lasker, had agreed to play the two-piano arrangement for him as he dictated the details of the orchestral score to them. This they wrote down themselves on the two-piano score, and used as a guide when it was time to create the full orchestral score.<ref>Notes to ''The Planets, Arranged for Two Pianos by the Composer'', J. Curwen & Sons, London.</ref> The two-piano arrangement was published in 1949. Holst's original manuscripts for it are now in the holdings of the Royal College of Music (Mars, Venus, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune), Royal Academy of Music (Mercury) and British Library (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus).<ref>''Holst: Music for Two Pianos'', Naxos catalogue no. 8.554369, [http://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.554369&catNum=554369&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English# ''About This Recording'']</ref>\n*[[Pianola]] \u2013 In the early 1990s an arrangement was made for piano rolls by the English pianolist, Rex Lawson, and published on the Perforetur label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pianola.org/history/history_repertoire.cfm |title=History of the Pianola \u2013 Pianola Repertoire |accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Organ (music)|Organ]] \u2013 American harpsichordist and organist Peter Sykes transcribed ''The Planets'' for organ.<ref>Peter Sykes. \" [http://www.hbdirect.com/album_detail.php?pid=225139 Holst: The Planets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929024606/http://www.hbdirect.com/album_detail.php?pid=225139 |date=29 September 2011 }}.\" HB Direct, Released 1996.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petersykes.com/index1.html |title=Peter Sykes |publisher=Peter Sykes |accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Chamber Orchestra|Ensemble or Chamber Orchestra]] \u2013 English orchestrator George Morton transcribed ''The Planets'' for 15-piece ensemble or chamber orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universaledition.com/The-Planets-Gustav-Holst/composers-and-works/composer/4605/work/15860 |title=Universal Edition |publisher=Universal Edition |accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://georgeconducts.weebly.com/arranging.html |title=George Morton, arranging |publisher=George Morton |accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Synthesizer (music)|Moog]] \u2013 [[Isao Tomita]] adapted ''The Planets'' for a Moog and other synthesizers and electronic devices.<ref>Isao Tomita. \" [http://www.isaotomita.net/recordings/planets.html Tomita's Planets].\" HB Direct, Released 1976</ref> The original LP release prompted legal action from Holst's estate. The composer's daughter, Imogen Holst, worked hard to prevent the recording being distributed in the UK.<ref>Grogan, Christopher. ''Imogen Holst: A Life in Music''. Boydell Press (2010), p. 422</ref> [[Patrick Gleeson]] also recorded an electronic version in 1976 called ''Beyond the Sun''. \n*[[Brass band (British style)|Brass band]] \u2013 Stephen Roberts, associate conductor of the English Symphony Orchestra, transcribed the entire suite for brass band.<ref>[http://www.4barsrest.com/classifieds/cards_detail.asp?id=188 ''Stephen Roberts''] at 4barsrest.com</ref>\n*[[Marching band]] \u2013 the movements Mars, Venus and Jupiter have all been arranged for marching band by [[Jay Bocook]].<ref>[http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/1998/md.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415164416/http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/1998/md.htm |date=15 April 2009 }}</ref> Paul Murtha also arranged the chorale section of Jupiter for marching band.,<ref>[http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/2002/grade2.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725032656/http://www.southernmusic.com/marching_band/2002/grade2.htm |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref> Kevin Shah and Tony Nunez created a work on Jupiter entitled \"Bringer of Joy\" as well [http://www.projectrisemusic.com/index.php/marching-band/184 Project Rise Music \u00bb Marching Band]\n*[[Concert band]] \u2013 there are numerous transcriptions of the whole Suite for concert band.\n*[[Percussion ensemble]] \u2013 James Ancona arranged ''Mercury'' for a percussion ensemble. It consisted of 2 [[glockenspiel]]s, 2 [[xylophone]]s, 2 [[vibraphone]]s, 2 [[marimba]]s, 5 [[timpani]], a small suspended [[cymbal]], and 2 [[Triangle (musical instrument)|triangles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tapspace.com/Mercury-from-The-Planets-pr-51.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731221534/http://www.tapspace.com/Mercury-from-The-Planets-pr-51.html|url-status=dead|title=Tapspace :: Solo & Ensemble :: Mercury (from \"The Planets\")|archivedate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Drum and bugle corps (modern)|Drum corps]] \u2013 selections from ''The Planets'' were performed by [[The Cavaliers Drum and Bugle Corps|The Cavaliers]] as part of their 1985 repertoire, and as the entirety of their 1995 feature field show, as well as appearing in their 2017 production \"Men Are From Mars\".<ref>[http://www.corpsreps.com/corpsreps.cfm?view=corpsdet&corps=9&corpstype=Junior, \"Song History for The Cavaliers\"], Retrieved 31 March 2013</ref> A similar performance was recorded for CD by [[Star of Indiana]] as part of their ''Brass Theater'' series.\n* [[Rock music|Rock]] bands:\n:*[[King Crimson]] performed a rock arrangement of \"Mars\" at their live shows in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2006/11/king-crimson-mars2.html|title=King Crimson \u2013 Mars|work=Paste Magazine}}</ref> The band intended to make a studio recording of \"Mars\" for their second album, ''[[In the Wake of Poseidon]]'', in 1970.  However, this plan was met with resistance from Holst's estate, and the band instead composed a new piece of similar structure, \"The Devil's Triangle,\" for the album.\n:*[[Emerson, Lake & Powell]], whose bassist [[Greg Lake]] had been a member of King Crimson during 1969\u201370, recorded a version of \"Mars\" for [[Emerson, Lake & Powell (album)|their eponymous studio album]] in 1986.\n:*[[Death metal]] band [[Aeon]] recorded a version of \"Neptune, the Mystic\" for their album ''[[Aeons Black]]''. Though much shorter than the original it was derived from a select few of the main melodies <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalblade.com/us/releases/aeon-aeons-black/|title=Aeon \"Aeons Black\"|work=Metal Blade Records}}</ref>\n:*British Metal bands: the introduction to Diamond Head's \"[[Am I Evil?]]\", as well as the main riff from \"[[Black Sabbath (song)|Black Sabbath]]\" and the bridge from \"[[Children of the Grave]]\" by [[Black Sabbath]], are loosely based on \"Mars.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diamond-head.net/article1.JPG |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825015447/http://www.diamond-head.net/article1.JPG |archivedate=25 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00vlq0y/Classic_Albums_Black_Sabbath_Paranoid/ |title=BBC Two \u2013 Classic Albums, Black Sabbath: Paranoid |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=26 October 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref> On their 1990 tour promoting the album ''[[Tyr (album)|Tyr]]'' parts of \"Mars\" are used as playback during [[Cozy Powell]]'s drum solo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=shFNwPet7v0|title=Black Sabbath Dies Irae [Full Bootleg \u2013 Live in Italy \u2013 1990]|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvgfk9zjGXc|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] used parts of \"Jupiter\" as a taped intro to their gigs in the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rc0wBwkSC6I|title=Saxon \u2013 10 Years Of Denim And Leather 1989 Full Concert|first=|last=Malfarius|date=3 March 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n* Japanese singer [[Ayaka Hirahara]] released a pop version of \"Jupiter\" in December 2003. It went to No. 2 on the [[Oricon]] charts and sold nearly a million copies, making it the third-best-selling single in the [[J-pop|Japanese popular music]] market for 2004. It remained on the charts for over three years.<ref>[http://www.last.fm/music/%E5%B9%B3%E5%8E%9F%E7%B6%BE%E9%A6%99 \u5e73\u539f\u7dbe\u9999 (''Hirahara Ayaka'')] at last.fm {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n\n=== Hymns ===\n{{main|Thaxted (tune)}}\n\nHolst adapted the melody of the central section of ''Jupiter'' in 1921 to fit the metre of a poem beginning \"[[I Vow to Thee, My Country]]\". As a [[hymn tune]] it has the title ''[[Thaxted (tune)|Thaxted]]'', after the [[Thaxted|town in Essex]] where Holst lived for many years, and it has also been used for other hymns, such as \"O God beyond all praising\"<ref>{{cite web|title=O God Beyond All Praising|work=Oremus|url=http://www.oremus.org/hymnal/o/o153.html|accessdate=1 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416033808/http://www.oremus.org/hymnal/o/o153.html|archivedate=16 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and \"We Praise You and Acknowledge You\" with lyrics by Rev. Stephen P. Starke.<ref>{{cite web|title=We Praise You and Acknowledge You, O God|work=Hymnary.org|url=https://hymnary.org/text/we_praise_you_and_acknowledge_you_o_god|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> \n\n\"I Vow to Thee, My Country\" was written between 1908 and 1918 by Sir [[Cecil Spring Rice]] and became known as a response to the human cost of World War I. The hymn was first performed in 1925 and quickly became a patriotic anthem. Although Holst had no such patriotic intentions when he originally composed the music, these adaptations have encouraged others{{Who|date=March 2010}} to draw upon the score in similar ways throughout the 20th century.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nThe melody was also adapted and set to lyrics by [[Charlie Skarbek]] and titled \"[[World in Union]]\".<ref name=\"Raynor\">{{cite news |last1=Rayner |first1=Gordon |title=Rugby World Cup: fans petition ITV to replace 'truly awful' Paloma Faith theme music |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/rugby-world-cup/11888395/Rugby-World-Cup-fans-petition-ITV-to-replace-truly-awful-Paloma-Faith-theme-music.html |accessdate=March 28, 2017 |work=The Telegraph|date=September 24, 2015 |language=en}}</ref> The song is used as the theme song for the [[Rugby World Cup]] and appears in most television coverage and before matches.<ref name=\"Raynor\"/>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* [[Bell's Brewery]] claims that the suite served as an inspiration for its ''The Planets Series'' of beers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gabler |first1=Jay |title=Holst and hops: Bells Brewery releasing beers inspired by \"The Planets\" |url=https://www.classicalmpr.org/blog/classical-notes/2014/07/08/holst_and_hops |website=Classical MPR |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=Jul 8, 2014}}</ref>  \n* [[Robert A. Heinlein]] references ''Mars'' in his novel, [[Stranger in a Strange Land]], used to establish Valentine Michael Smith's credentials when meeting the president.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Heinlein |first1=Robert |title=Stranger in a Strange Land |date=1961 |publisher=G. P. Putnam's Sons |isbn=978-0-441-79034-0 |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/334327/stranger-in-a-strange-land-by-robert-a-heinlein/}}</ref> \n* [[Bill Conti]] was strongly influenced by ''Neptune'' and ''Jupiter'' in his soundtrack for the 1983 film [[The Right Stuff (film)|The Right Stuff]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lochner |first1=Jim |title=CD Review: The Right Stuff |url=https://filmscoreclicktrack.com/cd-review-the-right-stuff/ |website=filmscoreclicktrack.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[King Crimson]]'s song \"The Devil\u2019s Triangle\" from [[In the Wake of Poseidon]] was adapted from ''Mars''.<ref name=\"devils_triangle\">{{cite book|last1=Martin|first1=Bill|title=Listening to the Future: The Time of Progressive Rock, 1968-1978|date=December 1, 1998|publisher=Carus Publishing|location=Chicago and La Salle, Illinois|isbn=9780812693683|page=186}}</ref> \n* [[Doctor Who]] features a brief excerpt from \"The Devil\u2019s Triangle\" in [[The Mind of Evil]].<ref name=\"devils_triangle\"/>\n* [[The Man Who Fell to Earth]] features excerpts of ''Venus'' and ''Mars''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gent |first1=James |title=\u2018The Man Who Fell To Earth: Original Soundtrack\u2019 |url=http://wearecult.rocks/the-man-who-fell-to-earth-original-soundtrack |website=We Are Cult |date=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Jazz fusion band Safety Squad used the famous rhythm from ''Mars'' in their song \"Mr. Mungo's Revenge\"<ref>Safety Squad [https://safetysquad.bandcamp.com/track/mr-mungos-revenge \"Mr Mungo's Revenge\"] (Apr 6, 2018).</ref>  \n* [[The Simpsons]] episode [['Scuse Me While I Miss the Sky]] features extracts of the beginning of ''Jupiter'' due to astronomy being the main subject of the episode.<ref name=\"Simpsons\">{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=James |title=This Flash Mob of Holst's 'Jupiter' Will Bring You Jollity |url=https://www.wqxr.org/story/flash-mob-holst-jupiter-bring-jollity/ |website=wqxr.org |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n* [[The Simpsons]] episode [[The Regina Monologues]] features an extract from ''Mars'' in a flashback scene to World War 2.<ref name=\"Simpsons\"/>\n* [[Mr. Robot]] features ''Neptune'' in the pre-credits sequence of Season 2, Episode 4.<ref name=\"Mr. Robot Soundtrack: S2 \u00b7 E4 \u00b7 eps2.2_init1.asec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/mr-robot/season-2/33420|accessdate=2018-11-22|title=Mr. Robot Soundtrack: S2 \u00b7 E4 \u00b7 eps2.2_init1.asec|publisher=tunefind.com}}</ref>\n* [[John Williams]] used the melodies and instrumentation of ''Mars'' as the inspiration for his soundtrack for the [[Star Wars]] films (specifically \"[[The Imperial March]]\")<ref>Shobe, Michael. and Kim Nowack. [http://www.wqxr.org/story/throwback-thursday-classical-music-influences-inside-john-williams-star-wars-score/ \"The Classical Music Influences Inside John Williams' 'Star Wars' Score,\"] WQXR (Dec 17, 2015).</ref>\n* [[Hans Zimmer]] closely used the melodies, instrumentation and orchestration of ''Mars'' as the inspiration for his soundtrack for the movie [[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]] to the extent that a lawsuit for [[copyright infringement]] was filed by the Holst foundation <ref>Carlsson, Mikael. [http://www.filmmusicmag.com/?p=638 \"Zimmer sued over 'Gladiator' music\"] (Jun 12, 2006).</ref>\n\n==Other Use==\n*[[East Japan Railway Company|JR East]] in [[Japan]] uses several part from \"Jupiter, the Bringer of Jollity\" as [[Train melody|departure Melody]] for some stations in the Greater [[Kant\u014d region]].\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Musica universalis]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist| group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|last=Boult|first=Adrian|title=My Own Trumpet|location=London|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|date=1973|isbn=0-241-02445-5 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Greene|first=Richard|title=Holst: The Planets|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|date=1995|isbn=0-521-45633-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Head|first=Raymond|title=Gustav Holst: The Planets Suite - New Light on a Famous Work|publisher=Sky Dance Press|date=2014|isbn=978-0-9928464-0-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|title=Adrian Boult|url=https://archive.org/details/adrianboult00kenn|url-access=registration|location=London|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|